<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Clark-Hope     09-10 0202</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Clark-Hope,0209</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bob Hope Host of Fund-Raiser for Roy Clark's Trip to USSR</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bob Hope wants to send country singer
Roy Clark ``to Russia with love,'' and played host of a
fund-raising dinner in pursuit of that goal.
   At Friday's dinner, Clark said he was eager to return to the
Soviet Union on his second goodwill tour.
   ``I guess I was the first person to introduce country music to
the Russians, and they loved it,'' Clark said. ``I, in turn, loved
them. They're just people, not so different from us.''
   Clark said work songs like ``Sixteen Tons'' were the
most-requested tunes when he first toured the Soviet Union in 1976.
   Clark, who stars on the television show ``Hee Haw,'' will give
12 concerts in Moscow and Leningrad on this tour, which is
partially funded by the U.S. Information Agency and the official
Soviet talent agency Gosconcert.
   Tennessee Sens. Albert Gore Jr. and Jim Sasser joined Hee Haw
co-star George Lindsey at the fund-raiser, which included some
light jabs at Clark by Hope.
   ``I send him to Russia, with love,'' Hope said. ``It's either
send him, or deport him. Who else would want him, except maybe his
wife?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
