<FILEID>AP-NR-09-10-88 2343EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-TropicalWeather 1stLd-Writethru a0621 09-10 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tropical Weather, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0621,0290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tropical Storm Gilbert Becomes Hurricane In Caribbean</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE WITH Gilbert upgraded to
hurricane. Picks up 7th graf pvs `Two weeks...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tropical Storm Gilbert strengthened into a
hurricane Saturday night in the Caribbean, boasting maximum
sustained winds of nearly 75 mph, forecasters said.
   Gilbert was expected drop 5 to 10 inches of rain on Puerto Rico
and the Dominican Republic by Sunday, the National Hurricane Center
said.
   At 10:30 p.m. EDT Saturday, Gilbert was centered 225 miles
southeast of Santo Domingo, Dominican Republic. It was near
latitude 16.0 north, longitude 67.3 west.
   Forecasters expected the storm to continue to strengthen.
   ``The system is becoming better organized,'' said Lixion Avila,
hurricane center meteorologist. ``The convection is becoming
concentrated in the center.''
   The storm was expected to continue moving west at near 15 mph
for the next 24 hours.
   The government of the Dominican Republic issued a hurricane
warning for the Barahona peninsula.
   Two weeks ago, a depression that later became Tropical Storm
Chris dumped 6.6 inches of rain on Puerto Rico, causing mudslides
and flooding blamed for three deaths and damage to more than 100
homes.
   Chris came ashore Aug. 28 at Charleston, S.C., destroying more
than a dozen mobile homes, killing one person, and leaving
thousands temporarily without power before losing steam over land.
   Meanwhile, the remnants of hurricane Florence moved into
Mississippi on Saturday while thousands of evacuated Louisiana
residents returned to their homes. Most found little damage from
the storm's 80 mph wind.
   Officials blamed Florence for one death.
   The 1988 Atlantic hurricane season has had eight named storms,
two of which strengthened into short-lived hurricanes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
