<DOCNO> AP880910-0007 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-10-88 0116EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-PostalCutbacks Bjt   09-10 0504</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Postal Cutbacks, Bjt,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Postal Window Service Restored</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Postal Service today is restoring the
window services it cut last February in a move that saved $40
million and helped cushion an expected $500 million deficit this
year for the U.S. mail system.
   Hours at post offices won't necessarily be the same as before
the cuts were imposed, however, with local managers allowed to make
changes that they think best serve their customers.
   Ordered by Congress to cut out $160 million in spending, the
Postal Service made a series of changes, including reducing window
hours at most offices by a half-day per week.
   The reduction in hours drew heavy criticism, coming just two
months before postage rates were increased.
   Postmaster General Anthony Frank has struggled to explain that
the two events were not related.
   The rate increase was in response to a rising deficit, and had
been in the works for more than a year. The service cuts were
necessitated when Congress unexpectedly ordered the spending
reduction. It was part of an effort to reduce the overall federal
budget, even though the post office no longer receives a taxpayer
subsidy.
   In restoring the window hours, local managers were given the
option to adjust hours to suit the needs of their communities.
   For example, Saturday hours will not be restored in heavily
Jewish sections of New York City, where little business was done on
that day anyway because of the sabbath. Instead, managers will
experiment with staying open later some days or perhaps having some
Sunday office hours.
   In other areas, instead of extending hours overall, managers
will add more clerks to handle business during peak times.
   While the hours of window clerk service are returning, other
money-saving cuts imposed in February remain in effect, including
curtailment of Sunday mail collection and sorting and a moratorium
on construction of new post offices.
   Congress, meanwhile, is considering bills to remove the Postal
Service from the federal budget as a way to avoid similar service
reductions in the future. The window closings saved about $40
million, officials reported.
   Unless action is taken, the Postal Service faces another $270
million in spending cuts in the fiscal year that starts Oct. 1.
   That will not mean that hours will be cut again, however.
   Postal managers say they have found ways to cut spending _
although at the cost of slower service _ by such things as
switching some mail from airplanes to trucks, changing trucking
schedules, reducing management travel and training spending and
cutting research and development.
   The Postal Service expects to finish the current fiscal year at
the end of this month with a deficit of between $500 million and
$550 million.
   Higher postage rates which took effect April 4 are expected to
help boost the agency into the black in fiscal 1989, however.
   The Postal Service has managed to break even over the last
decade, losing money in some years and showing a surplus in others.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
