<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--Malaysia-Opium     09-10 0129</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Malaysia-Opium,0132</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scavenger Sentenced To Death For Opium Possession</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The High Court sentenced a
78-year-old scavenger to death by hanging after convicting him of
possessing 6.4 pounds of opium.
   Teng Soi told the court he had just picked up the bag containing
the opium at a dump when he was arrested Nov. 24, 1984. He said he
did not know what was in the bag.
   Justice K.C. Vohrah, in passing the death sentence, said it was
improbable anyone would throw into the garbage that amount of
cocaine.
   Malaysia in 1975 passed laws providing the death penalty for
drug trafficking. Since then, 184 people have been sentenced to
death and 62 have been executed by hanging. The others are awaiting
appeals or execution dates.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
