<DOCNO> AP880910-0009 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-10-88 0117EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-EltonJohn     09-10 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Elton John,0323</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four-Day Elton John Sale Reaps More Than $8 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Small spenders were out in force for the final day
of an auction of Elton John's belongings, purchasing the rock
star's soap dish, chamber pot and even the posters advertising the
sale.
   The sale, which ended Friday, reaped a total of $8.17 million.
   ``A lot of this stuff was cheap, and small private buyers could
afford it,'' said Fiona James, a spokeswoman for Sotheby's auction
house. ``Lots of them were Elton John fans.''
   The sale started Tuesday and consisted of 1,922 lots, including
Rembrandt etchings, an umbrella with a large ``E'' for the handle,
a replica of Egyptian Pharoah Tutankhamun's throne, and the
singer's stilt-like boots from the 1975 film ``Tommy.''
   Sotheby's had expected the sale to bring in $5 million. Ms.
James said the final two days brought in $2.63 million, but she
could not provide a figure for Friday alone.
   Small and unusual items went on the block Friday, Ms. James
said. Among them were a pair of silver Cartier bowls, one of which
John used as a soap dish in his bathroom. They sold for about
$1,030.
   A chamber pot fetched $270. One American fan paid about $930 for
the plastic banners advertising the sale.
   John's cassette-tape player, in a miniature grand piano, sold
for $1,765 while a penny-operated amusement machine fetched $820.
   Top prices went to statuettes by the French artist Erte. One, of
a woman holding a globe, sold for $14,315, almost five times the
expected price.
   John, 41, has said he wants to make room in his mansion near
Windsor, west of London, to start new collections. Sotheby's said
he kept up with the auction proceedings by telephone from Miami.
   The singer's varied art collection sold for $1.3 million
Thursday. His stage costumes, memorabilia, furniture, ornaments and
jewelry were sold Tuesday and Wednesday.
</TEXT>
