<1ST_LINE>r w PM-MedicaidAbortions     09-10 0643</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Medicaid Abortions,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Effort To Amend Medicaid Abortion Rules Seems Doomed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first attempt to liberalize Medicaid
abortion restrictions in seven years appears doomed to failure in
the wake of a House vote to continue paying for abortions only when
a woman's life is endangered.
   The House voted 216-166 Friday to stand by existing policy
rather than go along with a Senate plan to permit
government-financed abortions for poor victims of rape and incest.
   The abortion controversy arose in connection with a $140 billion
spending bill for the departments of labor, education and health
and human services that also included funds for AIDS and student
financial aid. House and Senate negotiators came to agreement on
every other element of the massive fiscal 1989 appropriations bill,
but were stymied on abortion.
   The House action added to mounting pressure on the Senate to
back off its amendment. President Reagan has said repeatedly he
would veto the entire spending bill if abortion policy is
liberalized.
   The Senate could act on the bill and the abortion question as
early as Monday, Senate Majority Leader Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va.,
indicated Friday.
   ``We are disappointed but not defeated,'' said Kate Michelman,
president of the National Abortion Rights Action League, in a
statement after the House vote. Apparently anticipating a similar
setback in the Senate, she added, ``we shall redouble our efforts
with the new Congress and the new administration and we'll try
again.''
   Under an amendment authored by Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., Medicaid
pays only for abortions needed to save the life of a woman. It had
been seven years since either chamber had voted to liberalize the
policy until the Senate adopted the rape and incest provision on
July 27.
   Specifically, the Senate measure said Medicaid would pay for
abortions in cases of promptly reported rape or incest. States
still would have the option of barring payments for all abortions
except those necessary to save a woman's life.
   Douglas Johnson, legislative director for the National
Right-to-Life Committee, issued a statement saying ``the groups
pushing for these changes really want to restore federal funding of
abortion on demand.''
   Much of the House debate centered on the fundamental morality of
abortion, despite the narrow focus of the amendment.
   ``You can't avoid injustice in a rape situation. You can't avoid
injustice in an incest situation. But why compound the injustice by
putting on top of it exterminating an innocent human life?'' Hyde
said. ``Don't make us a part of that double tragedy. ... Out of
great, great tragedy, some good can come.''
   Lawmakers on the other side argued with equal passion that poor
women victimized by brutal crimes are entitled to a full range of
medical options.
   ``The consequences to individuals are very substantial,'' said
Rep. Steny Hoyer, D-Md. ``This is the appropriate and sensitive and
humane step for us to take.''
   Faye Wattleton, president of the Planned Parenthood Federation
of America, accused the House of treating poor women callously.
``To force a woman to bear her rapist's child because she is poor
is the cruelest insult imaginable,'' Wattleton said in a statement.
   However, some Hyde allies noted that medical procedures are
available to prevent conception after rapes or incest. Others said
the proposed exceptions would create problems for law enforcement
officers confronted with reports of rape.
   ``What we're going to do is make liars out of women so that they
can get an abortion funded by the government,'' contended Rep.
Harold Volkmer, D-Mo.
   Before moving to the abortion debate, the House voted 335-60 to
approve the other portions of the three-agency spending bill. The
measure includes $1.2 billion for AIDS research, treatment,
prevention and education; $4.3 billion in education grants for
disadvantaged students; $5.5 billion in college student financial
assistance, and $3.7 billion for the Job Training Partnership Act.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
