<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DeathRowTV     09-10 0256</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Death Row TV,0261</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Slayer In Hurry To Hit Death Row</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man convicted of murdering his 20-year-old
daughter asked a judge to confirm his death sentence as soon as
possible so he can watch television in his cell, a prison spokesman
says.
   ``Please bring me in and sentence me,'' Gary Starr, 47, of Moon
Township said in a letter filed with Allegheny County Judge Jeffrey
Manning's office Friday. ``I thought the jury already sentenced me
to death.''
   Starr requested the quick action because it will put him in a
section of the State Correctional Institution at Pittsburgh where
televisions are permitted, according to prison spokesman Thomas
Seiverling.
   A jury Aug. 23 sentenced Starr to die for the Feb. 19 stabbing
death of daughter Wanda Starr, also of Moon Township. The murder
occurred after Starr, a former apartment complex manager,
confronted his daughter about stolen rent money.
   During his trial, Starr admitted having a 6-year incestuous
relationship with the woman. Sixteen years ago, he was convicted of
shooting his wife Linda to death as she slept. He served 8{ years
in prison for that crime.
   Starr is housed in an area of the prison where televisions are
prohibited, Seiverling said.
   After Starr is sentenced by Manning, he will be housed in a
restricted area of the prison reserved for inmates facing
execution. Prisoners there are locked in their cells for all but 20
minutes each day, but are allowed to watch television.
   The state Supreme Court automatically will review Starr's death
sentence.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
