<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RollsFlap     09-10 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Rolls Flap,0372</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parking Dispute Causing Some Shakes, Rattles And Rolls</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: First available for Saturday AMs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL FLEEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Only in Beverly Hills could a
$200,000, chauffeur-driven Rolls-Royce be considered an eyesore.
   But that's the problem facing David Spellerberg, who says he has
gotten nothing but complaints _ and threat of prosecution _ for
parking his 1954 black Rolls in front of his art gallery on Rodeo
Drive.
   He says his neighbors aren't just mad about the car, but the
people it attracts: namely thousands of tourists in the last six
months who have posed in front of the sleek black beauty while
their pictures were being taken.
   ``Anyplace else in the world and people would be happy to have a
Rolls-Royce parked in front of their business,'' said Spellerberg.
``But not Beverly Hills.''
   Spellerberg readily admits he leaves the car in the one-hour
metered space as a tourist attraction at the National Heritage
Gallery, which sells seascapes and other traditional-style
paintings and sculptures.
   His chauffeur stands by, reading a book and feeding the meter
with $15 in quarters each day.
   ``After all, wasn't it the public and tourists that made Rodeo
Drive and Beverly Hills famous?'' he asks in a full-page ad taken
out Friday in a local paper. ``This magnificent vintage Rolls-Royce
has allowed thousands to capture a touch of the `glitter and
glamour' that Beverly Hills is famous for.''
   But the city doesn't see it that way. In fact, the city attorney
wrote to Spellerberg's attorney saying that the matter has been
passed to the ``litigation-prosecution department.''
   There was no answer at city hall offices Friday, which was a
state holiday. But in general, parking meter regulations in the
region do not allow motorists to keep their cars indefinitely in
one spot, even if they return periodically to feed the meter.
   Spellerberg, however, says he won't give up. His advertisement
in the Beverly Hills Courier urges people to phone City Hall and
speak up in support of the Rolls.
   ``This is just one of those crazy things your hear about,'' he
said. ``I didn't think it would happen to me.''
</TEXT>
