<1ST_LINE>r w PM-MIAs     09-10 0269</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-MIAs,270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congressman Says Vietnam Leaning Toward Excavations for MIA
Remains</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnamese officials are willing to allow the
excavation of 100 sites to search for the remains of U.S.
servicemen missing since the Vietnam War, says a member of a
congressional delegation who was in Hanoi earlier this month.
   U.S. military officials had been scheduled to begin a round of
meetings on the MIA search Friday in Hanoi, but the talks were
called off after a Vietnamese jetliner crashed minutes before
landing in Bangkok, Thailand, said Lt. Cmdr. Jim Kudla, a Pentagon
spokesman.
   The U.S. military team was to have taken the Friday afternoon
return flight to Hanoi for the technical talks, said Ross Petzing,
spokesman for the embassy in Bangkok.
   Kudla said the talks could begin as early as next week.
   Rep. Albert Bustamante, D-Texas, said Vietnam's foreign minister
assured members of a congressional delegation last week in Hanoi
that ``he would let us go in and excavate'' and will propose during
the scheduled talks that 100 sites be targeted for the search.
   ``He doesn't think there's any live MIAs in Vietnam,''
Bustamante said. ``Whether there are some in Laos or Cambodia, he
doesn't know.''
   There are 2,398 U.S. personnel still unaccounted for in the war,
Bustamante said.
   With the excavations, Bustamante said, ``I feel once and for
all, we can clear in the minds of some of our families what
happened to their loved ones.''
   Bustamante said the foreign minister also told the congressional
delegation that all of the Amerasian children in Vietnam, estimated
between 10,000 and 12,000, would be allowed to leave.
</TEXT>
