<DOCNO> AP880910-0034 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-10-88 0153EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Argentina Bjt   09-10 0596</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Argentina, Bjt,0617</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Union, Police Blame Each Other for Violence; 13th Strike Set for
Monday</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BAI4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police fired rubber bullets and
water cannons to break up an anti-government rally of 20,000 during
a nationwide general strike. Labor leaders called for another work
stoppage Monday.
   The clashes with police, vandalism, burning of cars and looting
of stores resulted in dozens of injuries and arrests during the
walkout Friday protesting spiraling inflation and unemployment.
   The unrest made the General Labor Conferation's 12th general
strike against the nearly 5-year-old government of President Raul
Alfonsin the most disorderly and bloody. Labor leaders and police
blamed each other for the violence.
   ``It's a lie that the incidents began among participants of the
rally,'' said Saul Ubaldini, general-secretary of the labor
confederation.
   Interior Minister Enrique Nosiglia and Federal Police Chief Juan
Pirker said agitators in the crowd started fights, as did members
of rival unions. When police attempted to restore order, they were
attacked, the said.
   ``Under these circumstances, police intervened to prevent
further damage,'' Nosiglia said. The police action was ``necessary,
prudent and correct,'' Pirker said.
   Nosiglia in a brief communique urged the federation to call off
the Monday walkout.
   ``Nothing justifies a new paralysis of the country, which keeps
delaying progress without any benefit to rights and liberties,'' he
said.
   No deaths were reported in the unrest Friday, but several people
had not regained consciousness hours after they were hospitalized.
   About 50 people were treated at Argerich Hospital for tear gas
inhalation, contusions from rocks and sticks, and abrasions from
falling to the ground when struck by compressed water fired by riot
police. Several dozen others went to at least two other hospitals.
   Two policemen were rushed to Churruca Hospital with severe
injuries, and about 20 others were treated for minor injuries.
   Pirker said he did not know the total number of people arrested.
   Inflation has soared 255 percent this year, and 440 percent for
the past 12 months. Unemployment and underemployment at a combined
14 percent are near 14-year highs. Real personal incomes have
declined for three straight years.
   ``Every day there's less work and my family can't live on what I
earn,'' said Daniel Rio, a middle-aged truck driver who attended
the rally. ``That's why I'm here.''
   President Alfonsin five weeks ago implemented his third major
anti-inflation plan since he took office in December 1983. The
austral was devalued, restrictions on some imports were lifted and
voluntary controls placed on wages and prices.
   The goal, in addition to reducing inflation, was to secure new
loans from the International Monetary Fund and commercial banks to
help repay interest _ $4.6 billion this year _ on Argentina's $56
billion foreign debt.
   Unions and the opposition Peronist Party raise the sensitive
issue of national sovereignty in response to Alfonsin's shaping of
national policy to meet demands by foreign banks.
   The 3.5-million member federation has complained bitterly that
prices have risen despite the controls and pressed for higher wages.
   Friday's strike was effective across this South American country
of 30 million. In the capital, Buenos Aires, striking signalmen
shut down commuter trains before dawn, stranding thousands of
people at home and causing huge backups on roads leading downtown.
   After 8 p.m., the hour the strike was scheduled to end, public
transportation resumed and the capital city of 3 million was calm.
   Late Friday, several public transport unions said they would
participate in Monday's strike, indicating that buses and subways
will be out of service as well as commuter trains.
  
</TEXT>
