<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Names     09-10 0828</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Names,0860</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Names In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sylvester Stallone, who played a Vietnam
veteran hero in his ``Rambo'' movies, got the government's ear when
he complained that dying grass at Los Angeles National Cemetery was
a disgrace to the war dead buried there.
   The federal government found money to pay the water bill for
sprinkling at the cemetery, where 77,000 veterans are buried,
following Stallone's complaint, cemetery director Patricia Hagler
said Friday.
   Stallone offered to pay for the sprinkling himself after he
learned the Veterans Administration didn't have the money to pay
the $9,250-a-month water bill and that watering had been halted
until new funds become available Oct. 1, said his publicist, Warren
Cowan.
   ``When I think about the amount of water that runs down the
driveways of Beverly Hills, the hypocrisy of it all becomes too
much,'' Cowan quoted Stallone as saying.
   ``His interest alone in the situation precipitated the cemetery
receiving additional funding from Washington, D.C. The grounds are
now being watered'' Ms. Hagler said.
   Stallone's ``spirit of patriotism is evidence that he shares
this nation's pride for its veterans,'' she added.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jessica Hahn is sorry more people haven't been
exposed to her true self _ one that ``gets lonely'' and ``cares for
people'' _ even though she has been well exposed in a man's
magazine.
   ``People only see the obvious. They see the Jessica Hahn who was
in Playboy, who made money doing that,'' Hahn said.
   ``The media's picture is the side everyone sees. But there is a
side no one sees,'' said the former church secretary-turned-model.
``It is where my heart really is. It is the side that gets lonely.
It is a side that cares for people.''
   Hahn, 29, says she doesn't have a boyfriend or a manager and
that her family isn't really pleased with her.
   Hahn on Friday reached the halfway point of a 30-day tryout as a
radio personality on KOY-FM, Phoenix. The reviews have been mostly
negative.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>FALL RIVER, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A movie based on the Big Dan's
gang-rape case starring Jodie Foster is being opposed by a
Portuguese-American group, which wants to block its release in the
area where the attack occurred.
   The Portuguese-American Business Association sent letters Friday
asking city officials, state legislators and the area's
congressional delegation to ask theater owners to refrain from
showing ``The Accused,'' which is set to open next month.
   ``The people of our region need not suffer the injustice of
implied guilt ... as a result of Hollywood's sensationalism,''
wrote association president John Miranda.
   In ``The Accused,'' Foster plays the victim of a gang rape,
based on an incident in March 1983 in a tavern in nearby New
Bedford in which a 21-year-old woman was raped on a pool table. The
case received national attention.
   All six defendants were of Portugese descent. Their supporters
said they were victims of lingering racial prejudice against
Portuguese.
   The association fears the film will stir old wounds now healed
after four men were convicted of the rape. Two others were
acquitted. The victim moved to Florida, where she died in a traffic
accident.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A music, fireworks and laser-beam extravaganza on
the River Thames, scheduled for later this month by French composer
Jean-Michel Jarre, may fizzle out because of fears of fire and
traffic jams.
   The Newham Borough Council, which runs the Royal Victoria Docks
in east London where the two-hour concert is scheduled Sept. 24,
delayed until Monday a decision on whether to permit the show.
   ``People are thinking it is a heavy-metal rock show and will
generate violence and trouble,'' said Jarre, who attended
Thursday's meeting. ``But it is something else. It is a concert
dealing with architecture. It is an experience.''
   Objections have come from fire brigades and a local factory
worried about the planned fireworks display, and from a local
council and an ambulance authority citing the danger of traffic
congestion.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retired Maj. Ronald Ferguson, father of the
Duchess of York, says he is quitting his job as deputy chairman of
the swank Guards' Polo Club following a difference of opinion with
the group's executive committee.
   ``By mutual agreement I will be leaving next month,'' the
56-year-old ex-Army officer said in a statement Friday night. ``I
am very saddened.''
   Ferguson, the father of Prince Andrew's wife, Sarah, refused to
elaborate. But the Daily Mail said Thursday he was sacked from the
post that pays $47,320 a year after management consultants
criticized him for lacking business acumen.
   The London newspaper said the committee discussed the
consultants' confidential report in Ferguson's presence last week,
then gave him a letter telling him his contract would not be
renewed when it expires Oct. 31.
   His departure does not affect his position as personal polo
manager to Andrew's brother, Prince Charles.
   Ferguson joined the club in 1955 and has been deputy chairman
for more than 12 years.
</TEXT>
