<FILEID>AP-NR-09-10-88 0312EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-GulfTalks     09-10 0328</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf Talks,0337</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Both Sides Intransigent, Break in Talks Appears Near</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY CZUCZKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran and Iraq remained deadlocked at U.N.-mediated
peace talks and a recess appeared near after both sides publicly
accused the other of blocking progress.
   In a statement Friday, Iraq said talks cannot go anywhere unless
the disputed Shatt-al-Arab waterway is cleared and Iraq is allowed
free navigation in it. Shatt-al-Arab is Iraq's only outlet to the
sea and forms the southern boundary of the two nations.
   The statement was in response to comments Thursday by Iran's
foreign minister, Ali Akbar Velayati. Velayati told reporters that
Iran considered the two issues related to the waterway ``extraneous
elements'' that should be raised later in the talks.
   The Iraqi statement dismissed Iran's position as ``fantasy'' and
accused Tehran of wasting time.
   A U.N.-sponsored cease-fire took effect Aug. 20, clearing the
way for talks on a lasting settlement of the nearly 8-year-old
Persian Gulf war.
   Face-to-face meetings were held only on the first two days of
negotiations, and neither foreign minister has met U.N. mediator
Jan Eliasson since last Saturday. Lower-level contacts have
continued.
   Signs increased Friday that talks would be suspended over the
weekend before resuming in New York later this month.
   Diplomatic sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
Eliasson was expected to announce a recess and that the last few
days were spent haggling over a resumption date.
   Among Iran's priorities at the talks are a withdrawal of troops
to internationally recognized boundaries, exchange of war prisoners
and a U.N. investigation to determine who started the war.
   On the border question, the countries are at odds over a 1975
treaty setting the Iran-Iraq boundary down the middle of the
Shatt-al-Arab.
   Iraq has renounced the pact and claimed the entire waterway, but
Iran says it still considers the treaty valid.
   The waterway has been blocked by sunken ships since the start of
the Persian Gulf war in September 1980.
</TEXT>
