<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Olympics-Chun     09-10 0145</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Olympics-Chun,0150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former President Cancels Plans To Attend Ceremonies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Chun Doo-hwan,
accused by opposition forces of corruption, has canceled plans to
attend the opening ceremonies of the Olympic Games in Seoul, aides
said today.
   The aides quoted Chun as saying he did not want to cause trouble
at the Games and would stay away despite government plans to invite
him as an honored guest. The ceremonies are Sept. 17.
   Olympic organizers have invited Chun as one of South Korea's
three living ex-presidents, and government officials have said
Chun's role in bringing the Games to Seoul justified the invitation.
   The invitation triggered a strong opposition backlash. Chun, who
seized power with military backing in 1980, has faced a
parliamentary inquiry for alleged corruption and other wrongdoings
during his administration.
   Chun left office in February after a seven-year term.
