<FILEID>AP-NR-09-10-88 0322EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-SouthAfrica-Sanctions     09-10 0427</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa-Sanctions,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING to fix cycle designator</HEAD>
<HEAD>Democrats Concede They Lack Votes to Pass Sanctions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Democrats are pressing ahead with a
package of economic sanctions against South Africa, but concede
that a united front of Republican opposition will probably keep the
measure from coming to a vote in the full chamber.
   The Senate Foreign Relations Committee will vote next Wednesday
on the bill, which would impose a near-total trade embargo against
white-dominated South Africa and a near-total withdrawal of U.S.
investment in the country.
   Republican members of the panel, accusing Democrats of playing
election-year politics with the issue, refused a chance to offer
amendments to the bill on Friday. They said they prefer the bill as
it stands because it is so extensive that it will not attract
enough votes to cut off a filibuster on the Senate floor.
   ``My guess is that it will be approved by the committee,'' said
Sen. Paul Simon, D-Ill., a principal author of the legislation.
   ``But because the Republicans are apparently united it will not
have the votes to overcome a filibuster _ we won't get cloture _
that's the way it looks right now,'' said Simon.
   ``But even if we do nothing more than pass it out of committee,
it is a signal to South Africa that we want to change the system''
of forced racial separation known as apartheid, he said.
   Sixty votes are required in the 100-member Senate to invoke
cloture and cut off debate on a bill.
   The 1988 Democratic platform brands South Africa a terrorist
state and Democratic presidential nominee Michael Dukakis has
supported sanctions. Republican presidential candidate George Bush
has opposed new sanctions on they ground they would remove any
leverage the United States may have to work for change in South
Africa.
   After a morning-long debate on the sanctions bill, Republican
committee member Sen. Dan Evans of Washington, told reporters:
   ``I think it's clearly, clearly pushed by domestic political
considerations and not be the urgency of the situation in South
Africa. I think the bill as it now sits will not have a single
Republican vote on the committee.''
   A coalition of Democrats and Republicans enacted a milder South
African sanctions bill two years ago over President Reagan's veto.
   Supporters of the present measure contend it is needed because
the earlier and less-sweeping bill has not forced the South African
government to end apartheid and to extend full citizenship rights
to the black majority.
   The House adopted a similar version of the far-reaching Senate
bill on Aug. 11.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
