<HEAD>US Increases Aid to Bangladesh Flood Victims to $150 million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. is raising assistance to Bangladesh
to $150 million to help flood victims in that country.
   Jay Morris, the No. 2 official in the Agency for International
Development, said Friday he was taking a relief flight this weekend
with 2.2 million square feet of plastic for shelters, 10,000
five-gallon water cans, 26 water tanks with a capacity of 3,000
gallons and two water purification units.
   He was to be accompanied by a team which will assess emergency
assistance needs in Bangladesh. Morris said $60 million of U.S.
food grain supplies will also be shipped immediately to Bangladesh
a year ahead of schedule.
   An estimated 73 million people, two-thirds of Bangladesh's
population, have been affected by the flooding.
