<HEAD>Soviets Make Additional Purchase of American Corn</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union's latest purchase of U.S.
corn has brought the total corn sold to the Soviets in the last
nine days to more than 2.6 million metric tons.
   The Agriculture Department announced Friday that the Soviet
Union has added 350,000 tons to the corn it has purchased since
Sept. 1 for delivery in the 1988-89 year.
   Corn prices have been averaging about $2.75 per bushel at the
farm level, according to USDA estimates, meaning that the latest
sale could have a farm value of around $38 million. The 350,000
tons of corn would be about 13.8 million bushels.
