<2ND_LINE>PM-Miss America,0482</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Miss America 1989 To Be Crowned Tonight</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto XACC1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB McHUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After nearly 1{ weeks of preparation
and preliminaries in this seaside resort community, 51 contestants
are ready to find out tonight who will reign as Miss America 1989.
   Miss Utah Sophia Christine Symko played a classical piano
rhapsody and Miss Florida Melissa Aggeles wore a simple, white
``supersuit'' to victory Friday night in the last preliminary round
of the 62nd Miss America Pageant.
   The 10 women who have accumulated the most points in preliminary
swimsuit, talent and evening gown contests and interviews with the
judges compete to succeed Miss America 1988 Kaye Lani Rae Rafko.
The 10 finalists start with a clean slate in tonight's judging.
   Miss Symko, 21, of Salt Lake City, offered selections from
composer Franz Liszt's difficult ``Spanish Rhapsody,'' showing the
piano prowess she developed in 17 years of study.
   She said she was pleased with her playing. ``Of course, it's not
flawless, but I was very happy. I had a lot of fun with this.''
   Miss Symko said she selected the piece because it was both
formal and fun.
   Miss Utah, born in Oxford, England, is a graduate student at the
University of Utah pursuing her masters in physics. She plans to
attend medical school.
   Miss Aggeles, a 5-foot-8, 128-pound brunette who once was
``quite the tomboy'' wore a white competition supersuit, the
now-traditional, custom-designed suit said to hide flaws and
enhance assets.
   She was the second contestant to wear a white supersuit to
victory this week.
   Miss Aggeles, 24, credited her success to a six-month rigorous
training regime. ``All the hard work paid off,'' she said.
   In addition to weight training, Miss Aggeles said she stuck to a
rigid diet that actually caused her to gain 12 pounds. ``I was too
skinny,'' she said.
   Asked if she had done anything unnatural to enhance her figure,
Miss Aggeles laughed and said, ``I'm real.''
   The 24-year-old from St. Petersburg, Fla., graduated in 1987
from Florida State University. She hopes eventually to receive a
masters degree in fine arts from New York University, specializing
in classics and film, and aspires to a career on Broadway and in
film.
   In the meantime, as Miss Florida she hopes to implement a
program to reduce the number of high school dropouts called
``School is Cool.''
   Winners of the preliminary swimsuit competitions earlier this
week were Miss Louisiana Valerie Brosset and Miss Mississippi Carla
Haag, while the preliminary talent winners were Miss Oklahoma Lori
Lee Kelley and Miss Minnesota Gretchen Elizabeth Carlson.
   The top evening gown contestants have been kept secret to
heighten the suspense for the televised finals.
   The preliminary awards carry scholarships: $3,500 in the talent
division and $2,500 in the swimsuit competition.
</TEXT>
