<FILEID>AP-NR-09-10-88 0455EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WearyFirefighter Bjt   09-10 0546</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weary Firefighter, Bjt,0565</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Firefighters Weary, But Have A Job To Do</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KURT J. REPANSHEK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SILVER GATE, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After a month battling fires, Richard
Gearhart would like nothing more than a break. But he doesn't
expect one as the worst fires in Yellowstone National Park's
history burn unabated.
   ``We're real tired, that's for sure,'' Gearhart said Friday
while on the fire line near the tiny community of Silver Gate,
which has been under seige by blazes for a week.
   ``We could still go on, but we've been away a long time,'' he
said. ``We'd like to go home for just a few days, and then they
could bring us back.''
   Gearhart, a member of the Vista Grande Hot Shots from San
Bernadino, Calif., has been on the line 35 days. Normally
firefighters are released for several days after 21 days.
   But these are not normal times.
   More than 800,000 acres in nearby Yellowstone have burned. The
151,000-acre Storm Creek-Hellroaring fire, one of several in and
around the park, persists in threatening Silver Gate and Cooke City
northeast of the park.
   Firefighters see no sign of an improvement, with high winds
forecast over the weekend that are expected to fan the flames.
   ``We are anticipating major fire activity,'' forest service
official Brian Avery said, adding that today ``may be the worst day
since this entire episode began.''
   Today was to have been the day Gearhart got a day off. But then,
so was Friday _ until Friday came.
   ``Now that this is a national emergency, maybe they'll keep us
even longer,'' he said.
   As a ``hot shot'' Gearhart and his fellow crew members are the
first on the lines of the most dangerous sections of fire.
   He works 12-16 hours a day wielding a chain saw with a blade
roughly 4 feet long, and sometimes has to hike 5 miles to reach the
lines.
   The smoke and ash that Gearhart breathes have left their mark on
his sooty face. As he walked along U.S. 212 on Friday, his sagging
shoulders and slow gait showed his weariness.
   But despite the hardships, he wasn't about to call it quits.
   ``We can't pack it in,'' he said. ``We have people that work for
the Forest Service full time, it's their job.
   ``It is our job,'' he added. ``We said we'd do it, you can't
really complain because we knew this could happen.''
   While there has been dispute over whether the thousands of
firefighters are actually fighting the flames or merely managing
their direction, Gearhart said he and his co-workers are doing
their best under poor conditions.
   When the fire's flames get to be 300 feet high, ``the fire can
do whatever it wants,'' he said.
   ``We're up against something that you really can't put out very
easily without weather cooperation,'' he said. ``We're basically
fighting (the fires) the way you have to do it, but it's just not
working out.''
   In his month on the Yellowstone fire lines, Gearhart has gotten
used to the danger of the work but hasn't forgotten who comes first.
   ``It's just trees and brush (burning),'' Gearhart said.
``They'll grow back, we won't. You just have to get out of the way
sometimes and let it do its thing.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880910-0046 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-10-88 0507EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Thailand-Crash     09-10 0472</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Thailand-Crash,0487</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vietnamese Experts Arrive To Help Investigate Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators today examined the
wreckage of a Vietnamese jetliner to try to determine what caused
the plane to crash minutes before its scheduled landing.
Seventy-five people, including some government officials, were
killed.
   One of the pilots of Air Vietnam Flight 831 reported it was
struck by lightning, said Tran Van Viet, third secretary of the
Vietnamese Embassy. The pilot, Khong Din Phuong, was the only one
of the six survivors who was conscious.
   The Soviet-made Tu-134 slammed into a rice field four miles
short of Bangkok's airport Friday and blew up. The crash occurred
during a thunderstorm, three minutes before the jet was scheduled
to land after a flight from Hanoi.
   Vietnamese investigators flew to Thailand to help Thai officials
in the probe.
   Voice and flight recorders were retrieved from the wreckage,
said Maj. Gen. Sopol Savigamin, a regional police commander. The
cockpit recorder contains conversation between the crew and the
airport control tower, and the flight recorder contains flight data.
   The passenger list included 50 Vietnamese, 11 Indians, eight
Poles, three Japanese, three Frenchmen, two Finns, two Swedes, one
Burmese and two others of unknown nationality. That totals 82, but
one person did not board the plane.
   Nguyen Van Quan, a Vietnamese Embassy official, said the dead
included Vietnam's Minister of Public Health, Dang Hoi Huan, and
its ambassador-designate to the Philippines, Nguyen Dhuong Vu, who
was on the way to take up his post.
   Quan said other Vietnamese victims included many lower-ranking
government officials on their way to conferences in Thailand, Japan
and other countries.
   India's ambassador to Vietnam, Arun Patwardhan, 48, was killed
along with seven other officials of India's Hanoi embassy, an
Indian consular officer in Bangkok said.
   The Japanese Embassy in Bangkok said the second secretary of the
Japanese Embassy in Hanoi, Kiyokata Ida, and two Japanese
businessmen were killed.
   Details on other victims were not available.
   Sopol said workers retrieved 75 bodies Friday. A Frenchman, a
Polish woman, the pilot and three other Vietnamese remained in
intensive care at Bhumibol Hospital.
   Hundreds of police, air force workers and volunteers hauled
bodies from a rice paddy, wrapping them in the thin beige-colored
cloth. The last two bodies, those of a man and a woman, were found
lying by lily pads after workers pumped the pond dry.
   Scattered over the area were earrings, a shell necklace, toy
plastic gun, seat cushions, backpacks, passports and more than 10
bags of diplomatic mail for the Australian Embassy in Bangkok.
   The twin-engine Tu-134 is the Vietnamese flag carrier's mainstay
aircraft.
   According to Jane's All The World's Aircraft, Tu-134s seat from
80 to 96 people. Vietnamese officials have said they would like to
switch to Boeings, Airbuses and other newer, Western-made planes
but do not have the money.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880910-0047 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-10-88 0502EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-PoliticalRdp     09-10 0880</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Rdp,890</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Blasts Bush In Texas; GOP Nominee Rips Democratic Rival In
Pa.</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Stands for PM-Dukakis story listed on PMs Digest</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The new political fire and brimstone in Michael Dukakis' blasts
at George Bush left black Baptist ministers shouting in Texas.
Flag-waving thousands thundered when the GOP candidate proclaimed
in Pennsylvania that he's questioning the judgment _ not the
patriotism _ of his Democratic rival.
   ``In just 60 days we can choose a president who will enforce
civil rights laws, not veto them,'' Dukakis told a meeting of the
National Baptist Convention U.S.A., a large, predominantly black
religious group, in Dallas Friday. He also advocated giving Old
Glory another star: Statehood for the District of Columbia.
   Dukakis' talks earlier this week often seemed flat and attracted
generally lukewarm applause. But this time he spoke like a preacher
at a revival and drew one of the best receptions of his campaign.
   Over and over, he told the crowd the election is only 60 days
away. And from the crowd, comprised largely of black ministers,
came loud shouts: ``Just 60 days.''
   Moments earlier, the group heard Jesse Jackson urge them to
``accept my recommendation'' and join him, a former rival for the
Democratic nomination, in backing Dukakis on Election Day. ``He can
be trusted to help keep hope alive,'' said Jackson, who slapped at
Bush and GOP ticketmate Dan Quayle.
   ``Why do I support Michael Dukakis? Why do I ask you to go and
support him with fervor? Because Bush does not care and Quayle does
not understand. Dukakis cares and understands,'' Jackson added.
   Bush, swinging through Illinois and Pennsylvania in search of
their crucial electoral votes, hammered at Dukakis on defense
issues Friday. He accused the Democrat of contradictions and
confusion about the fate of the Strategic Defense Initiative _ Star
Wars _ when Ronald Reagan vacates the White House.
   ``Calling it a fantasy one day, something he won't rule out the
next ... suggests a confusion in my view on the basic facts, a
confusion in terms of what he really believes and where he would
take this country,'' Bush told a group of Republican women in
Rockford, Ill.
   Dukakis suggested Republican attacks on him are similar to
Joseph McCarthy's accusations and other controversial tactics in
earlier eras. ``Just as they did to (President) Franklin Roosevelt
and (House Speaker) Sam Rayburn, they're now attacking my
patriotism,'' Dukakis said.
   ``And just as they did in the 1930s and 1950s, the American
people can smell the garbage,'' he added.
   Bush's audience at a flag-waving rally in York, Pa., roared when
the vice president said: ``I understand that today the liberal
governor of Massachusetts attacked me for questioning the
patriotism, his patriotism. I'm not questioning his patriotism. I'm
questioning his judgment.''
   While Bush returned to Washington for a weekend away from the
campaign trail, Dukakis was back in Boston to study defense issues
before dealing with military and foreign policy matters in speeches
next week.
   Three of the Democrats' chief defense experts in Congress _
Sens. Sam Nunn of Georgia and John Glenn of Ohio, and Rep. Les
Aspin of Wisconsin _ arranged meetings with Dukakis today and
Sunday, said Dayton Duncan, Dukakis' press secretary.
   Top aides, developing plans for a pair of presidential debates,
agreed Friday that the second round between Bush and Dukakis will
be in Los Angeles, said the Democrat's campaign chairman Paul
Brountas.
   Brountas and Bush campaign leader James Baker had decided
earlier to have round one in Winston-Salem, N.C., on Sept. 25, with
the second debate either Oct. 13 or Oct. 14 _ depending on the
American League baseball playoff series. Both debates are expected
to be general in subject matter.
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen of Texas, the Democratic vice presidential
nominee, pounded at the Republicans on labor issues Friday in
California, and also took the 60-day theme.
   Bentsen joined in a Democratic roast of the GOP's opposition to
legislation that requires giving workers 60 days notice of plant
closings or large-scale layoffs. Democrats around the country
passed out pink slips, saying they were putting the Republicans on
notice their days in office are numbered.
   Bentsen told a cheering crowd at a union hall in Bloomington,
Calif.: ``We're here today to give the Republicans a better break
than they give the American worker.''
   ``Sure, we could provide notice the Republican way. We could go
there election eve and change the locks on the door,'' said
Bentsen. ``We could take the vice president's White House mess card
and cancel that. And we could take away Air Force II. But we agree
with the vast majority of the American people who say 60 days'
notice is fair.''
   Quayle, meantime, said Friday he got into law school ``fair and
square'' _ not through an affirmative action program aimed at
helping minorities. ``No rules were broken,'' he added.
   Earlier Friday, The (Cleveland) Plain Dealer reported the
admissions program Quayle went through in 1970 was intended to
offer equal opportunity to members of minority groups, the
economically disadvantaged, and other ``students of different
viewpoints and backgrounds.''
   While Quayle was touring metals plants in Ohio, his Washington
office released financial records Friday showing he and his wife
own assets worth an estimated $1.4 million.
</TEXT>
