<2ND_LINE>PM-Gun Incident,0251</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vietnam Envoy Says May Be A Real Gun, Plus Toy, At Embassy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnam's ambassador turned in a toy gun and said
it was the weapon brandished by a Vietnamese diplomat during a
demonstration, the Foreign Office said.
   A Foreign Office official, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
said Friday that Ambassador Tran Van Hung acknowledged there may
also be a real gun in the embassy.
   The ambassador, who was summoned to the Foreign Office, handed
over the toy gun and was told to check whether there was a real gun
and report back, the official said.
   Telephone calls seeking comment from the embassy were not
answered Friday evening.
   On Thursday, the ambassador agreed to give up the diplomatic
immunity of a third secretary who allegedly waved a gun at
British-based Vietnamese refugees during a protest outside the
embassy on Sunday. The demonstrators took photographs, which were
published in London's Daily Express.
   The Foreign Office has said it takes a very serious view of the
incident and warned the ambassador this week of the ``gravest
consequences'' unless the diplomat's immunity was waived.
   Third Secretary Khang Than Nhan, who is accused of brandishing
the weapon, may now be questioned by police and, if necessary,
charged or expelled.
   Diplomatic missions in Britain not supposed to have weapons, and
the government has taken violations seriously since a gunman firing
from the Libyan Embassy killed a London policewoman during a
protest in April 1984.
</TEXT>
