<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AtkinsArrested     09-10 0283</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Atkins Arrested,0295</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Times: Ex-Chairman of Ashland Oil Secretly Arrested</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ashland Oil Inc.'s former chairman and a
business associate were secretly arrested for transporting stolen
company documents sought by Iran for use in its $500 million
lawsuit against Ashland, The New York Times reported today.
   Orin E. Atkins was arrested in Manhattan in July after U.S.
Customs agents videotaped him telling a business associate to sell
a pair of confidential 1979 Ashland memos to the Iranian government
for $600,000, the newspaper said.
   The associate, Roy Furmark, was also arrested in July, the Times
said.
   The arrests were kept secret as authorities tried to pursue the
Iranians involved in the incident, the newspaper said.
   Unidentified law enforcement officials told the Times that
Atkins pleaded innocent after his arrest and was released.
   Atkins' attorneys, John E. Jenkins Jr. and Martin Pollner,
confirmed their client was arrested for interstate transportation
of stolen property, the newspaper said.
   ``When all the facts are known, Atkins will be totally
exonerated,'' said a statement released by a third Atkins attorney,
John Lang.
   According to papers filed in federal court in Manhattan, two
other people were charged with interstate transportation of stolen
property: ex-Ashland vice president Charles Dugan and attorney
Charles Barnett, whose late father did legal work for Atkins and
Ashland.
   Both pleaded innocent, the Times said.
   The lawsuit stems from oil contracts between Iran and Ashland.
Part of it focused on seven Iranian oil tankers which Ashland
acquired but did not pay for during the oil crunch of 1979.
   The federal probe began after Ashland, concerned over reports of
stolen documents for sale, hired private investigators to check
into the allegations, the Times said.
</TEXT>
