<FILEID>AP-NR-09-10-88 0607EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthKorea     09-10 0398</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Korea,0410</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>Radicals Demonstrating Against Olympics Clash With Police
^By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Radical students yelling ``Oppose
dictatorial Olympics!'' hurled hundreds of firebombs at riot police
today. Student leaders charged the Games were being used to cement
military rule.
   About 2,000 students from several Seoul colleges rallied at the
capital's Yonsei University, denouncing the Olympics, President Roh
Tae-woo's government and the United States for backing the
government.
   ``Down with military dictatorship,'' the students chanted as
they marched around the campus with red, white and blue flags.
   The students, some armed with wooden and iron clubs, then
marched out of the school to confront hundreds of riot police who
were surrounding the campus. Protesters taunted the police and then
attacked.
   Waves of masked students rushed out of the school's gates and
climbed over walls to pelt police with firebombs that exploded in
orange balls of blazing gasoline. The firebombs exploded among the
police, setting fire to troopers' shields and clothing.
   Police, dressed in green combat fatigues and black visored
helmets, did not use tear gas because of government orders not to
use the powerful gas during the Olympics. They also hurled back
fewer rocks than in similar protests in the past.
   Police said they had no reports of arrests or injuries. The
clash lasted about 30 minutes and was confined to the highway in
front of the school.
   Student and dissident leaders speaking at the rally charged the
Roh government with using the Olympics, which begin Sept. 17, to
cement authoritarian rule.
   ``The Olympics are being used to cement the fascist regime,''
said a statement by the protesters. ``The regime is making all out
efforts to weaken the people's power.''
   Speakers charged the United States with conspiring with Roh to
continue military rule. The United States has about 42,000 troops
in South Korea under a mutual defense pact.
   Radical leaders have called for anti-Olympic protests, but the
protests so far have been confined to a few campuses in Seoul and
several other cities. There have been no demonstrations near
Olympic sites.
   The radicals, a small but powerful minority on campuses, have
virtually no public support. Most Koreans are critical of protests
against the Olympics and want nothing to disrupt the Games.
   Roh, a former general who won presidential elections in
December, has introduced broad democratic reforms and dismantled
authoritarian controls.
</TEXT>
