<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Taiwan-China     09-10 0229</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Taiwan-China,0236</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Task Force Proposes Allowing Chinese To Visit Taiwan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A government task force today proposed
easing a 39-year-old travel ban so residents of Communist China can
come to Taiwan to visit sick relatives, officials said.
   The Cabinet task force proposed that mainland Chinese be allowed
to enter Taiwan to visit spouses, parents or children who are
gravely ill or seriously injured, a Government Information Office
statement said. The trips would be restricted to two months.
   Visits to attend funerals of close relatives also would be
allowed, the statement said.
   The proposal will be submitted soon to Premier Yu Kuo-hwa for
approval, it said.
   The task force, headed by Vice Premier Shih Chi-yang, was
established last month to map out Nationalist policies toward China.
   The Chinese Nationalist government and about 2 million
supporters fled to Taiwan in 1949 after losing a civil war to
Communist forces on the Chinese mainland. Many of the people who
fled to this island left close relatives behind.
   Nationalist authorities banned all official contact with the
Communist government in Beijing but last year eased a ban on travel
to the Chinese mainland to allow Taiwan residents to visit
relatives.
   Mainland Chinese who have been members of the Chinese Communist
Party or have taken part in ``any seditious groups'' would still be
banned from entering Taiwan, according to the proposal.
</TEXT>
