<FILEID>AP-NR-09-10-88 0714EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TeenSlaying     09-10 0353</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Teen Slaying,0370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Authorities: Man Tried to Kill Wife Two Years After Slaying
Sister-in-Law</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILLIPS, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man accused of raping and killing his
sister-in-law because ``women flaunt their bodies'' dug the
teen-ager's grave two days before she was slain, and planned a
similar fate for his wife, authorities say.
   ``I'll make you disappear just like Carla (Lenz) disappeared,''
John R. Weber told his wife, Emily, according to a criminal
complaint by Assistant District Attorney Paul L. Barnett.
   Mrs. Weber, who said she was struck 20 times with a shovel, was
in serious condition at a hospital Friday.
   Weber, 24, was charged in Circuit Court in this northern
Wisconsin city Friday with first-degree murder, first-degree sexual
assault, kidnapping, false imprisonment and attempted first-degree
murder. Bond was set at $200,000.
   Weber prepared a grave for his wife and forced her to write
letters explaining her absence, Price County authorities said.
   The skeletal remains of Miss Lenz, a 17-year-old high school
senior who disappeared in November 1986, were found in a grave in
the woods Wednesday.
   Authorities looked for the remains after they happened on a tape
recording describing the death of Miss Lenz, Mrs. Weber's sister,
while investigating a report Weber had beaten his wife.
   Weber planned to use the tape to terrify his wife, according to
a criminal complaint filed by Barnett.
   The recording said the teen-ager died because ``women flaunt
their bodies and think they can get anything they want.''
   Mrs. Weber ``won't be the last,'' it said. ``There will be
others, many others.''
   The complaint said that, as Weber beat his wife, he was
surprised she kept getting up, and told her ``you're going to be a
tough one to kill.''
   The remains found Wednesday in the township of Flambeau were
identified as Miss Lenz's through dental records.
   According to the complaint, Weber provided investigators with a
map to the grave and asked that she be given a Christian burial.
   The cause of the girl's death was not determined, Sheriff Wayne
Wirsing said.
   If convicted, Weber could be sentenced to life in prison plus
100 years, Barnett said.
</TEXT>
