<DOCNO> AP880910-0057 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-10-88 0731EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RedistrictingSuit     09-10 0672</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Redistricting Suit,0695</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hispanic Leaders See Change in New Political Map For L.A. County</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: RETRANSMITTING a0481 to restore logo.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE V. BIGELOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawsuit that seeks to redress alleged
discrimination against Hispanics will represent a fundamental
reordering of political priorities in the nation's most populous
county, Hispanic leaders say.
   The suit, filed this week by the Justice Department in U.S.
District Court, alleges that county officials discriminated against
Hispanics by drawing political boundaries so as to dilute the
influence of Hispanic voters.
   ``It should have happened years ago,'' said Joseph M. Sanchez,
55, president of a thriving grocery business who was the first
Mexican-American to serve on the city's Board of Fire
Commissioners. ``I'm just so excited about it.''
   Sanchez predicted that changing the electoral districts would
lead to higher voter turnout because of the likelihood that
Hispanic candidates will run for the Board of Supervisors.
   Sanchez and others said they expect redistricting will result in
changes in county government services, particularly in health care,
zoning, police protection and social services.
   A similar Justice Department case against the city government in
1985 resulted in redrawn boundaries in which Hispanics comprise a
majority in at least three of the city's 15 council districts.
   Hispanic leaders say far more is at stake in the county
redistricting case.
   For one thing, no Hispanic or any other minority group member
has ever been elected to the county Board of Supervisors.
   Yet the percentage of Hispanics in the county is at least 27
percent, with blacks comprising more than 12 percent and Asians
about 5.8 percent, according to the lawsuit.
   ``Without a doubt, at least in Los Angeles, the County Board of
Supervisors is one of the most powerful elected bodies in
government,'' said City Councilman Richard Alatorre.
   ``Being elected to the Board of Supervisors is like being
elected pope,'' Alatorre said. ``They're the five gods.''
   ``I call them the five kings, and a lot of people call them the
five kings because of their imperial manner,'' said Alan Clayton, a
state civil rights representative for the League of United Latin
American Citizens.
   Such an appraisal is due in large part to the sheer size of
county government. The Board of Supervisors controls a budget of
nearly $9 billion, compared to the city's budget of roughly $3.5
billion.
   The county's population, estimated at 8.5 million, is greater
than that in each of 42 states.
   Roughly translated, that means that each of the five supervisors
has a constituency of 1.6 million to 1.7 million people.
   In comparison, the ideal population set for U.S. Congressional
Districts during the reapportionment of the early 1980s was a mere
526,000.
   And at 2,615 square miles, the county's 5th District seat in
northern Los Angeles County is bigger than the state of Delaware.
   Such huge numbers, Clayton said, means that immense power is
concentrated in the hands of a very few.
   Conversely, Clayton added, mounting a political challenge
against an incumbent supervisor requires tremendous financial
resources.
   Striking a conciliatory tone, Board of Supervisors Chairman
Deane Dana said the suit has left the five-member board with little
choice ``except to redraw our lines.''
   Hispanic community leaders sounded ecstatic about the prospects
of change to be wrought by the voting rights case.
   ``Hispanic groups have experienced a `tough guy' kind of
attitude from the Board of Supervisors when they protested over
clinics that have been closed,'' said City Councilwoman Gloria
Molina.
   The Justice Department's intervention, Ms. Molina said, is
``sending a tremendously positive message to a Hispanic community
that felt they had no place to go in terms of political redress.''
   Ms. Molina, who was elected to represent east Los Angeles in
February 1987, was one of the first politicians to benefit from the
city's redistricting case, and she believes that she has brought
important changes to the council.
   ``Having a Hispanic on the City Council has created kind of an
attitude change,'' Ms. Molina said. ``Before, there were many
issues that were not addressed.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
