<1ST_LINE>r p PM-DelawarePrimary     09-10 0327</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Delaware Primary,0339</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Beard, Woo in Primary Battle for Senate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THERESA HUMPHREY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DOVER, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lt. Gov. S.B. Woo and civic activist Samuel
S. Beard faced off in a Democratic primary today to determine who
will try to unseat Republican U.S. Sen. William B. Roth.
   Voter turnout was critical in today's race, the only statewide
competition in the primary. Volunteers from both camps planned to
canvass door-to-door and by telephone, as well as provide
transportation to the polls.
   A light turnout was expected to favor Beard, who was backed by
unions and party regulars who traditionally go to the polls in
force.
   A heavy turnout was considered good for Woo, whose main support
comes from college students and younger groups.
   Polls opened at 7 a.m. and were to close at 8 p.m.
   ``We're making sure we're real well-organized and getting our
people out,'' Woo's deputy campaign manager, Jack Markell, said
Friday.
   A poll conducted late last month for the Wilmington News-Journal
newspapers gave Woo 45 percent of the vote and Beard 31 percent.
Twenty-four percent of the likely voters polled were undecided.
   Woo, a 51-year-old physics professor at the University of
Delaware, was elected lieutenant governor four years ago in his
first bid for public office.
   A native of Shanghai, China, he became a symbol of success by
Asian-Americans.
   Woo was considered a shoo-in for another term as lieutenant
governor, but instead chose to challenge Roth, who is seeking his
fourth term.
   However, Democrats complained Woo is not loyal to the party and
threw their support behind Beard.
   Beard, 49, is a former staffer of the late Sen. Robert F.
Kennedy, D-N.Y. He owns a non-profit company that helps obtain
grants to attract economic devleopment.
   Woo apparently won the battle for campaign donations.
   By late August, he had raised $407,998, with most of the money
from the Asian-American community. Beard raised $65,008. Roth, who
runs unopposed in the primary, had $734,933.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
