<FILEID>AP-NR-09-10-88 0748EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TemptationBan     09-10 0359</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Temptation Ban,0371</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Blocks Enforcement of First-in-Nation `Temptation' Ban</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL KACZOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 50 people attended the first
showing of the controversial film, ``The Last Temptation of
Christ,'' after a federal judge blocked a first-in-the-nation
county ordinance banning theaters from showing it.
   U.S. District Judge Roger Vinson issued a preliminary injunction
Friday to stop enforcement of the ordinance, saying it was
unconstitutional.
   Vinson added that ``red flags should run up'' whenever
government tries to violate the rights of citizens.
   The ordinance had called for a maximum penalty of up to a $500
fine and 60 days in jail for showing the film.
   About a dozen pickets were at the Plaza III Theaters for the
movie's debut Friday, but there was no violence.
   In their complaint against the ordinance, the movie's director,
Martin Scorsese, and Plitt Theaters Inc. said Escambia County was
the first local government to ban the film outright, although
others have passed resolutions opposing it.
   County commissioners passed the ordinance on a 4-1 vote Thursday
on the advice of County Attorney William Buztrey, after Christian
fundamentalists and a group called Citizens Against Pornography
asked for the ban.
   Opponents objected to the film's humanizing of Christ,
particularly a scene in which he has a sexual fantasy involving
Mary Magdalene.
   Buztrey argued against the injunction, contending the film was
pornographic and patently offensive to the majority of citizens in
the county.
   ``It may be acceptable in Los Angeles, New York or Tampa, but it
isn't acceptable in Escambia County,'' he said.
   But Vinson listened to a tape recording of the emergency meeting
and said he heard no arguments concerning either obscenity or
violence.
   The only argument made by commissioners or citizens who spoke at
the meeting was that the film was sacreligious.
   Gregg Thomas, a lawyer representing the director and theater
company, cited rulings by the U.S. Supreme Court that it is not the
business of government to suppress real or imagined attacks on a
particular religion.
   Vinson agreed the case was virtually identical to ones in which
the high court has disallowed prior restraint of free speech or
expression.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
