<FILEID>AP-NR-09-10-88 0842EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Nicaragua     09-10 0356</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua,0368</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ortega Proposes New Talks With Rebels</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega said his
government is willing to meet in Guatemala with Contra rebels to
discuss resuming high-level peace talks aimed at ending the civil
war.
   Ortega said Friday that Deputy Foreign Minister Victor Hugo
Tinoco would go to Guatemala ``to discuss with a Contra delegation
a next meeting in Managua and to hear their concerns (and) fears
are about coming to Managua.''
   The president said in a speech that the preliminary talks should
take place Sept. 19-20 in Guatemala City.
   ``I would like to have the cable in my hand before I reply. I
came from Washington yesterday, this is the first news I have,''
Nicaraguan Resistance director Alfredo Cesar said from his home in
Miami today.
   A cease-fire in the 7-year-old civil war between the U.S.-backed
rebels and the leftist Sandinistas began March 21. But high-level
negotiations in Managua on a permanent truce broke down on June 9.
   Contra leaders claimed the Sandinistas restricted their freedom
of movement in Managua and said future talks must be held in
another Central American country.
   The government has extended the cease-fire on a monthly basis,
most recently to Sept. 30. The rebels say they will abide by the
truce indefinitely, but each side has accused the other of
violations.
   Ortega said he suggested the preliminary talks in conversations
with Guatemalan President Vinicio Cerezo.
   Ortega also said conditions existed for a new summit of Central
American presidents in El Salvador to evaluate progress in
implementing a regional peace plan signed by the leaders in August
1987. The leaders of Nicaragua, Guatemala, Costa Rica, Honduras and
El Salvador last met in January.
   The presidents would ``make decisions on the next steps that can
be taken to strengthen this process,'' Ortega said, adding that he
spoke by telephone with Cerezo and Costa Rican President Oscar
Arias about such a summit meeting.
   The peace plan calls for democracy in the five countries,
negotiated solutions to civil conflicts and political amnesties.
   Arias won the 1987 Nobel Peace Prize for authoring the plan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
