<DOCNO> AP880910-0067 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-10-88 0917EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Space     09-10 0183</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Space,0188</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cargo Ship Launched for Mir Orbiting Space Complex</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An unmanned Soviet supply ship bound for the
orbiting Mir space station was launched today, the Tass news agency
said.
   The brief dispatch said the spaceship Progress-38 was launched
at 3:34 a.m. carrying ``expendable materials and various loads to
the Mir piloted complex.'' Tass gave no other details of the
spacecraft's contents.
   The complex is manned by cosmonauts Vladimir Titov and Musa
Manarov, who are trying to break a 326-day endurance record set in
December by Yuri Romanenko. Cosmonauts aboard the Mir have received
cargo deliveries of food, fuel and mail every few months.
   Tass did not say when the spacecraft was expected to dock with
the orbiting laboratory.
   Earlier this week, equipment problems and human error delayed by
one day the return of two cosmonauts who had spent a few days at
the Mir station.
   On Friday Roald Z. Sagdeyev, head of the Soviet space program,
revealed that one of two exploratory probes bound for Mars was
rendered useless after a ground controller sent it an incorrect
message.
</TEXT>
