<1ST_LINE>r i PM-India-Insurgency     09-10 0202</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Insurgency,0208</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tribal Insurgents Surrender Arms In India</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Insurgents belonging to an outlawed
tribal group in the eastern state of Tripura surrendered arms today
after reaching a peace agreement with the government, the United
News of India reported.
   An unknown number of Tribal National Volunteers, the insurgent
group, gave the weapons to army officers at a village near the
India-Bangladesh border.
   The surrender follows a negotiated settlement Aug. 12 by the
Tripura state governement and the federal government with the
insurgents. The rebel group has been fighting for a separate state
for the past decade and has been blamed for the killing of at least
600 non-tribal settlers in the region.
   The problem started in 1951 with the steady influx of settlers
from Bangladesh and other parts of India into Tripura.
   The economic and social patterns in the state began shifting.
Soon the tribals who had originally settled the area were
outnumbered.
   In the 1970s, tribal unrest gave rise to the Tribal National
Volunteers, which declared ``independent Tripura'' as its objective
and took up arms.
   Under the August agreement, the insurgents agreed to give up
arms in exchange for 20 seats in the new state legislature.
</TEXT>
