<FILEID>AP-NR-09-10-88 1005EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel-Bernadotte     09-10 0581</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Bernadotte,0595</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two `Stern Group' Members Admit They Helped Kill Bernadotte</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two former members of a militant Jewish group
which was led by the now-Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir admitted
they helped kill a Swedish U.N. envoy to Palestine 40 years ago, an
Israeli journalist said today.
   It was the first time that members of the underground group,
Lohamei Herut Yisrael (Israel Freedom Fighters), also widely known
as the ``Stern Group,'' confessed to the 1948 killing of Count
Folke Bernadotte, said Dan Margalit of Israel's state-run
Educational Television.
   Margalit told The Associated Press his information was based on
interviews he conducted with Yehoshua Zetler and Meshulam Makover,
two of Bernadotte's killers. One of the interviews was shown Friday
on Educational TV.
   The radical Lohamei Herut Yisrael group, headed by Avraham
Stern, was a splinter faction of the more mainstream group Irgun
Zvai Leumi (The National Military Organization). The faction
advocated guerrilla rebellion against British rule in mandate
Palestine.
   In 1942, Stern was shot and killed by the British police, and
Lohamei Herut Yisrael devised a three-man leadership of Shamir,
Yisrael Scheib-Eldad and Natan Yellin-Mor, with Eldad serving as
the group's ideologist.
   Margalit quoted Zetler as saying he decided to kill Bernadotte,
President of the Swedish Red Cross during and after the World War
II, after the envoy raised far-reaching Palestine partition ideas.
   Bernadotte was appointed in May 1948 to negotiate a cease-fire
and recommend a settlement in Israel's 1948 War of Independence.
   ``Zetler said he conferred with Eldad, and the two traveled to
Haifa to discuss it with Yellin-Mor. Yellin-Mor demanded that after
the killing, the Lohamei Herut Yisrael deny its role and blame the
slaying on a tiny group of zealots called The Homeland Front,''
Margalit said.
   Zetler returned to Jerusalem and selected three men to join him
and Makover on the mission: the late Yehoshua Cohen, Ben Moshe and
another man, ``who is still alive but refuses to disclose his
identity,'' Margalit said. ``They call him (the fifth man) the
Gingi, or the red-haired one,'' Margalit said.
   Margalit quoted Makover as saying the guerrillas arrived in two
cars to the spot selected by Zetler for the Sept. 17, 1948, killing
in downtown Jerusalem. Zetler was driving a De Soto car and the
four others were in a jeep, dressed in khaki shorts and peaked caps
of the Jewish army.
   ``There was also an Australian journalist who told the group
when Bernadotte's convoy was due to pass,'' Margalit said without
elaboration.
   He quoted Makover as saying that when Bernadotte's three-car
convoy approached the narrow street, the jeep blocked its way and
three guerrillas jumped outside, with Makover staying behind the
wheel.
   ``They were supposed to find Bernadotte's vehicle. Each one
looked inside a car, and in the last vehicle, Cohen saw the
envoy,'' Margalit quoted Makover as saying. ``Cohen thrust the
muzzle of his machine-gun inside, fired and wounded a French U.N.
officer.''
   ``He then backed up two steps, took a careful aim, fired into
the car and killed Bernadotte.''
   Makover told Margalit he ordered the two other guerrillas,
``Gingi'' and Moshe, to fire at the tires of the remaining cars.
When it was done, ``they jumped into the jeep and escaped,''
Margalit quoted Makover as saying.
   The killing was widely blamed on the Lohamei Herut Yisrael
group, and the Israeli government launched a nation-wide hunt for
its members, arresting 400 people, among them Yellin-Mor. But the
killers were never found.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
