<FILEID>AP-NR-09-10-88 1044EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BrutalitySettlement     09-10 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brutality Settlement,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>City Proposes $3.5 Million Settlement For Motorist Beaten By
Police</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A motorist who suffered severe brain damage when
he was beaten and thrown down a flight of stairs by two Chicago
police officers will get $3.5 million from the city under a
tentative settlement, officials said.
   The settlement would be the largest in a police case in the
city's history, said Deputy Corporation Counsel Matthew Piers.
Piers testified Friday before a City Council committee, which
unanimously urged the full council to approve the settlement.
   The ``spectacularly severe injuries'' suffered by the victim,
Rafael Acosta, 43, in the May 1981 incident prompted city lawyers
to reach the settlement with Acosta's lawyers, Piers told the
committee.
   ``This is the most egregious case of police brutality I have
ever heard of,'' said Alderman Edward Burke, a former officer.
``Give these poor folks the money they are certainly entitled to.
This is outrageous.''
   The incident began when the two officers saw Acosta, a former
hotel waiter, make an illegal turn in traffic, officials said.
   The officers, Julio Lucotti and Steven Chirello, followed the
victim to his West Side apartment building and beat him severely
before throwing him down a 17-step flight of stairs, Piers told the
committee.
   Among the witnesses to the attack were Acosta's wife and two of
his children.
   The officers, who were never disciplined and are still on duty,
said Acosta fought with them and then fell down the staircase while
handcuffed.
   Acosta suffered permanent brain damage and has been at Elgin
State Hospital, a mental institution, for the past five years.
Piers said Acosta has undergone drastic personality changes
evidenced by a suicide attempt, physical and sexual assaults on
strangers, and frequent violent outbursts at the hospital.
   The Police Department's Office of Professional Standards made no
finding of excessive use of force by the officers and Cook County
State's Attorney Richard Daley declined to prosecute, Piers said.
   ``OPS is like a big washing machine,'' Alderman Anna Langford
said. ``Everything goes in dirty and comes out clean. We had better
take this settlement and run.''
</TEXT>
