<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LottoFraud     09-10 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lotto Fraud,0288</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Janitor Arrested On Charges Of Fraudulent Lotto Claims</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A janitor who convinced thousands he
had won the nation's largest Lotto jackpot has been arrested and
charged with two felony fraud counts, the Florida Lottery
Department said.
   Lottery security agents arrested Charles Hill at his home in
Bristol on Friday and booked him into the Leon County Jail in
Tallahassee.
   Hill, a father of five who earns $14,000 a year as a janitor at
Bristol Elementary School, claimed to have the winning ticket in
the Sept. 3 Lotto drawing that was worth $55.1 million.
   Liberty County sheriff's deputies were sent to guard Hill's home
Monday after he made his claim.
   Liberty County Sheriff Harrell Revell said he felt Hill might
need security, even though he stressed then that the man's Lotto
ticket had not been verified yet.
   And in spite of that lack of confirmation, Hill was able to buy
two customized vans, worth a total of $42,000, from two different
dealers, with no money down.
   But the lottery announced Wednesday that Sheelah Ryan, 63, a
real estate broker from Winter Springs, had won the $55.1 million
jackpot.
   The customized vans were returned.
   Hill was charged with knowingly presenting a counterfeit or
altered state lottery ticket and falsely making, altering, forging,
passing or counterfeiting a state lottery ticket with intent to
defraud.
   Lottery officials did not answer their phones after issuing a
news release saying they had arrested Hill. The release did not say
what penalties Hill could face if convicted. There also was no
answer at the office of State Attorney Willie Meggs, whose office
assisted lottery security police in the investigation.
</TEXT>
