<FILEID>AP-NR-09-10-88 1043EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-SportAid Bjt   09-10 0807</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sport Aid, Bjt,0830</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fifty Million Expected To Run For Charity</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BEN DOBBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Up to 50 million people will pound the boulevards,
main streets and mud tracks of the world Sunday in the second Sport
Aid ``Race Against Time'' to raise funds for starving children,
organizers say.
   Billed as the biggest participation event in history, the
six-mile road runs will begin in searing heat or torch-lit
darkness, at speed or at a casual pace, when starting pistols fire
simultaneously in 128 countries at 11 a.m. EDT.
   From remote island outposts to the crowded streets of London,
New York, Moscow and Hong Kong, young and old will don ``I Changed
the World'' T-shirts for an enlarged rerun of Sport Aid '86.
   Organizer Nick Cater called it ``a petition of blistered feet''
to help poor countries ``do something for their children.''
   ``Our slogan is `Change the World','' he said. ``We hope to
inspire people to feel that they can make a very real difference to
the world they live in.''
   The race starts at dawn local time on Monday in the Pacific
island of Tonga, ``the land where time begins,'' and as the Sunday
evening sun sets over the Pyramids in Egypt, Cater said.
   All 58 residents in the South Pacific island of Pitcairn Island
have pledged to run, as have the majority of the 2,000 residents in
Norfolk Island off Australia.
   ``When you live on a small island you tend to become very
isolated from the rest of the world,'' said Tom Lloyd, editor of
the Norfolk Islander newspaper.
   ``Now we feel part of it. It's the biggest thing that's happened
on the island.''
   Two children from each participating country will formally kick
off the global event with a 1,000-yard run from New York's Fifth
Avenue to the steps of the United Nations headquarters.
   They will be accompanied by Omar Khalifa, a Sudanese athlete who
launched the May 25, 1986, race that raised more than $35 million
for African famine victims.
   Official runs have been organized in only 15 major American
cities, and Cater said ``the bigger nations of the world can be a
little insular.''
   ``We just wish we could reach out to all the people in the
(United) States,'' he said.
   The 1986 race, which attracted nearly 20 million runners in 89
countries, flopped in the United States because it coincided with a
nationwide ``Hands Across America'' campaign to raise funds for the
poor.
   Sport Aid will be broadcast live in six languages to a potential
audience of 1.5 billion people through satellite TV and radio
link-ups to 23 cities. Coverage will include excerpts of carnivals
and concerts from Trinidad to Dubai to Rio de Janeiro.
   Pope John Paul II will relay a special message of support during
his visit to Zimbabwe.
   Money raised from runners' sponsors, ticket sales to the races
and from sideline events will go to charities in mainly
underdeveloped nations. One-fifth of funds raised in each developed
country will go to poor and disabled children in that country.
   The United Nations Children's Fund estimates that nearly 15
million children die each year from hunger and easily preventable
diseases.
   By Saturday, 26 million people had signed up to run, but London
officials of Sport Aid said they expect as many as 50 million when
the starting pistols are fired.
   Sport Aid said Zambia's President Kenneth Kuanda will start the
race in the capital city of Lusaka. Iceland's President Vigdis
Finbogadott, Mauritius' First Lady, Lady Sugnautah, and Brazilian
soccer star Pele will put on their running shoes and participate in
their country's runs.
   Other locally organized fund-raising events include a
cross-country ski event by British army marines in the South
Atlantic island of South Georgia, and runs by passengers aboard the
luxury ocean liner Canberra in the Mediterranean and by oil workers
aboard tankers in the Gulf of Oman.
   In China, where 2.3 million runners have signed up, doctors will
hold special roadside clinics and donate their fees to help
inoculation and other medical programs.
   Sudan has organized a run alongside the flood-swollen Nile River
in Khartoum, but Bangladesh, also devastated by floods, has
postponed its race, Cater said.
   In Malaysia, government ministers will join a relay race in
Kuala Lumpur. Free-fall army parachutists will herald the start of
the race in Oman by descending into Muscat's Sultan Qaboos Stadium.
   In the United Arab Emirates, a massive 11-tier Sport Aid cake
weighing 440 pounds was officially cut in Dubai and an official
Sport Aid torch was moved by helicopter from Abu Dhabi to Dubai.
About 2,000 people were expected to run Sunday.
   Cater urged ``everybody on Sunday to do anything they can to
help, whether it's just going out and giving money to a local
children's charity. Let's do something for the kids of the world.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880910-0077 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-10-88 1053EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Burma-Diplomats     09-10 0656</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Burma-Diplomats,0674</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hard Times Accompany Push For Democracy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Burma, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES W. HATTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The struggle for democracy in Burma is
threatening the nation's food supply, causing shortages of gasoline
and increasing prices of fruits and vegetables, diplomats said
Saturday.
   Western diplomatic personnel interviewed here said shortages of
food and other supplies were widespread in Rangoon, Burma's
capital. Even the exclusive Rangoon store at which diplomats shop
has run out of rice, they said.
   Diplomats are among the only residents who can still tap the
virtually exhausted fuel supply. Many Burmese have had to walk up
to 15 miles to take part in anti-government demonstrations, they
said.
   The demonstrations prompted the government Saturday to end 26
years of single-party rule and announce that general elections will
be held under a multiparty system.
   Embassies and foreign organizations sent more than 230
dependents and non-essential staffers to Bangkok Friday on a
special Thai Airways flight, leaving about 400 others awaiting
evacuation.
   Diplomats said the evacuees included Americans, Australians,
Filipinos, Malaysians, Indonesians, British, Japanese, South
Koreans, Soviets and Thais.
   Despite widespread looting and increasing violence in the
Burmese capital, the diplomats insisted they were evacuated
strictly as a precautionary measure and said they hope to return
soon.
   ``The diplomatic store is supposed to have rice, but it has not
had it for a week or so,'' said one diplomat, who spoke on
condition of anonymity. Diplomatic personnel ``have the same
shortages as everyone else. We get fresh food at the markets but in
limited supplies. And it has become very expensive.
   ``We (diplomats) are in the happy position of having freezers,
and everyone has been gobbling up the food in their freezers
because they are afraid the electricity will go off.''
   The food shortage has occurred mainly because strikes and a fuel
shortage have made it very difficult to get commodities into the
capital. But the diplomat said hoarding is also to blame.
   Indeed, other diplomats have said the military has been hoarding
goods in an attempt to starve the people into submission.
   Another Western diplomat, also speaking anonymously, said a
small bag of rice in Rangoon was selling for 600 kyats ($100),
``and the average person makes less than 400 kyats ($67) a month.
Vegetables and fruit are still around, but the prices have gone up
a lot.''
   A lack of gasoline has kept most buses from operating, ``so a
lot of people have to walk,'' the diplomat said.
   ``Thousands of people had to walk 15 miles or more to get into
town (for a pro-democracy rally Friday),'' she said. ``They passed
our (diplomatic) compound for more than an hour. Then they had to
walk home again.
   ``You see almost no cars except for (those owned by)
diplomats,'' she added. The few buses running ``are packed. You see
25 people sitting on the top of them. A lot of people are not going
to work because of the transportation problem.''
   Both diplomats said the foreign community had no fear of the
massive crowds that have rallied in Rangoon almost daily for
several weeks to press for an end to one-party rule and an interim
government to lead the country to democracy. But the crowds have
made it difficult to move about.
   ``There are a million out walking but they are gentle,
good-natured,'' the first diplomat said. ``There are reports that
youngsters have been attacked by military intelligence people, but
they (soldiers) are not interested in foreigners.
   ``There have been such huge crowds that if you wanted to get
from one side of the city to the other you had to wait for an hour
and a half'' for the protesters to pass, the diplomat said. ``Then
you go one block and they are snaking back again.
   ``During the day everything is OK. But at night there are a lot
of robbers and looters out and it is not safe.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
