<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthAfrica     09-10 0499</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa,0514</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Minister Says Tutu Manipulated By Radicals; Afrikaners To Meet
With ANC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The law and order minister
described Archbishop Desmond Tutu on Saturday as a ``tragic and
misled person'' who is challenging the government on the orders of
revolutionaries.
   Also Saturday, a newspaper reported that prominent Afrikaner
politicians and academics, including the brother of a Cabinet
minister, will meet next month with Soviet policymakers and black
nationalist guerrilla leaders.
   Adriaan Vlok, the law and order minister, said revolutionaries
have decided that Tutu, leader of the Anglican church in southern
Africa, should ``create incidents'' to embarrass South Africa
during the U.S. presidential campaign and the current visit to the
region by Pope John Paul II.
   Vlok, who oversees the national police force, was reacting to
Tutu's recent defiance of an emergency regulation forbidding calls
for an election boycott.
   Three times in the past week, Tutu has urged blacks and whites
to boycott next month's municipal elections, which many blacks view
as an entrenchment of segregated, white-controlled political
structures.
   Police are investigating Tutu's statements to determine whether
he should be prosecuted.
   Vlok, in a speech reported by the state-run South African
Broadcasting Corp., said ``naive church leaders'' are being misused
by the outlawed African National Congress guerrilla movement and
South African Communist Party.
   Vlok said Tutu, out of personal ambition, is playing a key role
in a campaign to ``bring the country to its knees.''
   The Argus, a Cape Town daily, said 18 white South Africans will
travel to Munich, West Germany, in late October for a six-day
conference.
   They will meet with officials of the African National Congress
guerrilla movement and with a Soviet delegation that will include
at least two deputy directors of the African Institute of the
Soviet Academy of Sciences, it said.
   South African authorities have discouraged contacts with the
African National Congress. The organization is outlawed in South
Africa and wages a bombing and sabotage campaign to undermine the
Afrikaner-dominated government.
   According to The Argus, the delegation heading to Munich will
include Willem de Klerk, a former newspaper editor whose brother,
Frederik de Klerk, is minister of education and a possible
candidate to succeed President P.W. Botha.
   Others in the group reportedly will include Wynand Malan, a
Parliament member who heads the small, anti-apartheid National
Democratic Movement, and Frederik van Zyl Slabbert, former leader
of the liberal Progressive Federal Party. Malan and Slabbert have
met with ANC officials previously.
   Afrikaners, descended from Dutch and other northern European
settlers, make up about 60 percent of South Africa's 5 million
whites.
   Many Afrikaners have broken with Botha's National Party in
recent years, some to the left because of disenchantment with
apartheid, and a far larger number to the right to protest what
they perceive as concessions to blacks.
   Under apartheid, the 26 million blacks have no vote in national
affairs. The white minority controls the economy and maintain
separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
