<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Burma 6thLd-Writethru a0495 09-10 0804</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Burma, 6th Ld-Writethru, a0495,0823</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Burma Announces End To One-Party Rule</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with Maung Maung speech confirming
earlier Radio Rangoon announcement. TRIMS to tighten. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SEIN WIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Maung Maung said Burma's ruling
party decided today to end 26 years of single-party rule and to
hold a general election under a multiparty system.
   The decision was a victory for opposition leaders and for
hundreds of thousands of Burmese who have taken to the streets in
sometimes violent demonstrations that have toppled two presidents
in three months.
   Speaking before 968 delegates at a special party congress, the
president admitted that major errors were commmitted by the party
and said the interests of the people were paramount.
   ``Power corrupts, and absolute power corrupts absolutely,'' he
said in a speech carried by the state-owned Radio Rangoon. He
pledged a free and fair general election will be held as soon as
possible but gave no date.
   The broadcast announcer said the decision was unanimously
adopted by the delegates of the Burma Socialist Program Party.
   Maung Maung said a party emergency session of Parliament on
Sunday will make necessary amendments to the constitution to adopt
the multiparty system and also to form an independent commission to
supervise the elections.
   He urged government employes, who have left their jobs in
sympathy with the pro-democracy movement, to return to their jobs
so the government can function.
   The special party congress was originally scheduled for Monday
to decide whether a referendum on one-party rule would be called.
Radio Rangoon said the delegates today decided to scrap the
referendum idea and to go ahead with elections under a multiparty
system.
   Today's announcement came one day after former Prime Minister U
Nu, toppled in a 1962 military coup, announced the formation of a
rival government to take power from Maung Maung. It was not
immediately clear how today's development would affect U Nu's plan,
which was not supported by all opposition figures.
   Also Friday, about 500 renegade soldiers joined protesters
demanding formation of an interim government and full democracy. It
was the first major defection of troops to the opposition.
   The moves followed weeks of massive, occasionally bloody turmoil
in this isolated Southeast Asian nation that left dozens of people
dead. Unofficial reports said the death toll could be in the
hundreds from street riots that broke out in July.
   In a letter to embassies on Friday, 82-year-old U Nu called for
general elections Oct. 9. He announced a Cabinet with himself as
prime minister, former President Mahn Win Maung as president and
retired Gen. Tin Oo, a vocal critic of the current authoritarian
leadership, as defense minister.
   However, Tin Oo and two other members of the rival Cabinet _
retired military commanders Aung Shwe and Saw Myint _ resigned
today, and reliable sources said U Nu had not consulted them about
his move. The Bar Council of Burma said students and other
opposition groups also had not been consulted.
   The three men also said in a statement that they were resigning
from a League for Democracy and Peace that U Nu had formed earlier
to oppose the Maung Maung's government.
   Aung San Suu Kyi, an opposition figure and daughter of slain
independence leader Aung San, told reporters the announcement of a
multiparty system was ``a positive step,'' but said it could take
up to two years to form parties to contest in general elections.
   ``Under the present economic and political situation, an interim
government will be the best solution. It (the interim government)
would deal with economic problems and also hold general
elections,'' she told reporters.
   Another opposition leader, retired Gen. Aung Gyi, said he
doubted ``the prevailing situation will permit holding of general
elections under the present government.''
   Toru Ohno, a Japanese Burma specialist at Osaka University, said:
   ``The fact that the ruling party took action two days ahead of
its original schedule ... means that Maung Maung's government can
no longer control or suppress protest. I'm glad the party made the
compromise in an effort to seek a peaceful and democratic
settlement.
   Ne Win led the 1962 coup that toppled U Nu. Ne Win resigned as
head of the ruling party in July, citing in part widespread street
protests in March and June. Riots flared when the party chose Sein
Lwin to succeed Ne Win. Sein Lwin is a hardliner widely hated for
his brutal suppression of dissidents.
   The government said 112 people died in anti-government
demonstrations, but diplomats estimated hundreds were killed.
   Sein Lwin resigned Aug. 12 after 17 days in power, and Maung
Maung was named to replace him. Maung Maung was Burma's first
civilian leader in 26 years, but protests and nationwide strikes
continued as opponents demanded an immediate end to one-party rule.
</TEXT>
