<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Afghanistan-Germans     09-10 0229</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan-Germans,0236</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two West Germans Reported Captured In Afghanistan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PESHAWAR, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two West German doctors are believed
to have been captured in Afghanistan by the communist government as
they sought to help wounded guerrilla soldiers, a private aid
official said Saturday.
   Andreas von Ramdohr, spokesman for the Committee of German
Emergency Doctors, said Moslem guerrillas reported a man and a
woman from the group were apprehended by Afghan communist
authorities in the southeastern provincial capital of Ghazni.
   ``We cannot confirm it 100 percent. We have had no news from the
German embassy,'' von Ramdohr said.
   He declined to identify the two but said they were about a week
overdue returning from a trip to the central Afghan province of
Bamyan.
   Von Ramdohr said a guerrilla source reported that the pair was
driving toward Pakistan with a wounded rebel and a translator when
they lost their way and accidentally strayed into
communist-controlled territory.
   The Germans and their wounded charge were apprehended, but the
translator fled, according to the report. He said guerrillas
believed the couple were flown to Kabul Friday or Saturday.
   German embassy officials were unavailable for comment as the
mission was closed for the weekend.
   Soviet troops have been helping the Afghan government fight the
U.S.-backed guerrillas since December 1979. The Soviet Union agreed
in April to withdraw its estimated 115,000 troops by February 1989.
</TEXT>
