<FILEID>AP-NR-09-10-88 1145EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-AmericanLegion-Candidates     09-10 0597</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-American Legion-Candidates,0616</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Faced `The Troops' In Address To American Legion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES WOLFE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 70th annual convention of the
American Legion, as conservative a conclave as one was likely to
find last week, was in high spirits for speeches by President
Reagan and Vice President George Bush.
   But some booed the mere mention of Michael Dukakis.
   So, why did the Democratic presidential nominee bother to show?
   ``He'd be foolish not to face the troops,'' said retired Marine
Andrew Steffanic, commander of the California Legion.
   The Massachusetts governor could not afford to ignore the
nation's largest veterans organization, ``even if he felt like he
wasn't going to sway the first vote,'' said Legionnaire Nathan
Wolfe.
   ``It would be detrimental to his campaign. The Legion is almost
3 million strong,'' said Wolfe, 58, of North Augusta, S.C.
   Democrat Walter Mondale clearly was no favorite of this group
when he ran against Reagan four years ago, but he ``toughed it
out'' at the Legion's 1984 convention, Steffanic said.
   Mondale paused in his speech, which to that point had been
received in stony silence, and jokingly advised his audience it was
OK to applaud. That brought laughter ``but he was no match
whatsoever for Reagan,'' said Steffanic, 67, of Portola, Calif.
   Dukakis' pitch before the American Legion on Thursday included
assurances that he favored a strong national defense, use of force
against terrorists and a Cabinet-level post for veterans' affairs.
He also lashed out at the Reagan administration for closing
hospitals, clinics and counseling centers and touted programs in
Massachusetts for homeless or unemployed veterans.
   ``An awful lot of guys who heard that speech were swayed,'' said
John Walsh, 36, a lawyer, disabled Air Force veteran and Dukakis
supporter from Quincy, Mass. ``He focused on the needs of veterans,
and the other two guys (Reagan and Bush) totally failed to do so.''
   Another Massachusetts delegate, Alfred Harwood of Lynn,
disagreed.
   ``I know some of the veterans' affairs that go on in
Massachusetts, and what (Dukakis) says up here and what he does,
doesn't agree,'' Harwood said. ``As far as the defense of this
country is concerned, I would have to agree with Bush. ... I'm not
going to vote for Dukakis.''
   Navy veteran George Ellerkamp, 65, said he was for Bush before
and after the convention.
   Even though Bush ``seemed nervous,'' including his blunder
Wednesday about Sept. 7 being Pearl Harbor Day, and although
veterans in general agree with Dukakis that the VA is in decline,
Ellerkamp said Dukakis said nothing to make him change his mind.
   ``I felt like both (Bush and Dukakis) told us what we wanted to
hear,'' said Ellerkamp, of St. Matthews, Ky.
   Also, veterans don't blame Reagan for cutting back VA services,
Ellerkamp said. ``They blame the system, not any individual,'' he
said.
   Walsh said most of those attending the convention were veterans
of World War II and Korea, older men who own homes, hold
established jobs or have retired, and have little in common with
Vietnam-era veterans.
   ``If you can afford to come to a national convention, you
certainly aren't representative of the average veteran on the
street,'' he said.
   Dukakis' reception was far politer than might have been expected
after Sen. Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz., a staunch advocate of
veterans in Congress, was booed Wednesday for urging the
Legionnaires to ``listen attentatively'' to Dukakis' message.
   The heckling brought a stern rebuke from Legion National Cmdr.
John P. ``Jake'' Comer, also of Massachusetts.
   ``We will do our booing in the voting booth in November,'' Comer
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
