<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Scotus-Election 1stLd-Writethru a0524 09-10 0969</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scotus-Election, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0524,950</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Supreme Court's Ideological Balance at Stake in November</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS last graf bgng, _Lawrence, to CORRECT, reading Laurence
instead Lawrence.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At stake in the voters' choice between George
Bush and Michael Dukakis in November is the delicate balance
between liberal and conservative justices that has set the Supreme
Court's ideological course in recent years.
   When the next president takes office, the three oldest and most
liberal justices on the nine-member high court will be over 80.
   The average age of the court's liberal wing will be a bit over
77. The average age of its conservative bloc will be 59.
   Bush almost certainly would appoint far more conservative
justices as president than Dukakis would.
   Four years ago, there were predictions that Reagan would have
the chance to decide the future of an aging Supreme Court for
generations to come, but things didn't work out that way.
   There is no question that the court is younger and more
conservative than it was at the start of Reagan's second term. But
liberal justices still exert critical influence, and Reagan's
opportunity to turn the court into a conservative stronghold has
passed.
   In this election year, however, predictions of sweeping changes
in the Supreme Court in the next four years seem more likely to
come true.
   The nine justices enjoy lifetime tenure. None is reported to
have grave health problems, and none has made any public mention of
retirement plans.
   The court's leading liberals are Justices William J. Brennan,
82, Thurgood Marshall, 80, and Harry A. Blackmun, soon to be 80.
   Justice John Paul Stevens, 68, often joins them, particularly in
criminal law decisions.
   The court's conservative bloc is led by Chief Justice William H.
Rehnquist, 63. Its most conservative member is Antonin Scalia, 52.
   In varying degrees, the conservatives are bolstered by Justices
Sandra Day O'Connor, 58, Anthony Kennedy, 52, and Byron R. White,
71.
   Unlike Reagan and Democratic nominee Walter Mondale in 1984, the
two presidential candidates this year have virtually ignored the
high court and their vision of its future in their stump speeches.
   Vice President Bush has noted that the next president ``will
very possibly appoint two or three justices to the Supreme Court,
where they'll sit well into the next century.''
   Bush promises to appoint judges ``who will interpret the
Constitution, not legislate from the bench.'' He also says he will
``appoint judges who don't reserve all their sympathy for
criminals; who understand that victims have rights, too.''
   The unspoken message appears to be that Bush, like Reagan, is
determined to select conservative justices who could sway the high
court's balance of power on such issues as abortion and affirmative
action.
   The court for years has been drifting toward more conservative
views regarding the rights of criminal suspects.
   As governor of Massachusetts, Dukakis has appointed numerous
judges who generally have been more liberal than conservative.
However, they are screened by an 18-member, non-ideological ``merit
commission.''
   Speculation about the impact that Bush or Dukakis might have on
the Supreme Court depends on who they would nominate and which
justices would be replaced.
   Reagan named O'Connor to the court in 1981. Since 1984, he has
appointed Scalia and Kennedy.
   All three are more conservative then the men they replaced, but
Reagan did not have a chance to place a conservative in a seat
formerly held by a liberal.
   O'Connor succeeded Potter Stewart, Scalia was a numerical
replacement for retired Chief Justice Warren E. Burger after
Rehnquist was elevated to chief justice, and Kennedy succeeded
retired Justice Lewis F. Powell.
   The National Law Journal recently asked 40 court observers _
including campaign officials, former White House aides, federal
judges, law professors and lawyers _ to speculate on possible
nominees of Bush and Dukakis.
   The 10 people named most often as potential Bush nominees, in
alphabetical order, were:
   _James A. Baker, 58, former White House chief of staff who is
the Bush campaign chairman.
   _C. Boyden Gray, 45, the vice president's legal adviser since
1981.
   _Orrin G. Hatch, 54, a Republican senator from Utah.
   _Patrick E. Higginbotham, 49, of Dallas, a judge on the 5th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals.
   _Roger J. Miner, 54, of Albany, N.Y., a judge on the 2nd U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals.
   _Samuel R. Pierce Jr., 65, secretary of Housing and Urban
Development.
   _Pamela A. Rymer, 47, a federal trial judge in Los Angeles since
1983.
   _Richard L. Thornburgh, 58, the former Pennsylvania governor who
last month succeeded Edwin Meese III as attorney general.
   _Ralph K. Winter Jr., 53, of New Haven, Conn., a judge on the
2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals.
   _Charles Alan Wright, 60, a law professor at the University of
Texas and a national authority on civil procedure and federal
jurisdiction.
   The 10 people named most often as potential Dukakis nominees, in
alphabetical order, were:
   _Derek Bok, 58, president of Harvard University and a former Law
School dean there.
   _Stephen G. Breyer, 50, of Boston, a judge on the 1st U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals.
   _Mario M. Cuomo, 56, governor of New York.
   _Harry T. Edwards, 47, a judge on the U.S. Court of Appeals in
Washington.
   _Ruth Bader Ginsburg, 55, a judge on the U.S. Court of Appeals.
   _Amalya L. Kearse, 51, of New York, a judge on the 2nd U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals.
   _Paul J. Liacos, 59, a member of the Massachusetts Supreme
Judicial Court.
   _Jon O. Newman, 56, of Hartford, Conn., a judge on the 2nd U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals.
   _Paul S. Sarbanes, 55, a Democratic senator from Maryland.
   _Laurence H. Tribe, 46, a Harvard Law School professor and a
leading constitutional scholar.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Editor's Note: Richard Carelli has covered the Supreme Court for
The Associated Press since 1976.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
