<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Carlucci     09-10 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Carlucci,0390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Agreement On Missiles, Satellites Highlight Carlucci Visit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SHANGHAI, China (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci on
Saturday wrapped up his visit to China, leaving the Chinese happy
about a U.S. decision that could permit Chinese rockets to launch
U.S. satellites.
   Carlucci also said he was satisfied that the Chinese would
exercise prudence in their arms sales to the Middle East and other
areas of the world.
   Carlucci said he conveyed the U.S. decision about satellites to
National Defense Minister Qin Jiwei.
   ``He was most pleased with that,'' Carlucci told reporters at
the Wusong Naval Facility in Shanghai.
   The Reagan administration on Friday announced it would give
export licenses for satellites manufactured by Hughes Aircraft that
are scheduled to be launched for Australian and Hong Kong companies
with China's Long March rocket.
   The decision must be approved by the U.S. Congress and a group
of Western allies that monitor high-technology transfers.
   Hong Kong-based AsiaSat is to put a satellite in orbit next
year, while AusSat from Australia will launch two satellites in
1991 and 1992 using the Chinese service.
   Carlucci said he had recommended to Washington that the licenses
be approved.
   The settling of the satellite issue was the second major area of
friction solved during Carlucci's first trip to China.
   In Beijing, on Thursday, he told a news conference that he was
``fully satisfied'' with China's statement that it would exercise
prudence in its arms sales to the Middle East and other areas of
the world.
   Carlucci and Defense Department officials did not elaborate.
   He said his talks were ``the best discussions we've had'' on the
subject.
   The United States was concerned that Chinese sales of
medium-range missiles to Saudi Arabia and proposed sales to other
Middle East countries would upset the regional military balance.
   Qin Jiwei told reporters that Chinese arms sales were small
compared to those of the United States and were carried out
responsibly.
   Carlucci was led by navy Cmdr. Zhang Lianzhong on a 50-minute
tour of the Wusong base. He called the visit ``a sign of efforts to
have exchanges with the entire range of the Chinese military.''
   The defense secretary left after the tour for a flight to Hong
Kong.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
