<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Britain-Vietnam     09-10 0249</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Vietnam,0257</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Britain Expels Vietnamese Diplomat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government today ordered a Vietnamese diplomat
who confronted demonstrators with a gun outside his embassy to
leave Britain.
   An announcement by the Foreign Office said Vietnamese Third
Secretary Khang Than Nhan must leave the country by Sunday.
   Vietnamese Ambassador Tran Van Hung, pressed by the British
government about Khang's actions Sept. 4., turned over a toy gun on
Thursday.
   But today he gave a real gun to junior Foreign Office minister
Timothy Eggar and said it was the one Khang was holding when he
confronted Vietnamese refugees protesting in front of the embassy,
the Foreign Office said.
   A government statement said Tran told Eggar he could not waive
Khang's diplomatic immunity to enable Britain to prosecute the
third secretary. On Thursday, the ambassador had agreed that Khang
would forgo his immunity.
   On Sept. 4, the demonstrators that Khang confronted took
photographs of him holding a gun. The pictures were published in
London's Daily Express.
   The Foreign Office said earlier this week that it took a very
serious view of the incident and warned the ambassador of the
``gravest consequences'' unless the diplomat's immunity was waived.
   Diplomatic missions in Britain are not supposed to house arms.
   The government has taken violations of that rule seriously since
a gunman firing from the Libyan Embassy killed a London policewoman
during a protest demonstration in April 1984. After a police siege
of the embassy, the building was closed and diplomatic relations
severed.
</TEXT>
