<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Mexico     09-10 0321</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mexico,0332</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Salinas Confirmed As Mexico's Next President</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDAJOY FENLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After a long and bitter debate, the Chamber
of Deputies today certified Carlos Salinas de Gortari as president
of Mexico.
   A spokesman for the chamber said the vote was 263-85.
   Opposition lawmakers, who claim Salinas won the July 6 election
through massive vote fraud, tried to stall the certification
process by making numerous speeches during an all-night session.
But they had no chance of prevailing.
   Salinas will begin a six-year term Dec. 1 and replace Miguel de
la Madrid.
   The raucous debate occurred because the election placed the
largest number of opposition lawmakers in the legislature since the
governing Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI, was founded
nearly 60 years ago.
   As expected, today's vote was along party lines. PRI, won a
majority of 260 in the 500-person chamber in the election, and at
least three opposition deputies have since defected to the
governing party.
   Orlando Arvizu, a PRI deputy from Hidalgo state, said Friday
evening the chamber debate would continue ``until we certify the
presidential election.''
   ``If it's up to us, it (the confirmation) could last three days.
We plan to destroy their arguments one by one,'' said a Popular
Socialist spokesman.
   The Popular Socialist Party belongs to the left-of-center
Democratic Front coalition headed by former presidential candidate
Cuauhtemoc Cardenas.
   On Friday, opposition delegates walked out on a key legislative
committee but failed to prevent the panel from recommending
Salinas' confirmation.
   The PRI members on the committee declared the July 6 election
valid and said Salinas won with 50.74 percent. The panel said
Cardenas won 31.06 percent, and Manuel Clouthier of the rightist
National Action Party won 16.81 percent.
   The PRI accused the opposition of trying to derail an orderly
presidential transition. ``What they are seeking is to destabilize
the government and degrade the republic, its institutions and its
politics,'' it said.
</TEXT>
