<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Thailand-Crash     09-10 0506</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Thailand-Crash,0531</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Olympic Team Canceled Reservations On Plane That Crashed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnam's Olympic team canceled
reservations on a jetliner two days before it crashed while
approaching Bangkok airport, killing 75 people, officials were
quoted as saying Saturday.
   Thai officials said they expected Soviet experts to join a team
of Vietnamese and Thai experts to investigate the Air Vietnam
accident. The Soviet-made Tu-134 jetliner with 81 people aboard was
flying from the Vietnamese capital of Hanoi Friday when it slammed
into a rice field and exploded four miles north of Bangkok airport
during a thunderstorm.
   The six survivors, including the pilot, remained in intensive
care Saturday at Bhumibol Hospital.
   Pham Vu Hien, a senior official of Air Vietnam, said the plane
apparently was hit by lightning, Japan's Kyodo news service
reported. A Vietnamese pilot who was among the six survivors
earlier gave the same cause for the accident.
   Hien said the airline will pay compensation to the relatives of
each victim, Kyodo said.
   Japan's Nihon television network quoted Vietnamese officials as
saying Vietnam's 16-member Olympic team canceled reservations on
the flight two days before the crash.
   Among the dead were Vietnam's public health minister, Dang Hoi
Huan, and its ambassador-designate to the Philippines, Nguyen
Dhuong Vu. Also killed were India's ambassador to Vietnam, Arun
Patwardhan, and seven other officials of his embassy. No Americans
were aboard the plane.
   Workers retrieved all 75 bodies from the wreckage on Friday.
   Thai newspapers said Saturday that workers of two charity groups
argued heatedly over who would be first to retrieve the bodies.
Workers of the Poh Tech Tung and Ruamkratanyoo foundations have
previously have fought bloody battles at accident sites.
   The Poh Tech Tung volunteers claimed they spotted a body first,
the Nation newspaper reported. But their rivals argued that they
were the first to grab the victim's feet, it said.
   ``The argument would have erupted into a fist fight had the
police not intervened,'' the newspaper said.
   State-run Radio Hanoi reported Saturday that Vietnam's Prime
Minister Do Muoi ordered an investigation into the crash.
   The plane broke into three when it hit the ground. The pieces
were scattered on a dirt road, a rice field and a pond, where the
charred cockpit and fuselage were found along with most of the
bodies. Two flight data recorders were recovered from the crash
site.
   The Tu-134, the Vietnamese flag carrier's main aircraft, also is
used by the Soviet airline Aeroflot. Several Tu-134s have crashed
in recent years, including one in Siberia in February that killed
an undisclosed number of people, and one in October 1986 that
killed President Samora Machel of Mozambique.
   The Japanese aviation magazine Kokujoho said the plane, which
was introduced in 1963, is no longer manufactured. Air Vietnam
officials said they lack funding to buy newer, Western-made planes.
   The last major plane crash in Thailand was Aug. 31, 1987, when a
Thai Airways domestic airliner fell into the sea off the southern
resort island of Phuket, killing all 83 people aboard the Boeing
737.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
