<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People     09-10 0947</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People,0980</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Spelling of Mercouri's brother's name, with an `s' on the
end, is cq.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Melina Mercouri, Greece's minister of
culture and science, canceled her appearance as guest of honor at a
celebration of the Walters Art Gallery's exhibition of Greek
artworks, forcing the gallery to cancel the black-tie event.
   ``It was just an unfortunate consequence of fate,'' said gallery
director Robert P. Bergman.
   ``The poor woman is exhausted and ill,'' he said Saturday. ``She
apologized to us. She sent us a very nice telegram.''
   Though the planned Friday gala was canceled, Ms. Mercouri's
brother Spyros Mercouris, coordinator of international exhibitions
for the Greek government, toured the show, accompanied by Greek
Ambassador George Papoulias, Bergman said.
   Howard White, a spokesman for the museum, said that when Ms.
Mercouri, 62, gave her regrets, ``We decided the only ethical thing
to do was to cancel the black-tie reception and dinner. We felt
badly about that, but we promised them Melina.''
   ``At something like this, if the guest of honor doesn't show up,
the event loses much of its cachet.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Country singer Roy Clark says he is
eager to return to the Soviet Union for a second good-will tour.
   Tennessee Sens. Albert Gore Jr. and Jim Sasser, and George
Lindsey, one of Clark's co-stars on the television show
``Hee-Haw,'' joined Clark at a fund-raising dinner in his honor
Friday night. The host of the dinner was comedian Bob Hope.
   Proceeds from the dinner will help pay for Clark's return to the
Soviet Union, which is also getting funds from U.S. and Soviet
government agencies. He is due to leave in mid-November for a tour
that will include 12 concerts in Moscow and Leningrad.
   ``I guess I was the first person to introduce country music to
the Russians, and they loved it,'' Clark said. ``I, in turn, loved
them. They're just people, not so different from us.''
   ``I send him to Russia with love,'' Hope quipped. ``It's either
send him or deport him. Who else would want him, except maybe his
wife?''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BEATRICE, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bibs, booties and other gifts that
Beatrice residents collected for Britain's newest princess _ named
Beatrice _ will be given to a London children's hospital, city
officials said.
   The gifts were shipped to Princess Beatrice Elizabeth Mary of
York, daughter of Andrew and Sarah, the Duke and Duchess of York.
In addition to baby shower-type gifts, they included Nebraska and
Beatrice T-shirts, an engraved watch from the local jewelry store,
and an offer of a scholarship to Southeast Community College's
Beatrice campus.
   Locals organized the project to draw attention to the name
shared by the princess, who was born Aug. 8, and the southeastern
Nebraska community of 19,000.
   However, Beatrice Chamber of Commerce President Diane Schwenke
said organizers have been notified that the package could not be
delivered because the royal family's policy is not to accept gifts.
   After discussions with British officials, they decided to send
the gifts to Children's Hospital of London in the name of Princess
Beatrice, she said. They still hope that some of the cards, letters
and honorary proclamations will find their way to the royal family.
   ``The whole thing really did benefit Beatrice, Nebraska, a
lot,'' Mrs. Schwenke said. ``It did a lot to put our community on
the map.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Valerie Harper and her husband stand
to lose nearly $23 million in future profits as a result of her
being dropped from the hit show originally titled ``Valerie,'' her
attorney said.
   Closing arguments were completed Friday in a contract dispute
between Lorimar Productions and Miss Harper, who was dropped from
the television show, along with her husband, last year. The judge
planned to give instructions to the jury Monday.
   Attorney Barry Langberg, who represents Miss Harper and her
husband, Tony Cacciotti, said the couple lost nearly $23 million in
future profits when they were cut out of the show. Cacciotti was
co-executive producer of the show.
   The figure was calculated by estimating the value of each
episode of ``Valerie,'' an NBC situation comedy. After Miss Harper
left the show, it was retitled ``The Hogan Family.''
   Langberg argued that Miss Harper was a perfectionist who wanted
to deliver the best show possible. He also portrayed Lorimar's
dismissal of the couple as unjustified and an act of bad faith.
   Donald Engel, an attorney for Lorimar, said Miss Harper made a
deal to quit the show, but became dissatisfied with it afterward.
Attorneys contended that Miss Harper made demands for more money
and staged months of bruising emotional battles on the set.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Country singer William Lee Golden has
reached an out-of-court settlement in a $40 million suit against
his former partners in the Oak Ridge Boys quartet, his attorney
said.
   ``There is money involved and both sides are happy it's over,''
attorney Wayne Halper said Friday. He refused to reveal the amount
of the settlement.
   Golden was forced out of the group in March 1987, after 22
years. Duane Allen, Joe Bonsall and Richard Sterban voted him out,
citing friction among band members. He was replaced by Steve
Sanders.
   ``This thing was more akin to a divorce than a suit for
damages,'' Halper said. ``There was nothing to be gained by having
a public airing of differences.''
   Golden is now concentrating on a solo career and plans to begin
recording songs this fall, Halper said.
   The Oak Ridge Boys are best known for their 2 million-selling
hit, ``Elvira.'' Since Golden's departure, the group has put the
single ``True Heart'' on the country charts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
