<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Korea 1stLd-Writethru   09-10 0659</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0521,0681</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Radical Students Protest Olympics, Battle Police</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with three grafs to ADD details on effigy. Pick up 3rd
pvs, `Oppose the...'
^By BARRY RENFREW</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of radical students yelling
slogans against the Olympics and the United States battled riot
police with firebombs and rocks Saturday.
   About 2,000 students from a dozen colleges took part in a rally
at Seoul's Yonsei University to denounce the Olympics and President
Roh Tae-woo's government.
   Many shouted ``Yankee go home.'' Some burned an effigy of an
American wearing the Stars and Stripes.
   ``Oppose the Olympics that squeeze out the blood of the
masses,'' shouted a radical leader as protesters chanted slogans
against the Games, scheduled to begin in Seoul Sept. 17.
   Police said they had no reports of arrests or injuries. Students
also clashed with police at Yonsei Friday in an anti-Olympic
protest.
   Students marched out of the school to confront hundreds of riot
police surrounding the campus in the western part of the city.
   Protesters, some armed with iron and wood clubs, taunted police
and then attacked them with firebombs and rocks.
   ``Oppose the dictatorial Olympics'' and ``Down with the military
dictatorship,'' protesters chanted.
   Waves of masked students rushed out of the school's gates and
climbed over walls to pelt police with firebombs that exploded in
orange balls of blazing gasoline, setting fire to some troopers'
shields and clothing.
   But police did not use tear gas because of a government ban
during the Olympics. Police also hurled back fewer rocks than
normal in an apparent attempt to limit violence.
   Police charged the protesters a few times, but remained on the
defensive most of the time. The fighting lasted about 30 minutes
and was confined to the road in front of the school.
   Radical students have called for widespread anti-Olympic
protests, but they have been confined to a few campuses in Seoul
and some other cities. There have been no demonstrations near the
Olympic venues.
   Student leaders told a rally before the clash with police that
the Roh government was using the Olympics to solidify authoritarian
rule. The leaders said the Olympics should not be staged unless
they helped to promote democracy.
   ``The Olympics are being used to cement the fascist regime,''
said a statement by the protesters. ``The regime is making all-out
efforts to weaken the people's power.''
   Speakers charged the United States was conspiring with Roh to
continue military rule. The United States has about 42,000 troops
stationed in South Korea under a mutual defense pact.
   National Assembly Speaker Kim Chae-sun, in a speech Saturday to
the opening session of the legislature's new session, said the
overwhelming majority of South Koreans support the Olympics.
   The radicals, a small but powerful minority on campuses, have
virtually no public support. Most South Koreans are critical of
radical protests against the Olympics and want nothing to disrupt
the Games.
   Radical students contend the Roh administration is a front for
continued military rule and say they are determined to topple the
government.
   Roh, a former general who won a presidential election in
December, has introduced broad political reforms and dismantled
authoritarian controls.
   In another development Saturday, aides to former President Chun
Doo-hwan said he canceled plans to attend the opening ceremonies of
the Olympics. Chun has been accused of corrpution by the opposition.
   The aides quoted Chun as saying he did not want to cause trouble
at the Games and would stay away despite government plans to invite
him as an honored guest.
   Olympic organizers have invited Chun as one of South Korea's
three living former presidents, and government officials have said
Chun's role in bringing the Games to Seoul justified the invitation.
   The invitation triggered a strong opposition backlash. Chun, who
seized power with military backing in 1980, has faced a
parliamentary inquiry for alleged corruption and other wrongdoing
during his administration.
   Chun left office in February after a seven-year term.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
