<FILEID>AP-NR-09-10-88 1445EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Vietnam     09-10 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Vietnam,0331</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Britain Ousts Vietnamese Diplomat Who Brandished Gun During
Protest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain on Saturday expelled a Vietnamese diplomat
who brandished a gun outside his embassy during a demonstration by
opponents of the Hanoi government.
   The Foreign Office said Vietnamese Third Secretary Khang Than
Nhan must leave Britain by midnight Sunday. The Vietnamese Embassy
said no official would be available to comment during the weekend.
   Vietnamese Ambassador Tran Van Hung, pressed by the British
government about Khang's actions during the Sept. 4 protest, turned
over a toy gun on Thursday.
   But on Saturday he produced a real gun and gave it to the
British Foreign Office. Tran acknowledged that Khang was holding
the gun when he confronted demonstrating Vietnamese refugees in
front of the embassy, the Foreign Office said.
   Tran told the Foreign Office that his government regretted the
incident and recognized that it constituted a breach of British and
Vietnamese regulations.
   But Tran said that in keeping with Vietnam's invariable
practice, the embassy would not grant a waiver of Khang's
diplomatic immunity to enable Britain to prosecute him.
   On Thursday, the Vietnamese ambassador initially agreed that
Khang would give up his immunity.
   The Foreign Office said Britain would not accept nomination of a
successor to Khang until it received a full account of the
disciplinary proceedings Khang would face.
   At the Sept. 4 embassy incident, demonstrators took photographs
of Khang, which were published in London's Daily Express.
   The Foreign Office said last week it took a very serious view of
the incident and warned the ambassador of the ``gravest
consequences'' unless the diplomat's immunity was waived.
   Diplomatic missions in Britain are not allowed to keep arms, and
the government has taken violations seriously since a gunman firing
from the Libyan Embassy killed a London policewoman during a
demonstration in April 1984.
   After a police siege of the embassy, the building was closed and
diplomatic relations severed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
