<FILEID>AP-NR-09-10-88 1530EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     09-10 0518</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0539</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANN ARBOR, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jack Matson's first class assignment
will be to have his University of Michigan Business School students
laugh as ridiculously as they can. Later, they will confront
humiliation.
   Then, when things go wrong in later life, Matson said, ``They'll
understand those are natural, normal sensations and by knowing
that, they'll be more confident to forge ahead.''
   Matson, a University of Houston engineering professor, is on
loan to the business school for the 1988-89 academic year.
   His ``Failure 101'' course was selected from among 158
competitors for the Zell-Laurie Fellowship visiting professorship,
intended to develop courses to foster entrepreneurship.
   It is based on a series of ``hurdle-jumping exercises'' that
confront students with repeated failures.
   Matson, 46, said the idea sprang from unusual events in his own
life. At 40, he was hit in the head by a bolt of lightning while
playing tennis, and that freed him from a ``straitjacketed''
academic life, he said.
   ``There was nothing wrong with me physically, but
psychologically I still felt dead,'' he said. He decided he was
having a midlife crisis and began exploring his creativity.
   ``I started to feel that success is somewhat predicated on a
nest of failures. That's how we learn. If we really want to
succeed, we have to take risks,'' he said.
   In his first class, on Monday, Matson plans to conduct a contest
to see which student can produce the most ridiculous laugh. He
wants to create a spontaneous, playful atmosphere.
   ``I want to teach them how to generate ideas, and bring out
these things that are inside of them, but have been suppressed
during their entire academic careers'' because of fear of failure,
he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOURNE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   What John Mullan and Thomas Lopes found
beside the road was literally a windfall, but they didn't hesitate
to get it back to its proper owner.
   The two state public works department employees found $6,100 in
cash in a blue nylon briefcase alongside a road here Wednesday and
promptly turned it over to police.
   Harry W. Turner of East Falmouth was carrying the money to buy a
boat when the bag blew out the window of his vehicle, said State
Trooper James Mattaliano.
   ``He didn't notice, I guess,'' Mattaliano said. ``He was very
happy to get it back.''
   Mullan and Lopes said they didn't have to think about what to do
with the money after they stopped and picked up the briefcase.
   After realizing it contained 61 hundred-dollar bills, ``we
looked at each other and started laughing, then turned the truck
around and took the bag to state police,'' Mullan said Thursday.
   ``It was hilarious,'' he said. ``You read about it in the paper
and never think it's going to happen to you.''
   Lopes, who at 62 is set to end a 28-year career with the
department in December, said he and his partner ``wanted to feel
good about doing the right thing.''
   ``We worried about the people who had lost it, figuring they
would get excited,'' Mullan said. ``It wasn't our nature to keep
it.''
</TEXT>
