<FILEID>AP-NR-09-10-88 1533EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Eastern Bjt   09-10 0549</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Eastern, Bjt,0572</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Another 4,000 Jobs Go; Incredible Shrinking Airline?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Money-losing Eastern Airlines eliminated 4,000 more
jobs Saturday in the ``downsizing'' it says it needs to survive,
but the unions charged that the cutbacks are actually making the
airline less competitive.
   The cuts, which are being contested in court by the unions,
reduced Eastern's workforce to fewer than 30,000. Less than four
years ago, it had 42,000 workers.
   Eastern eliminated 12 percent of its routes two weeks ago,
ending service to 14 cities.
   Laid-off workers with seniority can transfer to other cities,
``bumping'' newer employees out of their jobs. Thus, newer
employees could take the brunt of the layoffs when the bumping is
complete.
   The mood around work gates was sullen.
   ``We've had very few who have already gotten their layoff
notices, but we've heard there are about 80 who have shown
intentions of bumping,'' said Don Boyd, a union chief steward
representing ramp agents. ``So a lot of these people don't know
what to expect.''
   ``The people are devastated,'' said Charles E. Bryan, president
of the Machinists local, Eastern's largest union with nearly 12,000
members. ``It's a traumatic thing to lose your job when you've just
gotten your children started in school.''
   Of the 4,000 jobs eliminated, 1,500 were non-union positions,
including management and clerical.
   Among the 4,000 are few hundred flight attendants, mechanics,
baggage handlers and ramp agents who are taking early retirement or
quitting, Eastern said.
   ``The fact is we have lost over a billion dollars in this
decade,'' said Robin Matell, the company's chief spokesman. ``We
have to take prudent, although admittedly painful, measures.''
   Eastern, which lost $182 million in 1987 and $149 million in the
first half of 1988 and is $2.5 billion in debt, estimates it will
save $100 million a year with the latest cuts.
   Eastern was taken over more than two years ago by Houston-based
Texas Air Corp.
   Union members have accused Texas Air chairman Frank Lorenzo of
stripping Eastern's assets in favor of Texas Air's sister airline,
Continental, which has been non-union since Lorenzo took it into
bankruptcy reorganization in 1983.
   The unions say downsizing the carrier dooms Eastern to
decreasing ability to compete. Laying off employees drives up labor
costs per flight because less-senior workers being laid off are
paid less than those who remain, they said.
   ``The last thing you want to do in the airline industry is
downsize,'' Bryan said. ``Many of the costs are fixed, and the
break-even yield goes way up. It's a lose-lose proposition that
just feeds on itself.
   ``Frank Lorenzo is using typical robber baron strategy to
plunder the company and try to make all the cash he can.''
   Eastern's unions will argue against the layoffs later this month
in the U.S. Court of Appeals in Washington, which allowed Eastern
to cut the jobs if it posted a $4.7 million bond to cover wages if
workers are later reinstated.
   The appeals court earlier his month set aside an injunction by
U.S. District Judge Barrington Parker, who had barred Eastern from
eliminating the jobs without negotiating with its unions.
   Machinists' members will vote Thursday on a management demand
for $161 million in cuts. The union and Eastern have been in
federal mediation since January.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
