<FILEID>AP-NR-09-10-88 1547EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Fires-Holdout     09-10 0661</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fires-Holdout,0680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Silver Gate Waits For Final Firestorm</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Forest Fires Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KURT J. REPANSHEK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SILVER GATE, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hays Kirby refused to be run off by
the sheriff when his town was ordered evacuated, but he realizes
that nearby forest fires might succeed where the law failed.
   The owner of the 20-room Grizzly Lodge just to the east of
Yellowstone National Park's northeast entrance has watched forest
fires burn to the north, south and east of this mountain hamlet.
Saturday, he waited for flames from the Storm Creek fire some three
miles to the west to be fanned into Silver Gate.
   ``We're going to burn up. They can't stop this fire,'' Kirby,
45, said Saturday while finicky breeze whipped the American flag
outside his front door. ``If the wind blows, we're going to blow
up.''
   Forecasts of wind blowing up to 60 mph had been dropped,
although meteorologists still said gusts to 40 mph were possible.
   But a steady rain fell at mid-day.
   Forest fires have charred more than 1 million acres _ 300,000
acres on Friday alone _ in Yellowstone National Park and its
surrounding national forests since late June.
   To Kirby, a wiry man who flies F-16 fighters in the Air Force
Reserve and who has made this tiny community home for eight years,
the fires are an unnecessary tragedy.
   ``This fire laid up in a place we call Lake Abundance for days
and days, and you could have driven ... you could have driven fire
trucks in there and put this fire out,'' he said.
   But Lake Abundance is in the Absaroka-Beartooth Wilderness Area
in Custer National Forest just north of Silver Gate. Machinery is
not allowed in wilderness areas and natural fires are allowed to
burn without man's interference.
   Since it left the wilderness area, firefighters have been unable
to halt the fire.
   A backfire started last week to eliminate fuel between Silver
Gate and the Storm Creek fire reversed directions and burned east
along the ridge running east and west above Silver Gate and Cooke
City. Several homes and outbuildings were destroyed by the flames.
   ``There was no necessity for burning these communities up,''
Kirby said again.
   Since mid-August, these two sleepy towns that funnel summertime
tourists in and out of Yellowstone and winter sportsmen into the
surrounding mountains have acted mainly as fire camps.
   About 100 people call Silver Gate and Cooke City home throughout
the year, but the fires have brought 450 to 500 men and women in to
fight the fires. The Storm Creek fire camp just to the east of
Cooke City holds an additional 1,100.
   ``I live here. My life is here, my family is here,'' said Kirby,
who believes he and his immediate family are the only full-time
Silver Gate residents who have held their ground. ``I just couldn't
leave. I just ... I don't know. I really thought that we could get
a handle on this fire.''
   While some other residents had come back, he said, they were
ordered to leave quickly.
   ``They (the authorities) came in and were going to remove them
from their homes at gunpoint. Oh yes, absolutely, at gunpoint if
necessary,'' Kirby said. ``Montana law, to my knowledge, does not
allow for that. I know they've looked for me quite a lot. I just
haven't been available.''
   In nearby Cooke City, Phyllis and Bernie Kiley have been able to
stay to run their store, the Yellowstone Trading Post.
   The Kileys could lose everything they've worked for the past 17
years if the Storm Creek fire hits them. Their investment in the
trading post is about $250,000, and their adjoining home is worth
about $100,000. Their fire insurance won't come close to covering
the losses, they say.
   ``I guess we're naive,'' Mrs. Kiley said. ``The park
(Yellowstone) wouldn't let us burn because they put us in this
situation. Besides, we couldn't pack it all up and take it.''
</TEXT>
