<1ST_LINE>u p AM-DukakisBlues 1stLd-Writethru a0554 09-10 0895</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis Blues, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0554,850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Supporters Glad He's Finally Getting Tough With Bush</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS new graf after pvs 6th graf bgng, Dukakis plans, with
new comments on Bush.</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   By WILLIAM M. WELCH=
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With a few phrases under a hot East Texas sun,
Michael Dukakis displayed the combative, aggressive stance that
worried supporters have been beseeching him to display in his
lagging campaign against Republican George Bush.
   At the end of a week filled with calamities and plummeting
polls, the Democratic presidential nominee took on Bush in his
strongest language yet.
   Dukakis compared Bush's attacks, suggesting that he was short on
patriotism and soft on crime, to McCarthyism of the 1950s, and said
the American people could ``smell the garbage.''
   ``He finally went ahead and said what we all feel,'' said Ann
Richards, the blunt-spoken Texas state treasurer and Democratic
convention keynoter. ``You can be statesmanlike only so long, when
a schoolyard bully is pushing everybody around.''
   Campaign aides want Dukakis to keep up his tough talk about Bush
this week while he attempts to follow another piece of their advice
_ to add more specifics to his rhetoric.
   Dukakis plans to outline in greater detail his views on defense
and national security during appearances this week, including one
in Annapolis, Md., where he had sought but failed to win the vice
president's agreement for a foreign policy debate.
   The Massachusetts governor kept up the attack Saturday,
questioning the vice president's judgment in having three senior
advisers who are partners in a Washington lobbying firm that once
represented the Bahamas government for an $800,000 fee. ``In a
Dukakis White House, there will be no back doors for foreign
lobbyists,'' he said.
   Dukakis got an enthusiastic reception at a rally in Commerce,
Texas, on Friday with his tough new response to Bush. Campaign
aides saw the speech as an important move toward lifting Dukakis
out of his perceived slump.
   Dukakis himself was visibly changed after the speech, shedding
his reserved demeanor and draping his arm around a reporter.
   His campaign managers' discomfort over Dukakis' slide in the
polls since the Democratic convention in mid-July has been worsened
by a frustrating campaign kickoff week in which events were
disrupted or canceled, partly because of problems with chartered
planes.
   Democrats voiced alarm at seeing Dukakis drop from a lead of 17
percentage points in post-convention polls to an eight-point
deficit after Labor Day.
   Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., told The New York Times the Dukakis
campaign had only two weeks to turn things around.
   Democratic Sen. Tom Harkin of Iowa said an overly cautious
strategy of ignoring attacks by Bush caused the decline.
   ``A president has to be an aggressive person,'' Harkin said.
``It's not the kind of world where you want a Caspar Milquetoast in
the White House.''
   Mrs. Richards privately urged Dukakis to move swiftly to try to
regain the offensive.
   ``I talked to him a lot, and I told him, `you don't have to take
that kind of garbage','' she said. ``I think he had to respond.''
   Bush has dominated the presidential campaign since his
nomination in mid-August by carefully selecting and timing his
easily understood attacks on Dukakis' record.
   The vice president seemed to be casting doubt on Dukakis'
patriotism, while denying he was doing so, by making an issue of
the Massachusetts governor's veto of a bill aimed at requiring
public school teachers to lead their classes in reciting the Pledge
of Allegiance. Dukakis said he was advised that the bill was
unconsititutional.
   Dukakis press secretary Dayton Duncan said the governor had
written much of the Texas speech himself. Campaign chairman Paul
Brountas said Dukakis was angered by a pair of news stories during
the week.
   In one, members of a Bush booster organization were disclosed to
have voiced anti-Semitic views. In the other, a lobbying firm
associated with Bush's campaign manager had received $800,000 for
lobbying on behalf of a foreign official involved in a drug
investigation.
   ``He read that and said, `These people are questioning MY
patriotism,'' Brountas said.
   ``He was outraged,'' Duncan said.
   The new conviction behind Dukakis' assault on Bush coincided
with the return of his former campaign manager, John Sasso, who has
a close relationship with the candidate and was warmly welcomed by
other campaign staffers.
   Dukakis' formal campaign kickoff began on a dismal note.
   When he appeared in a Philadelphia neighborhood early Labor Day
morning, anti-abortion protesters clogged one end of the street and
their chants reverberated down the block. A faulty sound system
left Dukakis' words unintelligible. Campaign sources said an
advance man was fired.
   A day later in Chicago, Dukakis' speech was disrupted by
anti-abortion hecklers who determinedly tried to shout him down.
   Things got worse. Dukakis' campaign jet plane was effectively
grounded by a Federal Aviation Administration spot inspection which
began 15 minutes before the scheduled takeoff. The rest of the day
was lost. Press briefings were set up on the run, and contradictory
answers were given to reporters.
   Arriving in Baltimore for a welcome by Maryland Gov. William
Donald Schaefer, the Democratic nominee found there was no ramp at
the front of the plane.
   Nonetheless, Brountas told reporters Friday morning that the
week was ``tops'' for Dukakis. Later in the day, he repeated his
declaration and added, ``Now I can say that with more conviction.''
</TEXT>
