<FILEID>AP-NR-09-10-88 1659EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PresidentialYacht     09-10 0462</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Presidential Yacht,0474</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Presidential Yacht Comes To Boston</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IAN DONNIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fancied by Herbert Hoover, sold by Jimmy Carter
and ignored by Ronald Reagan, the presidential yacht Sequoia is on
the last leg of a 120-city fund-raising tour before it is returned
to White House control.
   The Sequoia was bought by the Commerce Department from a
Philadelphia family in 1929. After Hoover wintered on the boat in
Florida in 1933, it was acquired by the Navy and declared the
official presidential yacht.
   The 105-foot vessel served eight presidents over a period of 44
years before Carter ordered the ship sold at auction in 1977 as an
austerity move.
   ``The Sequoia is really a symbol of the presidency in the 20th
century,'' said J. Michael McGehee, spokesman for The Presidential
Yacht Trust, the private group that bought the ship and began
restoring it in 1981.
   Franklin D. Roosevelt planned war strategy from the ship, Harry
Truman used it for the first international conference on nuclear
arms control and Richard Nixon held working sessions with the likes
of Soviet leader Leonid Brezhnev on board, McGehee said.
   The ship was open for public visits over the weekend at the
Charlestown Navy Yard in Boston. It will make more stops along the
Atlantic Coast before it is donated to the Navy on Nov. 15 and
again becomes the presidential yacht.
   The fund-raising voyage has raised $5.5 million, half the $11
million needed for restoration costs and to create an endowment for
future maintenance and operations without taxpayer expense, he said.
   But McGehee said Reagan has failed to stamp his imprimatur on
the project.
   ``This is the ultimate private sector project,'' he said. ``One
would think Ronald Reagan would be willing to hold this up and say,
`This is what I've been talking about.' ''
   Lyndon Johnson used the lure of an afternoon cruise on the ship
to entangle legislators in marathon discussions and hold them
hostage until they came around to his point of view, McGehee said.
   ``We've had some funny stories about senators and congressmen
telling the captain to turn the boat around and go back to dock.
The captain would say he could only listen to his
commander-in-chief.''
   Nixon enjoyed taking cruises on the Potomac in the Sequoia and
announced his decision to resign the presidency to his family
aboard the ship.
   A joint congressional resolution in 1985 provided for the
Sequoia's eventual return, and the ship was designated a National
Historic Landmark earlier this year.
   McGehee said the Presidential Yacht Trust has spent $3.5 million
restoring teak paneling, bleached ash interiors, handmade carpets,
engines and other details. The ship was built for $210,000, but to
build it now would cost between $8 million and $10 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880910-0123 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-10-88 1710EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-JetlinerMystery     09-10 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jetliner Mystery,0313</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newspaper Says Investigation Shows Jetliner Hit By Missile</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILAN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Experts have concluded that an Italian
jetliner which mysteriously crashed into a sea eight years ago,
killing all 81 people on board, was shot down by missile, a
newspaper reported.
   British and American experts have been analyzing the recently
salvaged wreckage of the DC-9, which exploded and crashed into the
Tyrrhenian Sea on June 27, 1980.
   The Italian government financed a salvage operation to raise the
fuselage so experts could determine the cause of the disaster.
   The Milan newspaper Corriere della Sera said that British
explosives experts and American engineers at McDonnell Douglas
Corp., the jetliner's manufacturer, have determined the plane was
downed by a missile.
   The paper said the missile exploded seconds before it would have
struck the jetliner. It said the blast destroyed the cockpit,
killed the flight crew, damaged the baggage compartment door on the
right, scorched the outside of the plane and punched three
grapefruit-size holes in the fuselage.
   The same newspaper reported in June that experts were certain
the airliner had been hit by a missile. But a member of the
investigating commission later denied it had reached any
conclusions.
   Corriere della Sera said on Friday that the experts completed
their investigation Thursday and that the results were being
forwarded to Judge Vittorio Bucarelli, who is in charged of the
inquiry.
   The newspaper said the voice recorder on the flight picked up an
undecipherable shout just before the explosion.
   It also said the British experts are still trying to determine
the chemical composition of the explosive as a way to trace the
nationality of the missile.
   The plane was on a flight from Bologna to Palermo, Sicily. It
crashed in the sea 30 miles southwest of Naples, between the
islands of Ponza and Ustica.
</TEXT>
