<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MissFirefighters     09-10 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Miss Firefighters,0287</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mississippi Firefighters Home From Yellowstone Blazes</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Forest Fires Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thirty-four weary Mississippi firefighters
have returned home to rest after ``scary ... but exciting'' work
fighting forest fires in Yellowstone National Park.
   ``I want to go home, take a bath, clean up and see my family I
hadn't seen in 25 days,'' said Mike Melton, 38, of Forest, when
they arrived Friday night.
   Sonja Durrwachter, 29, of Wiggins said she was looking forward
to ``a hot bath and hugging my babies.''
   ``We put in a lot of long hours,'' Durrwachter said. ``We got to
see a lot of fire. We got a lot of experience on fires we don't get
around here. It was scary, but it was real exciting.''
   Crew members averaged 15 hours per day, sometimes working as
long as 19 hours, said crew boss Tony Wilder, 37, of Starkville.
   ``We defended structures around the canyons and the flames that
hit us were 200 feet high. We were in hazard situations most of the
time we were there. It was insane,'' Wilder said.
   ``You could hear the fire coming an hour before it got there,''
Wilder said.
   The Mississippi crew was part of the team that tried to protect
the Old Faithful geyser complex, he said, but the fire ran away
from them and destroyed several buildings.
   Firefighters also had to contend with stubborn animals.
   ``The wildlife offered not only a challenge but a hazard to work
around,'' Wilder said, saying a buffalo wouldn't allow them to
approach one area they wanted to hose down. ``We saw a lot of fresh
bear signs. That was a constant concern.''
</TEXT>
