<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Argentina-Strike     09-10 0444</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Argentina-Strike,0460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Labor Rejects Appeal To Call Off General Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM H. HEATH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's largest labor
federation on Saturday rejected a government appeal to call off
another general strike and said the work stoppage will be held to
protest police repression.
   The General Labor Confederation said its unions will hold a
24-hour nationwide strike on Monday.
   It had organized an 8-hour general strike Friday to protest the
gpvernment's economic policies and police used tear gas, rubber
bullets and clubs to disperse about 20,000 demonstrators at a rally
in downtown Buenos Aires.
   ``The Monday strike is unchangeable and there will be no
modification,'' Saul Ubaldini, secretary-general of the labor
federation, told reporters as he arrived at a union meeting to
discuss Friday's violence.
   He said Monday's strike would be ``a peaceful repudiation'' of
police actions Friday.
   Federal police said Saturday that 76 demonstrators and 37
policemen were injured during the disturbances in the Plaza de
Mayo. They reported four civilians and eight policemen were
hospitalized for fractures and cuts.
   Thirteen demonstrators were arrested and face charges of
assault, resisting arrest, arson and vandalism, according to the
report.
   The Interior Ministry had appealed to the labor federation to
reconsider its call for a Monday strike. It said police intervened
in the Buenos Aires rally to halt vandalism and fighting between
rival union groups.
   But Ubdaldini said, ``It's a lie that the incidents began among
participants of the rally.''
   Interior Minister Enrique Nosiglia issued a communique saying
violence ``can only benefit small anti-democratic sectors.''
   ``Nothing can justify a new paralyzation of the country that
will only postpone progress without providing any benefit for
rights and freedoms,'' it said.
   Monday's strike will be the 13th organized by the General Labor
Confederation since the elected government of President Raul
Alfonsin and his centrist Radical Civic Union came to power Dec.
10, 1983, ending nearly eight years of military rule. The labor
federation is dominated by the opposition Peronist Party.
   Both Nosiglia and Federal Police Chief Juan Pirker rejected
union charges of police brutality and blamed agitators for the
violence.
   Ubaldini, who fled the platform at the Plaza de Maya rally
Friday in a cloud of tear gas, had described the strike as ``a
peoples' referendum against the plan of hunger and misery that they
(the government) want to impose on us.''
   He referred to an anti-inflation plan introduced by the
government last month that devalued the currency, lifted
restrictions on some imports and called for voluntary wage and
price controls.
   Inflation has registered 255 percent so far this this year and
440 percent during the past 12 months.
</TEXT>
