<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BRF--InVitroReunion     09-10 0150</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--In Vitro Reunion,0152</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>About 100 Test-Tube Babies Participate in In Vitro Reunion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOWSON, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 100 babies born through in vitro
fertilization techniques at Greater Baltimore Medical Center,
including triplets, returned to the hospital for a reunion Saturday.
   Dr. Theodore Baramki, head of the Division of Reproductive
Endocrinology, said the so-called test-tube program can be credited
with the births of 136 babies _ 74 boys and 62 girls _ since it
began in 1985.
   The program is one of 169 in the country, according to hospital
spokeswoman Vivienne Stearns-Elliott.
   Ms. Stearns-Elliott says 10 mothers enrolled in the program
currently are awaiting the births of triplets as well.
   In vitro fertilization involves stimulating the woman's ovaries
with hormones so she produces more than one egg. Those eggs are
retrieved and combined with sperm in a laboratory dish. The
fertilized eggs then are implanted in the woman's uterus.
</TEXT>
