<DOCNO> AP880910-0127 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-10-88 1730EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ContaminatedMarsh     09-10 0412</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Contaminated Marsh,0422</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Discovery Of Mercury Could Threaten Plans For New Wildlife Refuge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The discovery of mercury in freshwater
marshes in eastern New Orleans has complicated plans to turn the
area into the Bayou Sauvage National Wildlife Refuge.
   The U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service told city and state officials
Thursday that they discovered quantities of mercury well above
federal health levels near a landfill that has a history of leaking
into the surrounding marshes.
   The city-owned Recovery I landfill is operated by Waste
Management Inc., and a company spokesman denied the landfill was
the source of the mercury contamination.
   The Fish and Wildlife report said it found only mercury, not
pesticides or petroleum hydrocarbons. The report said additional
samples have been taken to confirm the mercury findings, and those
results should be available in October.
   Officials said the mercury contamination poses no immediate
health hazard. The marshland near the landfill is not used for
commercial fishing or hunting, and since mercury is a heavy metal,
it tends to sink and combine with sediment at the bottom of the
marsh.
   Wildlife Service officials already were concerned that about
1,500 acres of marshland near the landfill was depleted of oxygen,
a symptom of chemical and biological contaminants, and was not
supporting wildlife.
   City officials had been negotiating with federal officials to
see if an airport could be constructed near the proposed refuge.
The questions raised by the Wildlife Service test results will slow
down those negotiations, city officials said.
   City officials said they aren't convinced the landfill is the
source of the contamination, and suggested the mercury might be
from a spill from railroad tank cars on tracks that cut across the
property. No such spill has been reported.
   Planning Commission Director Bob Becker said city consultants
also don't understand why the test results turned up no other
contaminants, when a mixture of contaminants would be more likely
to escape from a landfill.
   State Department of Environmental Quality officials said they
will review the Recovery I operating permit, which expires Oct. 17.
   City officials have notified the state that they don't plan to
renew Waste Management's contract to operate the facility, although
Waste Management requested a 10-year extension of its state permit
last year.
   The city wants to put operation of the landfill out to bid, and
has asked the state for a seven-year grace period to continue to
dispose household garbage in the landfill before shutting it down.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880910-0128 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-10-88 1733EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis 1st-LdWritethru a0577 09-10 0871</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 1st-Ld Writethru, a0577,820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Steps Up Attack On Bush With Assault On Aides' Ties To
Bahamas</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Inserts new graf after pvs 11th graf bgng ``Jerome Brentar
...'' with comment from Rep. Schumer on other members of Bush's
Nationalities panel</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis lashed out anew at George Bush's
judgment and leadership Saturday, accusing the vice president of
associating with aides who helped the Bahamian government when it
was under drug investigation and others reported to be sympathetic
to Nazis.
   ``My staff will not have divided loyalties,'' the Democratic
presidential nominee said. ``In a Dukakis White House, the staff
will pledge allegiance to only one flag _ Old Glory.''
   Dukakis, spending the weekend off the campaign trail, gave
reporters copies of a memorandum from a Washington lobbying firm
with which several top Bush advisers are associated.
   In the memo, the firm of Black, Manafort & Stone promised to
improve the image of the government of the Bahamas among Reagan
administration officials and Congress.
   The Bahamian government accepted the proposal and paid the
Republican lobbying firm $800,000 between April 1985 and September
1986. The Bahamian prime minister, Lynden O. Pindling, long has
been suspected of involvement with drug traffickers.
   The lobbying firm's memo boasted of the company's influence
within the administration and listed more than a dozen contacts
with Bush's office.
   Three Bush aides and advisers are partners in the firm. They are
Charles R. Black, Paul J. Manafort and Roger J. Stone. All have
strong ties to the Reagan White House in addition to their campaign
roles. Bush campaign manager Lee Atwater also is listed on the
memo, but Bush campaign spokesman Mark Goodin said Atwater had no
role in the contract.
   ``The measure of a president is the quality and the integrity of
the people with whom he surrounds himself,'' Dukakis told a
statehouse news conference.
   ``The American people have the right to know that the back door
of the White House will not be the front door for paid agents of
foreign governments. In a Dukakis White House there will be no back
doors for foreign lobbyists.''
   The Massachusetts governor said Bush's association with the
Black, Manafort & Stone partners and with campaign aides who have
defended Nazis and Nazi organizations ``raises serious questions
about Mr. Bush's judgment and the kind of people he attracts.''
   Jerome Brentar, co-chairman of The Bush '88 Coalition of
American Nationalities, was a defender of former Ohio autoworker
John Demjanjuk, who was convicted in Israel as a Nazi war criminal.
Brentar resigned under fire.
   ``But Florian Galdau and Philip Guarino (respectively honorary
chairman and vice chairman of the panel) stay on -- despite
revelations of their ties to fascist, pro-Nazi and anti-Semitic
organizations,'' said Rep. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., on Saturday,
calling for the two to resign.
   The Philadephia Inquirer reported Saturday that several other
Bush campaign officials have supported Nazis.
   ``I think it says a great deal about that campaign,'' Dukakis
said. ``It says a great deal about the judgment of Mr. Bush.''
   Dukakis used the ``pledge allegiance to only one flag'' line to
counter Bush's attacks on Dukakis for his 1977 veto of a bill aimed
at requiring state public school teachers to lead pupils in
reciting the Pledge of Allegiance. Dukakis had been advised the
bill was unconstitutional.
   The House rejected a Republican proposal Friday that each day's
session in that chamber begin not only with a prayer but with the
Pledge of Allegiance, but Speaker Jim Wright said the pledge would
be recited on two mornings next week.
   Dukakis said he had no objection if Congress decided to start
each legislative day with the pledge. He then quickly cited Bush's
official duty as president of the Senate, and said:
   ``To the best of my knowledge he's never once suggested that the
pledge be part of the regular routine of the Senate. So who's
kidding whom?''
   On Friday, Dukakis likened the Republican attacks on him to
McCarthyism of the 1950s. He stopped short of directly accusing
Bush of such tactics Saturday, but criticized him for not
condemning several unsubstantiated attacks on Dukakis, his wife and
Democratic vice presidential nominee Lloyd Bentsen.
   ``Remaining silent, in my judgment, is not the way you take
responsibility and provide leadership,'' the governor said.
   Dukakis planned to meet Saturday night and Sunday with several
Democratic members of Congress who are experts in national security
and defense matters, including Sens. Sam Nunn of Georgia and John
Glenn of Ohio and Rep. Les Aspin of Wisconsin.
   Those sessions were to help prepare Dukakis to outline his
positions in detail next week on those issues. Republicans have
labeled Dukakis weak and naive in those areas.
   ``I happen to think Mr. Bush is very vulnerable on foreign
policy and national security issues,'' Dukakis said Saturday.
   ``It's a question of judgment, questions of support for
Iran-Contra, Latin-American policy which is failed and illegal,
statements made, failure of execution, a whole series of task
forces which the vice president has been in charge of which have
been absolute failures,'' he said.
   ``I think it's time now that the American people take a good,
hard look at his record.''
</TEXT>
