<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     09-10 0461</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0471</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leftovers Of Hurricane Spread Heavy Rain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The remains of hurricane Florence spread heavy rain over the
South on Saturday, and a cold front ushered cool air and showers
southward along the Rockies.
   The center of what was left of Florence was over southwestern
Mississippi drifting slowly towards the northwest, spreading
showers and thunderstorms over Mississippi, Louisiana, Alabama and
northwestern Florida.
   A band of thunderstorms from the storm's remains produced heavy
rain and severe weather over northwestern Florida and southern
Alabama. A tornado touched down near Freeport, Fla., in Walton
County, damaging some mobile homes, the National Weather Service
said, and some bridges in Florida's Santa Rosa County were under
water.
   Rainfall totals over southern Alabama ranged from 2 to 6 inches,
with more than 3.50 inches at Montgomery in 24 hours.
   Tropical storm Gilbert was located in the eastern Caribbean
about 400 miles southeast of Santo Domingo, Dominican Republic. It
was expected to strengthen and move westward Sunday.
   A cold front pushed across the northern Rockies and the area to
the west, marking the leading edge of cooler air with showers and
thunderstorms. Showers and thunderstorms were widely scattered over
southwestern Montana and western Wyoming, an earea of severe forest
fires. It was expected to push across sections of Nevada and Utah
and drop temperatures 15 to 20 degrees below normal for this time
of year.
   Other showers and thunderstorms were scattered over the Florida
Peninsula, South Carolina and Georgia. Thunderstorms also developed
over western North Dakota.
   Mary Esther, Fla., got 1.36 inches of rain in the six hours up
to 2 p.m. EDT.
   Orlando, Fla., posted a record high temperature for the date at
96 degrees.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 44
degrees at Pullman, Wash., to 103 at Palm Springs, Calif. Saturday
morning's low was 31 at Warroad, Minn.
   For Sunday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast
over the Tennessee Valley, the lower Ohio Valley, most of Illinois,
southeastern Missouri, and northern sections of the lower
Mississippi Valley. A cold front was forecast to spread showers and
some thunderstorms over the northern Plains, the northern Rockies,
and northern sections of the central Rockies. Scattered
thunderstorms were forecast over the southern half of Florida.
   Highs in the 40s and 50s were predicted in Montana and
northwestern Wyoming; in the 60s in western sections of the
northern Plains, central Wyoming, most of Idaho and the northern
half of New England; in the 90s in Florida, southern Alabama and
Georgia, the southern Plains, most of Kansas, the southern Rockies,
parts of the Southwest and the inland valleys of California;
between 100 and 105 over the desert Southwest; and in the 70s and
80s over the remainder of the nation.
</TEXT>
