<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Perry'sFlagship     09-10 0436</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Perry's Flagship,0447</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Perry's Flagship Launched 175 Years After His Victory</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ERIE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Commodore Oliver Hazard Perry's brigantine
Niagara returned to the Great Lakes on Saturday, exactly 175 years
after his fleet defeated the British in the Battle of Lake Erie.
   ``We are starting a new page in Pennsylvania's history, and you
all are a part of it,'' Gov. Robert Casey told an estimated 5,000
people gathered for the launching ceremony.
   Casey's wife, Ellen, lifted a bottle of Erie County wine and
struck the 182-foot, 278-ton restored ship, bedecked with the
American flag and Perry's battle flag, ``Don't Give Up the Ship.''
The bottle didn't break, however, and she had to strike the ship
again, this time successfully.
   Shortly afterward, a crane lifted the ship into Lake Erie's
Presque Isle Bay. Eighteen cannons fired a military salute, and
more than 200 private boats anchored in the bay to watch the
festivities blared their horns.
   It was the fourth time the ship had been restored, this time
using $3.8 million in state and private funds.
   The restored Niagara will be outfitted by next spring with
118-foot and 113-foot masts, square rigging, about 22,000 square
feet of polyester sail and 20 aluminum cannon.
   It will then tour the Great Lakes and East Coast ports as
Pennsylvania's ``official flagship.''
   The first USS Niagara was one of six small ships built in this
port city during the War of 1812 and put under Perry's command to
break a British blockade of American Great Lakes ports and to
defend the Northwest Territory.
   On Sept. 10, 1813, Perry's nine-ship squadron met six British
vessels under Commodore Robert Heriot Barclay in a short but fierce
battle near Put-in-Bay, Ohio.
   Perry's flagship, the USS Lawrence, was disabled by British
fire. Perry transferred to the Niagara, where he hoisted his famous
battle flag, ``Don't Give up the Ship,'' and attacked again. The
Niagara helped break the British battle line and forced Barclay to
surrender.
   ``We have met the enemy and they are ours: two ships, two brigs,
one schooner and one sloop,'' Perry reported to his superiors.
   The Niagara served as a station ship in Erie until 1820, when it
was scuttled in nearby Misery Bay. The ship was raised by Erie
citizens in 1913 and restored for a Great Lakes tour to celebrate
the 100th anniversary of Perry's victory. The ship was restored
again in the 1930s and 1940s.
   In the latest restoration, Melbourne Smith, an Annapolis, Md.,
marine architect, dismantled the Niagara and rebuilt it to
historical specifications. Forty-two pieces of the original ship
are incorporated in the restored brigantine.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
