<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DwarfToss     09-10 0392</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dwarf Toss,0405</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dwarf Loves Being Tossed Around, Ignores Criticism From Other
Little People</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GAINESVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   David Wilson loves getting thrown
around in dwarf-tossing contests, and shrugs off bitter criticisms
of the practice by associations for little people.
   ``I think it's a lot of fun,'' said the 4-foot-5 human
projectile. ``If Eddie Murphy can make fun of being black, if Dom
DeLuise can make fun of being fat, why not me? Why can't I make fun
of being short?
   ``I'm into it. I'm an entertainer.''
   He also works as a welder and circus entertainer. ``I eat fire,
eat nails, walk on broken glass,'' he said.
   Wilson, 27, is next slated for a show Sept. 13-15 at a downtown
bar, Animal House, with a $1,000 prize for the winner.
   Wilson, who'll be wearing a crash helmet, knee pads and a
harness for contestants to grab, says he'll be rooting for
participants to outdistance the 7-feet, 8-inch distance he was
tossed in a Bradenton bar last summer.
   Dwarfism groups hate the idea.
   ``From the standpoint of little people, it's demeaning,'' said
Robert Van Etten, former president of Little People of America,
which represents about 4,000 dwarfs.
   ``It's mean-spirited. It moves us back to the Dark Ages. It's
poking fun at a minority group,'' said Van Etten, noting that
public outcry helped kill plans for a dwarf-throwing contest in
Chicago in 1985.
   Manatee County Commissioners didn't like the Bradenton dwarf
toss, but couldn't find a law under which they could ban it.
   ``I think we all pretty much felt like it was low-level type of
entertainment,'' said commission Chairman Kent Chetlain. ``It's
like somebody capitalizing on someone's disfigurement or
infirmity.''
   Animal House publicist Richard Levy brushed off such
contentions, saying the contest is fun, attracts customers and is
certain to generate publicity for the bar.
   And Wilson said he makes good money being tossed.
   Dwarf-tossing began as a bar stunt in Queensland, Australia,
said Van Etten's wife Angela, author of ``Dwarfs Don't Live in Doll
Houses.''
   ``It is actually freak show entertainment, the sort of thing you
saw in the 1930s,'' she said. ``The problem with freak show
entertainment is it sets the dwarf apart as something to be stared
out and made fun of, which makes it difficult for the rest of us,
who aren't participating, to be treated as equal.''
</TEXT>
