<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Poland 1stLd-Writethru a0558 09-10 0824</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0558,0848</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Polish Opposition Convenes Before Round-Table Talks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 17 grafs to UPDATE with Solidarity statement;
picks up 8th pvs: Among the...; Deletes last five grafs and edits
throughout to tighten</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GDANSK, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lech Walesa and other Solidarity leaders
Saturday demanded an end to government reprisals against workers
who went on strike and said authorities should be prepared to
consider legalizing the labor group.
   Walesa, key Solidary advisers and other activists gathered in a
Roman Catholic Church to plan their strategy for talks with
authorities on the future of the outlawed labor movement.
   They issued a statement late Saturday saying they wanted
confirmation that authorities are prepared to ``create conditions''
for legalizing Solidarity, which was suspended in 1981 and
subsequently outlawed.
   The weekend conference is one of the largest gatherings of the
Polish opposition in years.
   The meeting Saturday included Solidarity regional leaders and
strike committee members, and a gathering Sunday is to include
intellectuals and cultural figures who advise Solidarity founder
Walesa.
   The group is meeting to discuss the communist government's offer
to enter negotiations. On Aug. 31, authorities agreed to open talks
and Walesa agreed to end a 19-day wave of strikes.
   Andrzej Stelmachowski, a Roman Catholic intellectual acting as a
mediator between the governent and opposition, said he expected the
gpvermment-Solidarity talks would begin in the middle of the week.
Diplomatic sources said they were told the meeting would begin
Sept. 15.
   At the end of Saturday's meeting the Solidarity leadership
released a statement saying: ``We expect a clear expression by the
Polish authorities of readiness to create conditions for legal
functioning of Solidarity.
   ``Only the legalization of Solidarity allows the effective
participation of the union in reforming the country.''
   The statement also demanded an end to reprisals against workers
who had participated in strikes.
   Actions such as detentions, firings and induction of strike
participants into the military ``impair the credibility of the
authorities' proposals,'' it said. ``We expect an immediate end to
repressions.''
   Union activists have reported about 350 miners were fired
following strikes in the coal region of southern poland and dozens
of other workers received army draft notices.
   Solidarity sources, speaking with the condition of anonymity,
said the statement should not be considered an ultimatum and the
round-table talks could begin even without official gestures.
   Tadeusz Mazowiecki, an adviser to Walesa, said Solidarity wanted
a signal from authorities that the talks could be held ``in serious
conditions with a chance for success.''
   Mazowiecki said Walesa and representatives of four regional
strike committees would represent Solidarity at the talks with the
government.
   Saturday's meeting was held at St. Brygida's church near the
Lenin shipyard where Solidarity was born in 1980 amid nationwide
strikes and became the first free trade union in the Soviet bloc.
   Attending the meeting were the 15-member national executive
commission of Solidarity, representatives of strike committees
during the Aug. 16-Sept. 3 wave of strikes and members of the
interfactory strike committees.
   Among the 40 participants were solidarity advisers such as Jacek
Kuron, Adam Michnik and Zbigniew Romaszewski who monitor human
rights abuses.
   Nearby in another church, leaders of the banned Independent
Students Association met and drafted a statement in support of
Solidarity.
   ``I'm surprised by the way these people are prepared,'' Walesa
said during a break in the session.
   ``There are a lot of fighting people who I expected to represent
their fighting manner. And I am surprised by their great feeling of
responsibility and great wisdom, especially among the young
people.''
   Solidarity is seeking to win back the legal status it lost
following Polish leader Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski's Dec. 13, 1981,
martial-law crackdown.
   Government spokesman Jerzy Urban and Politburo member Alfred
Miodowicz, leader of the officially sanctioned trade union OPZZ,
last week reiterated the official stand that Solidarity cannot be
legalized again as a trade federation. But Urban also said
officials were entering the talks with no preconditions.
   Opposition spokesmen said they insist on the legalization of the
union, and they want the issue settled before they will engage in
talks on the broad range of political and economic problems.
   The talks to discuss workers' grievances were proposed by
Interior Minister Gen. Czeslaw Kiszczak during the August strikes,
Poland's worst wave of labor unrest since 1981.
   When Kiszczak and Walesa met Aug. 31 they agreed that the talks
could include discussing the future of Solidarity. Walesa then
appealed to his supporters for a speedy end to the remaining
strikes so the talks could convene.
   Col. Stanislaw Kwiatkowski, the chief government pollster, said
the authorities have no one to blame but themselves for being
forced back into talks with Walesa and Solidarity.
   ``Briefly stated, it is the sluggishness of the party and the
government which are to blame for the rebirth of Solidarity, whose
cadres have begun to count again in the political game,''
Kwiatkowski said in the Warsaw daily Zycie Warszawy.
</TEXT>
