<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel-Stern 1stLd-Writethru   09-10 0684</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Stern, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0590,0701</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Former Stern Group Members Say They Helped Kill UN Envoy</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 7th graf, The organization...' to CORRECT when group
disbanded to four months, sted six months before killing; picks up
8th graf: Although members...; SUBS 18th graf, `Makover was ...' to
restore dropped first reference to Cohen; picks up 19th pvs: The
assassination...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two former guerrillas of an underground Jewish
group once led by Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir said they helped
assassinate a Swedish U.N. envoy to Palestine 40 years ago,
according to a television program.
   It was the first time that members of the Stern Group
acknowledged they were involved in the killing of Count Folke
Bernadotte, Israel's state-run Educational Television said.
   The militant group, also known as Israel Freedom Fighters, was
initially headed by Avraham Stern. It was a splinter faction of the
right-wing National Military Organization.
   The faction, which carried out terrorist acts to undermine
British rule in mandatory Palestine, opposed Bernadotte's proposals
that the United Nations be given control over Jerusalem and key
areas be returned to Arab jurisdiction.
   In 1942, after British police fatally shot Stern, the group was
led by Shamir, Natan Yellin-Mor and Yisrael Scheib-Eldad, the
group's ideologist.
   In interviews for Educational Television aired Friday, two
former members of the group said that Yellin-Mor and Scheib-Eldad
approved the assassination.
   The organization officially disbanded about four months before
the killing, and Shamir had no connection with the assassination,
said his spokesman Yossi Ahimeir.
   Although members of the group may have been involved, Ahimeir
said, ``There was no organization at the time, and Shamir was not a
commander.''
   Asked about Shamir's response to the TV report, Ahimeir said the
prime minister ``is dealing with the issues of present and future
and not with the distant past.''
   The issue was not expected to have any effect on upcoming
elections. Israelis have believed for years that the Stern Group
was behind the killing.
   Journalist Dan Margalit interviewed Yehoshua Zetler and Meshulam
Makover, who he said were the mastermind and the driver in
Bernadotte's killing.
   Margalit quoted Zetler as saying he decided to kill Bernadotte,
president of the Swedish Red Cross during and after World War II,
after the envoy proposed the formation of a union of an Arab and a
Jewish state.
   Bernadotte was appointed in May 1948 to negotiate a cease-fire
and recommend a settlement in Israel's 1948 War of Independence.
   ``Zetler said he conferred with Eldad, and the two traveled to
Haifa to discuss it with Yellin-Mor. Yellin-Mor demanded that after
the killing, the (Israel Freedom Fighters) deny its role and blame
the slaying on a tiny group of zealots called The Homeland Front,''
Margalit said.
   Scheib-Eldad, now an elderly philosophy lecturer living in
Jerusalem, said in a telephone interview he could not comment
because Zetler and Makover ``were talking about the operational
side, and I was the ideologist. I have no way of knowing if their
account is correct.''
   The television program quoted Makover as saying the guerrillas
arrived in two cars to the spot selected by Zetler for the Sept.
17, 1948, killing in downtown Jerusalem.
   When the three-car U.N. convoy approached the narrow street, the
jeep blocked its way and three guerrillas jumped outside, with
Makover staying behind the wheel, it said.
   Makover was quoted as saying guerrilla Yehoshua Cohen fired the
shots that killed Bernadotte.
   The assassination was widely blamed on the Israel Freedom
Fighters, and the Israeli government launched a nationwide hunt for
its members. About 400 people, including Yellin-Mor were arrested,
but the killers were never found.
   Scheib-Eldad said most of those detained were released, but some
faced trial for membership in an illegal organization.
   The organization was disbanded in May 1948 and most of the
members joined the Israeli army, but it preserved a separate status
in Jerusalem until it was outlawed after Bernadotte's assassination
in September.
   Yellin-Mor and Matitiyahu Shmulevitch, also a group member, were
sentenced to short jail terms and pardoned when the first Knesset,
or Parliament, convened in 1949, Scheib-Eldad said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
