<1ST_LINE>u i AM-GulfTalks 1stLd-Writethru a0574 09-10 0501</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Talks, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0574,0512</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran And Iraq Meet For First Time In More Than Two Weeks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with three grafs to UPDATE with talks ending for night;
picks up 4th pvs: As at...; ADDS three grafs with comments from
non-aligned meeting in Nicosia</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TONY CZUCZKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The foreign ministers of Iran and Iraq met
Saturday for their first face-to-face peace talks in more than two
weeks.
   But talks were halted after less than four hours, suggesting an
impasse over Iraq's refusal to move the negotiations to New York
and Iran's support of a recess and change of location.
   U.N. officials said the negotiations would resume on Sunday.
   Foreign Minister Tariq Aziz led the Iraqi delegation to the
meeting at the U.N. office in Geneva. The Iranians, headed by
Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati, came less than five minutes
later.
   As at their previous full meetings in Geneva, the two
delegations sat down at separate tables about 30 feet apart in the
Council Chamber of the U.N. building. The mediator, Jan Eliasson,
was seated at his own table at the head of the triangular
arrangement.
   Saturday's session was the first direct session at ministerial
level since the second day of talks Aug. 26.
   Earlier, an Iraqi official was quoted as saying Baghdad refused
to suspend negotiations and move them to New York.
   Sadoon Hamadi, Iraq's Minister of State for Foreign Affairs, was
quoted in a newspaper interview as spelling out his side's
position, which clashes with Tehran's willingness to consider a
break and shift of venue.
   ``There is no justification to move the negotiations to New
York, because Iraq, Iran and the U.N. Secretary-General agreed on
Geneva as the place for these negotiations,'' Hamadi said in an
interview published Saturday in the Abu Dhabi daily Al-Ittihad.
   He said the talks are passing through a difficult stage and
accused Iran of trying to scuttle them from the start.
   The U.N. had no immediate official word on whether the latest
conflict has been resolved.
   Among Iran's priorities at the talks are a withdrawal of troops
to internationally recognized boundaries, exchange of war prisoners
and a U.N. investigation to determine who started the war.
   A long-standing dispute concerns a 1975 treaty setting the
Iran-Iraq boundary down the middle of the Shatt-al-Arab waterway.
Iraq has renounced the pact and claimed the entire waterway, but
Iran says it still considers the treaty valid.
   The waterway has been blocked by sunken ships and silt nearly
since the start of the war in September 1980.
   In Nicosia, Cyprus, the foreign ministers' conference of the
101-nation non-aligned movement called on Iraq and Iran to
cooperate in good faith with the secretary-general for full
implementation of the U.N.-sponsored cease-fire.
   Earlier, Iranian deputy Foreign Minister Mohammed Hussein
Lavasani charged Iraq was preventing progress in Geneva by raising
``extraneous issues'' in the talks.
   Iraq's deputy foreign minister, Wissam al-Zahawi, told a plenary
session Iran was ``trying to create a crisis in the negotiations.''
</TEXT>
