<1ST_LINE>u i AM-RefugeeBaseball     09-10 0458</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Refugee Baseball,0473</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Major League Baseball Teams Donate Equipment To Nicaraguan
Refugees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACALEAPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the American Stock
Exchange hurled a symbolic pitch Saturday to mark the delivery of a
shipment of baseball equipment to Nicaraguans at a refugee camp in
Honduras.
   Arthur Levitt Jr., the exchange chairman, said another shipment
will be delivered to the refugees later and a third will be given
to Hondurans.
   Baseball has been a popular Nicaraguan sport since the U.S.
military intervention in the 1920s.
   Hundreds of refugees looked wide-eyed at the bats, balls and
gloves donated by U.S. major league baseball teams and sporting
goods manufacturers.
   ``This makes me happy,'' said Sabel Correa, 28, who fled
Nicaragua six years ago and at one time was a rebel fighting the
Sandinista government. ``Baseball is important to Nicaraguans.''
   Juan Enrique Gomez, who said he left Nicaragua two years ago to
escape being drafted into the army, agreed. He said the camp at
Jacaleapa has four adult basebll teams and two junior leagues.
   ``There's not much else to do,'' he said.
   The 517 helmets, 2,400 gloves, 1,600 bats, 800 caps, 700 balls
and 500 T-shirts delivered Saturday by a U.S. military transport
plane will be shared among 13,000 Nicaraguans in three U.N.-run
refugee camps in Honduras.
   Levitt, who is co-chairman of the International Commisson for
Central American Recovery and Development, said the idea for
providing baseball equipment emerged in 1987 when he visited the
Jacaleapa camp 60 miles east of the capital of Tegucigalpa.
   ``As you can see, there are vast numbers of children here with
nothing to do,'' he said, standing amid the rows of wooden shacks
that house more than 6,000 people.
   He said he approached Baseball Commissioner Peter Ueberroth
about providing equipment and ``the response was great.''
   Levitt walked among crowds of children in tattered clothes, many
of them too young to remember their homeland. Their families fled
Nicaragua shortly after the left-wing Sandinistas ousted the
government of President Anastasio Somoza in July 1979.
   Many other refugees here crossed the border because of the
6-year-old war between the U.S.-backed rebels known as Contras and
the Sandinistas.
   Oscar Grenado, 12, said his family left Nicaragua in 1981. He
said his father and a brother were both Contra and were killed
fighting the Sandinistas. A sister and another brother are still
with the Contras, he said.
   ``I really learn baseball,'' he said quietly, adjusting his
baseball hat.
   Scores of youths took part in a training session led by Rafael
Avila, a Cuban-born scout for the Los Angeles Dodgers.
   ``I tell them I never saw a city until I was 14 and three years
later I was playing major league ball,'' Avila said.
</TEXT>
