<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PipelineBreak 1stLd-Writethru a0623 09-10 0303</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pipeline Break, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0623,0307</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands of Gallons of Oil Gush Into Streets</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs grafs 3-5 with seven grafs to UPDATE with Mobil comment.
Picks up 6th graf pvs `A police...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Up to 60,000 gallons of crude oil from a
burst underground oil line gushed down a busy suburban street into
sewers and the Los Angeles River Saturday, officials said.
   The break in the Mobil Oil Co. pipe closed Ventura Boulevard in
the Encino area and exits from the Ventura Freeway. The line broke
about 4:30 a.m. and leaked down streets in a half-mile radius, said
police Sgt. Frank Guarino.
   Mobil spokesman Jim Carbonetti said the company hired
contractors to vacuum oil off the streets into trucks, sand
oil-stained curbs and steam-clean and hose down Ventura Boulevard.
   The cause of the break was unknown, Carbonetti said. A similar
incident 2{ years ago in Granada Hills was caused by corrosion.
   An operator at Mobil's Torrance plant shut down the pipe four
minutes after a drop in pressure was noticed, he said. Automatic
controls would have shut down the pipe a few minutes later, he
added.
   The leak in the pipe, which spans 180 miles from Bellridge to
Torrance, will have no significant effect on the company's
operations, he said.
   Carbonetti said the company sent representatives through the
affected neighborhood to take damage claims from residents and
businesses.
   Six barriers were placed in the river to prevent crude oil from
reaching the ocean, he said.
   Officials did not know how much oil seeped into the river
through sewers, Fire Department spokesman Jim Williamson said.
   A police hazardous materials team notified county health
officials but determined the spill posed no danger and did not
require evacuations, Guarino said.
   Reserve and traffic officers spent the day diverting traffic.
</TEXT>
