<1ST_LINE>r a AM-EarlyActivists     09-10 0329</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Early Activists,0337</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>College Honors Civil Rights Figures at a Reunion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WILLIAMSTOWN, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Civil rights activists who worked
together in the 1960s were honored at a reunion Saturday for a
struggle that one said is ``not for one day, or one week, or one
year, but for a lifetime.''
   Rep. John Lewis, D-Ga., former chairman of the Student
Nonviolent Coordinating Committee, received an honorary doctorate
at a convocation opening Williams College's 196th academic year,
along with Rosa L. Parks, whose refusal to surrender her seat to a
white passenger on a Montgomery, Ala., bus sparked the modern civil
rights movement.
   Parks received a standing ovation from the audience of 1,000
students, faculty members and administrators.
   Others were also honored, including the Rev. Ralph D. Abernathy,
former president of the Southern Christian Leadership Conference,
and Charlayne Hunter-Gault, the first black woman at the University
of Georgia and now a public television news correspondent.
   ``We have lost some of our finest leaders, but we are still very
involved in that same movement for liberation,'' said Lewis during
his address. ``Our struggle is not for one day, or one week, or one
year, but for a lifetime if that's what it takes.''
   Lewis was jailed 40 times and severely beaten during the 1960s
for leading peaceful marches and demonstrations throughout the
South.
   He said people often ask him if the civil rignts movement is
dead and he always says no.
   ``The nature and the character of the movement has changed, but
these changes are merely part of a natural process and do not spell
doom for our hopes,'' Lewis said.
   Lewis said the American people must elect leaders with the
``moral capacity'' of the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. if civil
rights are to improve with time.
   ``There are going to be some setbacks,'' he said. ``But we are
going to move toward the beloved community; we are going to make it
as a people and as a nation.''
</TEXT>
