<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-LastEmperor     09-10 0385</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Last Emperor,0395</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Last Emperor' Premieres In China</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLENE L. FU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``The Last Emperor'' officially premiered in
Beijing Saturday with little fanfare and less than a full house,
drawing few luminaries and only scattered applause.
   Originally set for Sept. 27, the official premiere of the
acclaimed film about the life of China's last emperor, Henry Pu Yi,
was moved up at the last minute.
   Associate producer Franco Giovale, who is in Beijing working on
another movie, was the only representative from the West who
attended. He said he was informed of the Saturday afternoon
screening only three days in advance.
   Director Bernardo Bertolucci was in his hometown of Parma,
Italy, and unable to make the trip on short notice, Giovale said.
   Also missing was China's Vice Minister of Culture Ying Ruochen,
an actor who played the prison warden, and leading members of the
government and culturual circles.
   The official Xinhua News Agency said the premiere was moved up
at the request of Chinese cinema managers anxious to show the
Italian-Chinese co-production that has won international acclaim.
   Selected theaters in Beijing and Shanghai have had special
screenings that have drawn large crowds of Chinese eager to see why
the film won nine Oscars and to compare it with a Chinese TV series
of the same name.
   However, the audience at the premier filled only three-quarters
of the cinema in Beijing's Nationalities Palace, and one woman said
she came only because a friend had given her the free ticket.
   Although the audience reacted with laughter at the antics of the
baby emperor and cheered during the scenes of zealous Red Guards
marching through the streets during the Cultural Revolution, there
was only brief and scattered applause when the credits rolled.
   Some have criticized the movie, which was shot in China, as
being inaccurate, and others say it represents a foreigner's view
of China.
   ``It's likely that some Chinese audiences will be unhappy with
that,'' said Chen Haosu, Vice Minister of Radio, Film and
Television, the highest government official who attended the
premiere.
   ``But why should we ask the foreign director to make films the
same as we are used to seeing?'' he asked in his remarks at the
movie's premiere.
   Chen said the film helped introduce China to millions.
</TEXT>
