<FILEID>AP-NR-09-10-88 2146EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-PassengersPay     09-10 0260</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Passengers Pay,0268</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Passengers Foot Fuel Bill For 737</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of idled airline passengers used the power
of the pocketbook to avert a long layover on a Portugese island,
paying to refuel a Boeing 737 after an airport refused the pilot's
credit card, British Airways said Saturday.
   The airline said the pilot of the London-bound flight raised
$2,000 from among the 100 passengers after the Porto Santo airport
refused to accept the standard credit card used by pilots for
refueling costs.
   One passenger even kicked in $1,000, said an airline spokesman,
speaking on condition of anonymity. The airline reimbursed the
passengers on the Sept. 3 flight when they arrived at London's
Gatwick Airport, he said.
   The snafu occurred during what should have been a routine
refueling stop on the island in the north Atlantic Ocean, the
spokesman said.
   The flight originated on the island of Funchal, which like Porto
Santo, is in the Madeira island group.
   British Airways initially had planned to use a Gibralta Airways
aircraft for the flight, but because of a scheduling change used a
chartered Caledonian Airways aircraft.
   When the flight landed at Porto Santo to refuel, the ground
staff refused to accept the credit card because the aircraft was
not the one the airport had been expecting, the spokesman said.
   He said the fuel collection was a ``bit unorthodox, but it was
done to save time. It is the first time I have heard of such a
situation occurring.''
   He said British Airways has filed a complaint with the airport.
</TEXT>
