<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ForestFiresRdp 3rdLd-Writethru a0627 09-10 0811</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Forest Fires Rdp, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0627,0827</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yellowstone Firefighters Brace For Long Day On The Lines</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE with new information on rain.
Picks up 8th graf, `All roads...'.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos XYS1, CKCX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEN IWANSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YELLOWSTONE NATIONAL PARK, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain fell on Old Faithful
on Saturday, as thousands of firefighters faced high wind that
fanned already enormous forest fires, and Cabinet-level officials
inspected damage to the oldest national park.
   A nearby mining town was evacuated and nonessential people were
sent out of park headquarters.
   A storm with winds up to 30 mph and gusts of up to 40 mph
measured near Mammoth moved south and east through Wyoming Saturday
afternoon.
   But in most areas of Yellowstone, ``things didn't get quite as
intense as they thought probably they would,'' said Linda Miller, a
spokeswoman at park headquarters at Mammoth Hot Springs.
   About a quarter inch of rain fell in the Lake Yellowstone area,
while scattered showers hit most of the southern half of the park.
Fire information officials said puddles gathered in the roads and
the rain quieted fire activity by increasing humidity in the area.
   All roads and entrances were closed to visitors Saturday, and
reporters had to travel in convoys escorted by park personnel.
``We're making sure people don't get into situations they can't get
out of,'' said Yellowstone spokeswoman Marty Tobias.
   Interior Secretary Donald Hodel, Agriculture Secretary Richard
Lyng and Deputy Defense Secretary William Howard Taft IV arrived at
West Yellowstone, Mont., where they were briefed in private by fire
and weather officials before going to Old Faithful geyser and
flying over the park.
   ``I didn't think I'd ever see anything quite like Mount St.
Helens, but I did here,'' Lyng said.
   Fires have charred more than 906,000 acres of the
2.2-million-acre park. Adding destruction in the national forests
and parks surrounding the park in Idaho, Montana and Wyoming pushes
the figure to over 1.2 million burned acres.
   Fires also burned in Alaska, California, Colorado, Utah and
Washington.
   So far this year, Western fires have burned nearly 3.8 million
acres, an area larger than Connecticut, in what officials call the
worst fire season in 30 years. That includes some 2 million acres
in Alaska.
   The 229,400-acre North Fork fire had burned to within a mile of
Mammoth Hot Springs and was slowly bearing down on the area, fire
managers said. Nearly 400 firefighters were on hand to protect
buildings.
   The Mammoth Hot Springs Inn, the last of the lodging facilities
available in Yellowstone, was closed Friday. It had been scheduled
to stay open for the season until Sept. 19.
   The 650 residents of Gardiner, Mont., which is at the north
entrance to Yellowstone and five miles north of Mammoth Hot
Springs, stood ready to evacuate.
   Jardine, Mont., a mining community of 100 to 150 people four
miles from Gardiner, was evacuated Saturday because its only escape
route was through a canyon to Gardiner, said Betty Schmitt of
Gallatin National Forest in Montana.
   A review of National Park Service policy on fighting wildfires
will likely lead to changes after this year's devastating fires in
the West, Hodel said.
   ``In light of what has happened, we recognize you simply fight
every fire as hard as you can from the beginning,'' Hodel said to
cheers from townspeople in the audience at a news conference in
West Yellowstone, Mont.
   ``I think they'd have to'' change, Hodel said of the Park
Service's so-called ``let burn'' policy in which natural fires are
allowed to burn except where they threaten lives or property.
   In Washington state, the bodies of two men were recovered
Saturday from the burned wreckage of a helicopter that disappeared
Friday while fighting that state's largest forest fire, a
46,000-acre blaze, said Forest Service spokesman Greg Thayer. The
craft was found near a ridgetop north of Wenatchee, and recovery
teams had to ride helicopters to the top of the ridge and hike down.
   Chelan County Sheriff Joe Collins said the HU-204 ``Huey''
helicopter apparently snagged its empty water bucket on some trees
and crashed. Collins said the victims were believed to be Canadians.
   Last month, one person died in the crash of a helicopter
involved in battling a blaze in Wyoming's Bighorn National Forest.
   The first death directly attributable to fires this year
occurred last week in Glacier National Park in Montana, when a
firefighter was struck by a falling, burning tree.
   In northeastern Utah, residents who were driven from 50 homes in
the tiny community of Whiterocks were allowed to return home
Saturday. A fire in the Ashley National Forest had knocked down
power lines to the community, and the residents were without power.
   Four mobile homes were destroyed by the fire, which surged to
within a mile of the hamlet before being checked by firefighters
and the weather.
</TEXT>
