<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MummyExam     09-10 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mummy Exam,0342</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Museum Gets 3-D Look at 2,500-Year-Old Mummy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Children's Museum sent its
2,500-year-old mummy to the hospital Saturday to learn more about
the ancient woman from Egypt.
   During her visit to Indiana University Hospital, Wenu-hotep got
her picture taken with a three-dimensional CT scan that provided a
never-before-seen view of her face.
   ``We found much finer pictures than I would have expected of the
bones. These were incredibly clear and detailed images of the
skull, the tissues, the internal bones of the skull,'' said Robert
Pickering, curator of anthropology for the museum.
   Pickering said the X-rays could be used later as the basis for
artistic renderings to show what Wenu-hotep's face looked like.
   The physical anthropologist said the scan also showed in detail
the hole used to remove Wenu-hotep's brain during the mummification
process, as well as resins and linen wrappings used to preserve the
body.
   ``We also cleared up an old problem,'' he said. ``In X-rays
taken about 1967 it appears there was a fracture of the left hip.
We were able to show pretty conclusively there was not a fracture
of the hip. In fact the hip appears to be normal.''
   Interest in Wenu-hotep has increased dramatically in the two
weeks since Frank J. Yurco, a Egyptological consultant from the
Field Museum in Chicago, performed new studies on her.
   Until then, scholars thought Wenu-hotep and her family were only
of minor importance. But Yurco discovered that she was a pivotal
mummy, meaning she provides totally new information about ancient
Egypt.
   Yurco's detailed readings of the art and hieroglyphics on the
coffin indicate Wenu-hotep's father, Hor-em-hat, was a high priest
of Thoth, the most important deity of the time.
   Yurco's study of the decoration on the coffin indicated that
Wenu-hotep lived between 525 and 400 B.C., 200 years earlier than
scholars previously thought; that she lived during a Persian rule
of Egypt; and that she was a woman of wealth and power in her own
right.
</TEXT>
