<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nicaragua     09-10 0223</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua,0232</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebel Leader Rejects Nicaraguan Proposal For New Peace Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A member of the Nicaraguan rebels'
directorate on Saturday rejected the Sandinista government's offer
of a meeting in Guatemala to resume peace talks.
   President Daniel Ortega on Friday suggested a meeting Sept.
19-20 in Guatemala to discuss reopening high-level negotiations at
a later date in Managua to end the civil war.
   Roberto Ferrey, a member of the Nicaraguan Resistance said the
rebels, known as Contras, could not accept the proposal.
   In a telephone interview from his office in Miami, Ferrey said,
``A preparatory meeting isn't necessary and peace talks would have
to be somewhere other than Managua.''
   During a June round of talks in Managua, Contra leaders said the
government restricted their freedom of movement and any further
talks would have to be in another Central American country.
   There has been a cease-fire in the 7-year-old civil war between
the U.S.-backed rebels and the Sandinista government since March
21. But high-level negotiations to deal with a permanent truce
broke down on June 9 in Managua.
   The Sandinistas have extended the cease-fire month-by-month and
the rebels have said they will abide by it. But each side has
accused the other of violations.
   Ferrey also said the Contras want opposition parties inside
Nicaragua included in future peace talks.
</TEXT>
