<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Lennon     09-10 0382</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Lennon,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yoko Ono Denounces Biography Of Lennon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yoko Ono, widow of slain Beatle composer and
guitarist John Lennon, has denounced a biography of her husband by
Albert Goldman as ``all lies,'' according to The Sunday Times of
London.
   The weekly reported it was told by Ono at her home in New York
that she contemplated suicide when she discovered what the American
writer intended to publish in his book, ``The Lives of John
Lennon.''
   ``I've been undergoing character assassination for the past 20
years,'' she was quoted as saying. ``When this whole thing started,
I kept thinking of ((Spanish painter Pablo) Picasso's wife and how
she finally killed herself. Then I realized I could never do
anything like that because I have my son Sean.''
   The newspaper reported she rejected Goldman's account that
Lennon was brain-damaged from childhood, psychopathic, vindictive,
cruel, homosexual and used to hit her. She said he never hit her
once and if he felt like hitting anything he would punch a big
pillow with both hands.
   The newspaper report said Ono was particularly hurt by Goldman's
assertion hat her love affair with Lennon was a cynical move to
promote record sales.
   It quoted her as saying Lennon was told as late as 1980 he could
sell more records if he pretended not to be attached to one woman,
but he refused.
   ``Neither of us was an angel. But we cherished and loved each
moment we were together, and were always frightened of losing each
other,'' Ono was quoted as saying.
   The Sunday Times said she believes a new film titled ``Imagine:
John Lennon,'' scheduled to be shown next month, ``is her best
defense against Goldman'' as it was compiled from footage of their
life together after the Beatles musical group broke up in 1970.
   Philip Norman, who wrote ``Shout. The True Story of the
Beatles,'' interviewed Ono and her son for The Sunday Times. He
called Goldman's book ``700 brutishly ill-written, ill-researched,
pretentious but soggily ignorant pages.''
   Lennon was shot to death Dec. 8, 1980, in the courtyard of his
New York City apartment building by Mark David Chapman, a former
Beatles' fan who was convicted of the killing and sentenced to
prison for a term of 20 years to life.
</TEXT>
