<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Non-Aligned 1stLd-Writethru a0618 09-10 0475</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Non-Aligned, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0618,0482</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Foreign Ministers Attack South Africa And Israel, Back Palestinian
Uprising</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with one graf to UPDATE with meeting adjourning; picks
up 2nd graf pvs `In their...'; ADDS one graf with Yugoslavia chosen
to host and chair movement</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALEX EFTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign ministers of the 101-nation
non-aligned movement closed a four-day meeting early Sunday after
adopting resolutions condemning Israel and South Africa.
   In their political report, the ministers said there was
``increased cooperation between Israel and South Africa,'' and
expressed ``indignation and dismay that certain Western nations ..
. continued to aid and abet apartheid economically, financially,
politically, diplomatically and militarily.''
   They noted ``with regret'' that, despite efforts to press
leading industrialized countries to impose mandatory economic
sanctions against white-ruled South Africa, the U.N. Security
Council had again been prevented from adopting sanctions by
American and British vetoes.
   The document expressed disappointment that Japan increased its
trade with South Africa, whose apartheid policies establish a
racially segregated society in which the 5 million whites control
the country and the 26 million blacks have no vote in national
affairs.
   It called on member states ``to begin in earnest the stockpiling
of relief materials for appropriate use in support of the
front-line and other states in southern Africa, to assist them to
withstand reprisals by South Africa.''
   South Africa has been accused of launching raids in neighboring
black countries to strike at the African National Congress, the
main guerrilla group fighting the white-led government.
   The final document ``strongly condemned the hypocrisy of the
U.S. administration and the Pretoria racist regime for talking
peace'' in Namibia while continuing to provide military support to
the UNITA rebels fighting the Marxist government in Angola.
   With regard to the Palestinian attempts to establish a homeland
in the West Bank and Gaza Strip, the report said, ``The ministers
saluted the heroic uprising of the Palestinian people in the
(Israeli) occupied territories.''
   It said the uprising was ``tangible evidence of their
determination to have a state of their own, which proves the
futility of the Israeli efforts to continue the occupation of
Palestine.''
   The final report also said a Middle East settlement should be
based ``on the right of the Palestinian people to
self-determination and their right to establish an independent and
sovereign Palestinian state in their national homeland, Palestine.''
   The report called on both Iraq and Iran to cooperate in good
faith with the U.N. secretary-general for full implementation of
the UN-sponsored cease-fire in the Persian Gulf war, which went
into effect on Aug. 20.
   The non-aligned movement was formed in 1961 by nations claiming
not to be aligned with the East or West.
   Before adjourning, the foreign ministers decided early Sunday
that Yugoslavia will host next year's summit meeting and have the
chairmanship for the next three years.
</TEXT>
