<FILEID>AP-NR-09-10-88 2352EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Iraq-Kurds     09-10 0482</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iraq-Kurds,0499</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraq Protests U.S. Stand on Alleged Use of Chemical Weapons
Against Kurds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Iraqi foreign minister said Saturday
that a U.S. Senate call for economic sanctions against his country
for allegedly using chemical weapons against Kurdish rebels was
ridiculous and unacceptable.
   Kurdish separatists praised the Senate action, which they said
came amid continued heavy fighting in Iraq's mountainous north.
   Minister of Information Latif Nassayif Jassim denied all reports
accusing Iraq of using chemical weapons against the rebellious
Kurds, the official Iraqi News Agency reported.
   INA quoted Jassem as saying, ``All the allegations aired by
certain political and media circles are ridiculous.''
   He called the Senate vote unacceptable and said America cannot
speak out about human rights while it is arming Israel's forces for
their attacks against Palestinians, according to the agency.
   Iraq's latest offensive against Kurdish separatists began soon
after a U.N.-mediated cease-fire was accepted Aug. 20 by Iran and
Iraq in their 8-year-old war. Many Kurdish separatists had backed
Iran in the conflict.
   The U.S. Senate voted Friday to condemn Iraq's alleged poison
gas attacks on its Kurdish minority and to impose stiff economic
sanctions aimed at throttling Iraq's ability to pay off its
estimated $60-billion debt.
   The measure, following the State Department's announcement that
it had proof of the attacks, still must be approved by the House of
Representatives and signed by President Reagan.
   A spokesman for the Kurdish rebels said the Senate action proved
the separatists' accusations about chemical weapons.
   ``The U.S has its own evidence through its own sources which
proves what we've been saying for a month,'' the spokesman said in
a telephone interview with The Associated Press in Cyprus. He spoke
on condition of anonymity.
   The spokesman, speaking from a European capital where he
maintains radio contact with the insurgents, said the fighting is
continuing in the northern Kurdish regions.
   He said Iraqi forces were concentrated along the border with
Turkey, where he claimed 40,000 Kurds trying to escape were trapped.
   ``We are trying to rescue as many people as we can but we
haven't had much news from them in the last few days,'' he said,
adding that there was heavy fighting Sept. 6 and 7.
   He said 80 Iraqis were killed in the fighting in the northern
Amadiyeh district Sept. 7 and most rebel fighters had withdrawn. In
Sidikan on Sept. 6, Iraq launched a ``massive attack'' and lost 200
of its soldiers in the battle, according to the spokesman.
   He said 250 guerrillas had been killed since Aug. 26. Last week
the rebels said 2,000 civilians have been killed and 5,000 wounded,
many in chemical bomb attacks.
   Chemical weeapons are banned internationally under the 1925
Geneva accords.
   Diplomats in Baghdad said that since March Iraq has demolished
scores of Kurdish villages in the north, moving the inhabitants to
blocks of concrete apartment buildings in larger cities.
</TEXT>
