<2ND_LINE>AM-Tomcat Down,210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Navy Fighter Crashed In Arabian Sea</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Navy F-14 Tomcat jet fighter crashed in the
northern Arabian Sea earlier this week but both crewmen escaped
serious injury, the Navy said Friday.
   The two-seat fighter, assigned to Squadron VF-111 at the Miramar
Naval Air Station, Calif., was flying off the carrier USS Carl
Vinson on a ``routine training flight'' when it was forced to ditch
at sea Thursday night, the Navy said.
   The Navy added the cause of the crash was now under
investigation, but one Pentagon official who asked not to be named
said the plane had suffered ``a mechanical problem.''
   The Navy said the pilot ditched the Tomcat about 40 miles from
the carrier and that both the pilot and his weapon's officer were
subsequently rescued by a helicopter from the Vinson.
   One of the two suffered minor injuries while bailing out, the
Navy said, adding it did not have the identities of the crewmen
available.
   The Vinson recently began patroling in the northern Arabian Sea
to support other Navy warships assigned to escort duties in the
Persian Gulf. The United States is maintaining a large naval
presence in the Gulf while it waits to see if the cease-fire
between Iran and Iraq will hold.
</TEXT>
