<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--BigTurtle     09-10 0157</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Big Turtle,0160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Maine Man Bags World Record Snapping Turtle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A world-record snapping turtle, recently captured
by a Maine man, will be exhibited this winter at the Bronx Zoo
before being returned to the wild, the Massachusetts Division of
Fisheries and Wildlife said Friday.
   John Rogers caught the turtle, which weighed in at 67 pounds and
has a shell length of 19.8 inches, in an undisclosed area in
northern Middlesex County. With its head and neck and foot-long
tail measured, it was well over three feet in length.
   The former world-record turtle, caught by a fisherman in
Minnesota in 1986, weighed 65\ pounds and had a shell length of
19.2 inches.
   Snapping turtles are among the most common reptiles in
Massachusetts, spending most of their time in the water.
   They feed primarily on vegetation, fish and carrion, and
occasionally catch waterfowl from the surface. Unless provoked, the
turtles pose no danger to people.
</TEXT>
