<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Times-Cost,0139</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New York Times Raises Newsstand Price By A Nickel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For the first time in six years, The New York
Times is raising the price of its weekday issues.
   The price is going up Sept. 19 to 35 cents on newsstands within
75 miles of the city and on all of Long Island.
   The increase was made necessary by cost increases, including a
21.5 percent rise in the cost of newsprint over the past two years,
according to Lance R. Primis, president of the newspaper.
   The Sunday edition still will cost $1.25 on newsstands within
the 75-mile area and the cost of home delivery from the Times
direct delivery service will remain the same.
   The nickel increase is the Times' first for the weekday editions
since March 1, 1982.
