<FILEID>AP-NR-09-10-88 0617EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-GulfTalks     09-10 0371</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Talks,0380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraq Accuses Iran of Wasting Time at Peace Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY CZUCZKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq on Friday accused Iran of wasting time in
negotiations for a settlement of their 8-year-old war, and the U.N.
mediator was reported ready to call a recess.
   A written Iraqi statement dismissed Iran's position as ``fantasy
to explain its flight from direct talks lately as a result of the
instability of the government it represents.''
   The Iraqi statement said negotiations cannot move past basic
cease-fire arrangements without action on two of the Baghdad
government's demands: free navigation in the Persian Gulf and
U.N.-supervised clearing of the Shatt-al-Arab waterway, which forms
the southern frontier.
   The waterway, Iraq's only outlet to the gulf, has been blocked
by sunken ships and silt since the early weeks of the war, which
began in September 1980.
   On Thursday, Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati repeated the
Iranian position that those issues were ``extraneous elements'' and
could be addressed later.
   Velayati said negotiations have been hung up the agenda
disagreement since they began Aug. 25, five days after a cease-fire
took effect. He said Iran's priority is withdrawal of military
forces to internationally recognized boundaries.
   Iraq said Iran was giving a false picture and that Baghdad had
stated its position in two letters to U.N. Secretary-General Javier
Perez de Cuellar before the talks began, ``so the raising of these
two issues is neither extraneous nor new.''
   The statement said Iran was procrastinating and Velayati should
``get down to business.''
   Direct talks occurred only on the first two days in Geneva and
neither Velayati nor the Iraqi foreign minister, Tariq Aziz, has
met with U.N. mediator Jan Eliasson since last Saturday. Perez de
Cuellar was mediator when the talks began, but put Eliasson in
charge Sept. 1.
   Signs increased Friday that the talks will recess and resume
later this month in New York.
   U.N. spokeswoman Therese Gastaut said continuing low-level,
indirect contacts were focusing on ``how to proceed'' and Eliasson,
a Swedish diplomat, probably would hold a news conference Saturday
or Sunday.
   Sources close to the talks said privately he was expected to
announce a recess but there still was disagreement over a date for
resumption.
</TEXT>
