<1ST_LINE>r a AM-StarvationSentence     09-10 0312</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Starvation Sentence,0319</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Ordered By Judge To Avoid Pregnancy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who admitted allowing her
3-month-old child to die of starvation was ordered Friday by a
judge not to become pregnant during her five-year probation.
   Stella Belona, 23, pleaded guilty in June to manslaughter with
the understanding that she would not be sentenced to more than 10
years in prison. According to probation terms set down by State
District Judge Mike McDonald, Belona must not become pregannt while
under court supervision.
   According to a police report, Arell Belona died Nov. 30, 1987,
from malnutrition so severe that he ``appeared mummified.'' The
infant had not been fed in three days, investigators said.
   ``This is a welfare mother who had no resources,'' defense
attorney Kathleen Richey said. ``What welfare meant to her was if
she could get a ride, then she could get food stamps.''
   Belona told police she had wanted to take the child to a doctor,
but had no transportation. Authorities said the child's weight had
dropped from about 7 pounds at birth to less than 6 pounds at death.
   McDonald said Belona was pregnant when she dropped out of school
in the seventh grade at age 16.
   In addition to a requirement that she not become pregnant,
Belona was ordered to live at a rehabilitation residence, learn to
read, obtain a high school equivalency certificate and undergo job
training.
   Belona's three other children _ ages 3, 2 and 1 _ appeared not
to suffer abuse, authorities said. They have been turned over to
child protection officers.
   A judge in Arizona last week reversed her order that a teen-age
mother, who left her two sons alone in a sweltering apartment for
three days, practice birth control throughout her child-bearing
years. The judge said her order was unenforceable since no method
of birth control is fool-proof.
</TEXT>
