<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Controller Probe,0146</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Miami Chief Controller Probed For Hitching Rides</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chief air traffic controller in Miami has been
pulled off his job because he allegedly hitched too many free rides
on commercial airliners, a federal official said.
   William Abernathy is being investigated for possible abuse of
the ``flight familiarization'' program, which allows controllers to
ride in cockpits to observe flight procedures.
   Abernathy, who oversees 300 controllers, has been temporarily
replaced during the investigation, Roger Myers, spokesman for the
Federal Aviation Administration, said Thursday.
   Under the flight familiarization program, controllers are
limited to eight free rides a year, and only one can be
international.
   Abernathy, who has worked for the FAA for 24 years and has
headed the Miami office since January 1985, could have his flight
privileges suspended for two years if the abuse is proved, Myers
said.
