<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BleachersCollapse 1stLd-Writethru a0747 09-10 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bleachers Collapse, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0747,0383</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>High School Bleachers Collapse; More Than 70 Students Injured</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `Ms. Dent-Brown...', to include height and
seating capacity of bleachers; SUBS 10th graf, `Nine other...', to
CORRECT number of hospitalized by deleting nine.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>POMFRET, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bleachers in a high school gymnasium
collapsed Friday during a junior assembly, injuring at least 78
people and creating ``major chaos,'' authorities reported. None of
the injuries was described as serious.
   The entire junior class, about 300 students, was attending the
assembly at Maurice J. McDonough High School when the steel
bleachers gave way shortly after 8 a.m., said Linda Dent-Brown,
administrative assistant for the Charles County Board of Education.
   Ms. Dent-Brown said she didn't know how many students were on
the bleacher that collapsed. The 16-foot bleachers had a seating
capacity of 175.
   Charles County Fire Chief Ken Chaplin said it appeared a section
of the bleachers came apart.
   ``When we got here, it was basically major chaos,'' Chaplin
said. ``We had students, teachers in the bleachers trying to
comfort one another. A lot of victims, a lot of pain and agony
going on. A few of the students were actually still in the
bleachers themselves.''
   The incident was under investigation, officials said.
   ``It sounded like fireworks or a shotgun. It sounded like a
whole bunch of shots were going on. It was scary,'' one student
told WUSA-TV in Washington. ``It was like you saw them (the
bleachers) and then you didn't see them. ... They went one at a
time, but real fast. It was like dominoes.''
   Thirteen people were admitted to hospitals, including four who
were flown by helicopter to Prince George's Hospital Center in
Cheverly. They were in satisfactory condition Friday afternoon,
hospital spokeswoman Rosie Cobb said.
   At least 65 persons were treated and released. None of those
admitted was in serious or critical condition, hospital spokeswomen
said.
   In addition, a team of doctors and nurses from Physicians
Memorial Hospital in La Plata went to the school to treat an
unknown number of students with very minor injuries, said
spokeswoman Mary S. Haag.
   Classes at McDonough High, which has an enrollment of about
1,300, began Sept. 1. Pomfret is about 80 miles south of Baltimore.
</TEXT>
