<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Japan-USSales     09-10 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-US Sales,0324</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Commerce Secretary Opens Campaign To Sell U.S. Products In Japan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY THORSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Commerce Secretary C. William Verity opened a
campaign Friday to sell the Japanese American goods ranging from
speedboats to cat food.
   The drive has the approval of the Japanese government and the
powerful Keidanren, or Federation of Economic Organizations. The
Keidanren presented a lunch that included California orange juice,
Montana beef and Budweiser beer to show the growing acceptance of
American imports.
   Verity brought executives of 25 U.S. companies to Tokyo to study
the Japanese market and meet government officials.
   ``Now is the time to come and do business in Japan,'' Hajime
Tamura, minister of international trade and industry, said in
welcoming the group.
   In a speech to some 70 Japanese executives at Keidanren
headquarters, Verity said many trade disputes between Japan and the
United States have been resolved in the past year. Washington wants
to reduce Japan's huge trade surplus with the United States by
selling more in Japan rather than by restricting Japanese imports
to America, he said.
   ``Our firms are now very price competitive'' because of the
dollar's fall since 1985, and Japan is removing trade barriers,
Verity told the businessmen.
   He said the next thing required is ``an intensive effort by U.S.
firms to learn about and then develop imaginative and sound ways to
penetrate the Japanese distribution system in order to reach the
consumer.''
   Verity and Tamura call the campaign ``Market Japan _ with
America's best.'' They agreed in Washington in June to focus their
first effort on five areas of consumer products: Leisure goods,
sporting goods, jewelry, furniture and processed foods including
juices and pet food.
   Companies on the trade mission include Ralston-Purina of St.
Louis; Harry Winston of New York; Ladd Furniture of High Point,
N.C.; Cigarette Racing Team of Miami, and Woodstream Corp. of
Lititz, Pa.
</TEXT>
