<FILEID>AP-NR-09-10-88 0052EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LILCO-Shoreham     09-10 0396</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-LILCO-Shoreham,0407</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Utility's Nuclear Plant Gets Evacuation OK</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HICKSVILLE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Shoreham nuclear plant, which
earlier this year seemed destined for mothballs, received a high
rating for the work of Long Island Lighting Co. workers in an
emergency evacuation drill, a federal report showed.
   The positive report from the Federal Emergency Management Agency
came despite the refusal of state and Long Island officials to
cooperate because they claimed evacuation of the island was
impossible in the event of a real accident.
   ``The Shoreham monster is rising from its grave,'' said Richard
Kessel, the executive director of the state consumer protection
board and a long-time Shoreham opponent, after the FEMA rating was
issued.
   The two-day drill, which began June 7, tested how LILCO
responded to a simulated plant accident that required mock
evacuation of residents living within 10 miles of the plant.
   State and local officials said in June that LILCO showed it was
incapable of protecting the public because a majority of emergency
sirens in the evacuation zone failed or were not heard during the
drill.
   But FEMA officials said at the time that sounding the sirens was
not a required part of the exercise.
   Under current federal regulation, the Nuclear Regulatory
Commission may not license a nuclear plant until there is an
emergency plan that gives reasonable assurance the public will be
safe if an accident occurs.
   LILCO spokesman James Lois said FEMA told the NRC in its report
Friday that the utility proved in the drill that its plan did
provide reasonable assurance.
   According to Lois, FEMA's evaluation of the June exercise and
the emergency plan itself support a finding of reasonable assurance
that the health and the safety of the public will be carried out.
   If the plan is acceptable to the NRC licensing board, it removes
emergency planning as an obstacle to issuance of a full power
operating license for a plant, Lois said.
   Kessel, saying he was extremely disappointed in the FEMA
decision, charged the federal agency ``turned logic upside down''
in its ruling.
   Earlier this year, Gov. Mario Cuomo _ another Shoreham opponent
_ helped work out a deal to purchase the nuclear plant from LILCO
and shut it down for good. But the plan has yet to be approved by
the Legislature, meaning that it still is possible for Shoreham to
one day go into operation.
  
</TEXT>
