<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf-Prisoners,0180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Names 703 Soldiers It Says Iraq Has Captured</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran says Iraq has captured 703 Iranian
officers and soldiers since both countries began observing a
cease-fire on Aug. 20, according to documents released Friday.
   ``The capture of these people by Iraq is in contravention of the
agreement on the cease-fire, and they should therefore not be
considered as prisoners of war,'' Mahmoud Sadat Madarshahi, charge
d'affaires at Iran's U.N. Mission, said in a letter to
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar.
   ``It is hoped that the United Nations will take all the
appropriate and necessary measures to ensure the safe and speedy
return of these people.''
   The letter accompanied a list of the names of the missing men,
ranging in rank from private to colonel.
   Each side has accused the other of numerous violations of the
truce in their 8-year-old war. The belligerents have engaged in
peace talks in Geneva since Aug. 25.
   U.N. officials have said they will not comment on specific
claims of violations by the combatants.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
