<FILEID>AP-NR-09-10-88 0100EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MafiaViolence     09-10 0256</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mafia Violence,0263</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Organized Crime Strike Force Head Predicts Mafia War</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NANTUCKET, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Underworld violence in the Boston area
may rise sharply in coming months and some defense attorneys may be
conspiring with mobsters to murder government informants, a
prosecutor says.
   Jeremiah T. O'Sullivan, chief attorney of the U.S. Justice
Department's New England Organized Crime Strike Force, suggested in
a speech to Massachusetts prosecutors Thursday that one reputed
Mafia leader is marked for death by his associates.
   Discussing the difficulties faced by federal authorities trying
to build cases against Mafia leaders who took over after the 1986
convictions of underboss Gennaro J. Angiulo and his associates,
O'Sullivan said:
   ``Any time we execute a warrant, the paperwork goes to a corps
of lawyers who attempt to identify informants so they can be
murdered.''
   O'Sullivan made the comments to a conference of the
Massachusetts District Attorneys Association.
   He said federal investigators know of ``an active attempt by
some unscrupulous members of the defense bar'' to assist the mob.
He did not name individual attorneys.
   O'Sullivan described Vincent M. Ferrara, whom the FBI publicly
identified in April as one of seven Mafia leaders in Boston, as a
``psychopathic killer'' who had angered his associates so that some
want to kill him.
   Ferrara's lawyer, Anthony M. Cardinale, said O'Sullivan had
engaged in ``prosecutorial conduct of the worst kind.''
   ``He is attempting not only to poison the minds of the grand
jury, he is making a mockery of the entire grand jury system,''
Cardinale told the Boston Globe.
</TEXT>
