<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ForestFires-Pollution     09-10 0162</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Forest Fires-Pollution,0165</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Forest Fires Cause Air Pollution Warning in Nebraska</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Smoke drifting into the Nebraska Panhandle
from forest fires in Wyoming and Montana caused state environmental
officers to place the western half of Nebraska under an air
pollution warning Friday.
   The alert was prompted by high pollutant concentrations downwind
from the fires. It will remain in effect until the smoke clears,
said Dennis Grams, director of the Nebraska Department of
Environmental Control.
   People with respiratory ailments, young children and elderly
persons should curtail exposure and outdoor activities until
conditions visibily improve, he said.
   Exceptionally high levels of smoke particles were measured
Friday in Sheridan, Wyo. Higher concentrations were expected to
develop to the south, he said.
   Visibility was reduced to 4 miles at the Alliance Airport on
Thursday, the National Weather Service said. A thin veil of smoke
remained across most of the state Friday with visibility again in
the 5-mile range at some weather stations.
</TEXT>
