<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Dhellemmes,0121</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Father of Pygmies' Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YAOUNDE, Cameroon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ignace Dhellemmes, the French
missionary known as the ``father of the pygmies,'' died in
Sangmelima in southern Cameroon, a French diplomatic source in
Yaounde said Friday. He was 74.
   The diplomatic source, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
the missionary died Wednesday at the bishop's residence in
Sangmelima. No cause of death was provided.
   In a 1985 autobiography, Dhellemmes described his 40 years of
work in Cameroon and Congo, where he sought to improve the health
and social welfare of pygmy tribes.
   As a young missionary, Dhellemes worked from 1948 to 1952 in a
leper colony in eastern Cameroon. He began working among pygmy
tribes in 1953.
</TEXT>
