<FILEID>AP-NR-09-10-88 0632EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DenverSymphony     09-10 0258</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Denver Symphony,0262</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fund Raising Billed As Key To DSO Season</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT C. UNRUH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Denver Symphony Orchestra, which had
threatened to file for bankruptcy, on Friday announced cutbacks and
new fund-raising designed to save the 1988-1989 season.
   It also announced the appointment of a blue-ribbon panel to
ensure its future financial viability.
   At a news conference in the lobby of Boettcher Concert Hall,
DSO's home, Symphony Board Chairman Bob Lee said that the season
could go on only if several hundred thousand dollars was raised by
Oct. 1, and the budget was cut by reducing administrative costs and
freezing orchestra members pension contributions, eliminating
clothing and instrument allowances and not filling three vacant
positions.
   ``(Bankruptcy) It's not totally out of the picture,'' said Lee.
``I hope we don't have to revisit that.''
   The orchestra already canceled its scheduled season-opener
Thursday, but could be ready for its second scheduled concert if
the money is collected, officials said.
   Mayor Federico Pena also announced that he would appoint an 8-10
person panel to study long-term solutions of symphony funding and
make recommendations that would stabilize the situation that has in
recent years become an annual problem.
   Two years ago, the musicians in the orchestra took 20 percent
cuts in wages to keep the group solvent, and spokesman Brian
Ventura said the fact they were willing to accept further delays in
resumption of full benefits indicated their commitment. This year's
problem was a difference of about $650,000 in projected expenses
and projected revenue.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
