<DOCNO> AP880910-0178 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-10-88 0106EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Sun-TimesPay     09-10 0326</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sun-Times Pay,0336</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sun Times Seeks Pay Cut From Staff</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chicago Sun-Times is asking its editorial
staff to take a 15 percent salary cut and accept reductions in
other benefits and the elimination of overtime pay, staff members
say.
   A union memo posted at the newspaper Friday presented the
management offer, which proposes a three-year contract with staff
members taking a 15 percent pay cut the first year, confirmed a
staffer who asked not to be identified.
   Editorial staffers would get a 5 percent raise the second year
of the contract and a 10 percent raise in the third, he said.
   Sun-Times Executive Editor Kenneth D. Towers refused to comment
on the memo.
   Officials at the Chicago Newspaper Guild, which represents about
280 reporters, photographers, copy editors, assistant city editors,
library staff and other workers, could not immediately be reached
for comment.
   The offer called for the elimination of overtime pay and would
throw out a 10 percent bonus for working at night.
   Instead of overtime pay, the Sun-Times proposed giving
additional time off to those who work overtime.
   The proposal would also increase the amount of time employees
work from 7{ hours a day to 8 hours a day, eliminate severence pay
and allow workers to be terminated if their jobs become obsolete
because of advances in technology.
   The newspaper and the union have been negotiating for a new
contract. The old pact expired May 31, but employees have been
working under its terms.
   The memo comes one month after Sun-Times president and publisher
Robert Page resigned, two years after spearheading a $145 million
buyout of the newspaper from Australian publisher Rupert Murdoch.
   Page resigned amid speculation of a rift between him and
Sun-Times Chairman Leonard P. Shaykin about the newspaper's
financial performance.
   The Sun-Times was founded in 1948 by the Field family of
Chicago, which owned the newspaper until 1984 when it was sold to
Murdoch for $90 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
