<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-USBlacks     09-10 0276</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-US Blacks,0284</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Florida Church Group Claims Harassment by Israeli Troops</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of blacks from a church in Florida
claimed Israeli troops harassed them Friday and denied them entry
to visit holy places in the occupied West Bank of the Jordan River.
   The Rev. S. D. James said the Israeli officials at the Allenby
Bridge accused people in his 31-member group from James' church in
Opa-locka, Fla., of having false passports.
   The Allenby Bridge is a major crossing point over the Jordan
River between Jordan, where James' group is staying, and the
Israeli-occupied West Bank.
   ``They claimed that some members of the group had forged
passports,'' James said. ``Soldiers accused all of us of being
members of a Black Israelite group and they said that we needed a
special visa to get in.''
   Israel has had a long dispute with the predominantly American
Black Israelite organization that claims its members are Jewish and
have the right to settle in the Jewish state.
   James said Israeli soldiers pushed members of his group, forced
them back into their bus and would not let them through the bridge
checkpoint.
   He said a similar incident occurred last year when Israeli
authorities denied members of his church access to the West Bank.
   Israel captured the West Bank from Jordan in the 1967 Middle
East War.
   James said he had registered a complaint with the U.S. Embassy
in Amman, the capital of Jordan, and his group would try again
Wednesday to enter the West Bank.
   He said all the members in the group were from his church in
Opa-locka, a community 12 miles north of Miami.
</TEXT>
