<2ND_LINE>AM-Daughter Killed,0213</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Slayer In Hurry To Hit Death Row</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man convicted of stabbing his daughter to
death has asked a judge to formally sentence him as soon as
possible so he can be put in a cellblock where televisions are
allowed.
   ``Please bring me in and sentence me,'' Gary Starr said in a
letter filed with Allegheny County Judge Jeffrey Manning's office
Friday. ``I thought the jury already sentenced me to death.''
   A jury on Aug. 23 sentenced Starr to die for the Feb. 19 murder
of Wanda Starr, 20, of Moon Township. The stabbing occurred after
Starr, a former apartment complex manager, confronted his daughter
about stolen rent money.
   During his trial, Starr admitted having had a 6-year incestuous
relationship with the woman.
   Starr requested the quick action because it will put him in a
section of the State Correctional Institution at Pittsburgh where
televisions are permitted, according to Thomas Seiverling, a prison
spokesman.
   Starr now is housed in the prison's diagnostic and
classification center, where televisions are prohibited, Seiverling
said.
   Sixteen years ago, Starr was convicted of shooting his wife,
Linda, to death as she slept in their Beaver County home. He served
8{ years in prison for that crime.
</TEXT>
