<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-FishWedding     09-10 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Fish Wedding,0291</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Congressman Weds Housekeeper In Englewood Ceremony</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ENGLEWOOD, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former New York Rep Hamilton Fish Sr.,
99, the oldest living former member of Congress, married his
live-in housekeeper Friday during ceremonies at a friend's house
here.
   Fish, who represented the mid-Hudson region from 1920 to 1945
and whose son, Hamilton Fish Jr., currently holds that 21st
Congressional District seat, wed Lydia Ambrogia, a former editor of
a weekly newspaper in the New Windsor area.
   It was the fourth marriage for the elder Fish. His third
marriage, to Alice Curtis Desmond, ended in divorce.
   The ceremony was held at the Englewood home of Fish's longtime
friend, Temple Hoyen Buell, who celebrated his 93rd birthday Friday.
   The bride, 56, is a grandmother of 10 and has children ranging
in age from 29 to 34. It is her third marriage.
   ``I'm getting married because I'm fortunate enough to meet a
very beautiful woman,'' Fish said. ``And I'm just lucky she'd marry
me at my age.
   ``I would go as far as saying that I feel _ and I'm not a deeply
religious fellow _ she's an angel from God,'' Fish said. ``She's
done more for me in the last three years to keep me alive and I
hope she can keep me alive for three or four more so I can spread
my message about the disarmament of nuclear arms.''
   Said the bride: ``He wants to talk about nuclear arms _ I say he
ought to talk about my arms.''
   Fish and his son both are Republicans; his grandson, Hamilton
Fish III, former publisher of The Nation magazine, currently is
running for Congress from the 20th Congressional District as a
Democrat.
</TEXT>
