<NOTE>For Release Wed PMs, Sept. 14, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Former President Mounts Campaign Against Debilitating Disease</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note graphic nature of contents.
^By CAROLYN S. CARLSON</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Jimmy Carter is rallying other
nations' heads of state and health officials to eradicate a
debilitating disease that infects 10 million people and disrupts
agriculture in the Third World.
   Carter has also persuaded the World Health Organization to
target guinea worm disease, which sometimes has fatal
complications, as the second disease _ after smallpox _ that the
agency seeks to wipe out worldwide.
   He became concerned about the readily preventable disease
through a famine relief program sponsored by Global 2000, a public
health foundation headquartered at the Carter Presidential Center
in Atlanta.
   The program, whose primary goal is to improve yield for farmers'
crops, found that agriculture in many remote areas was hampered
because the cyclical worm disease strikes so many people in the
spring, sickening them at planting season.
   The disease itself is sickening to describe. In spring, infected
people find the worm _ a yard-long, stringlike creature _ painfully
emerging from boils that form in soft tissue between the toes or
elsewhere on the body, having completed its growth cycle inside its
human host. It enters the body through contaminated water.
   Seeing the ailment's devastation is ``heartrending,'' Carter
said in a telephone interview from his home in Plains. ``And just
to realize that, with a simple education program and very simple
prevention techiques, this affliction could be eliminated forever.''
   Last spring, he and his wife, Rosalynn, visited heavily infected
villages in the West African nation of Ghana. ``The first village
we went to had a population of 500 and they had 213 people
stretched out on the ground under the kasha trees for us just to
see and to meet,'' Carter said.
   ``When we talked to the village elders and chiefs, they didn't
have any idea what caused guinea worm. They thought it might come
from the praying mantis or from drinking the blood of goats or from
some superstition like the confluence of the planets or that it was
a punishment of the gods to test their endurance,'' he said.
   ``They didn't have any idea it came from drinking filthy water.
Then we went down to look at the water hole that was their only
source of drinking water. It was covered with scum and the people
had to wade out I'd say at least knee deep before they could get a
bucket full of water,'' he said.
   Some of the waders were infected and entered the water to ease
their pain.
   When the emerging guinea worm comes in contact with water, it
spews out its larvae which are then eaten by a microscopic animal
called a cyclops.
   Villagers drink the water contaminated with cyclops and the
cyclops die in their bodies, leaving behind the larvae to grow into
worms. Infections caused when the worm dies inside the body can be
fatal, though that is rare, Carter said.
   In the first worm eradication program undertaken by Global 2000,
in Pakistan, foundation workers developed inexpensive techniques
for breaking the creature's 12-month life cycle.
   Carter said the infestations can be prevented by replacing water
holes with deep wells, ``but that costs $700 or $800 and we don't
have $700 or $800 for every village in Africa.''
   Other preventive measures include keeping people out of the
water holes or having all villagers strain their water for a full
year. But widespread illiteracy makes it difficult to educate the
people at risk.
   Still, with the support and participation of the Pakistani
government, Global 2000's eradication program is going so well that
Carter predicted the disease would be eliminated there by 1990.
   Full-scale programs have started in Ghana and Nigeria in the
last year and a new program is about to begin in Uganda.
   ``One of the things that I can contribute as a former president
is to go not to an assistant minister of health, who may not have
much influence or may not know anything about health to start with,
but I go directly to the king or the president or the prime
minister and ask him to bring his Cabinet members together,''
Carter said.
   The news media attention his involvement receives also helps
educate potential victims about the disease.
   ``It's a gratifying thing to see a village that was formerly
devastated five or six months a year from guinea worm to emerge
after a couple of years with no guinea worm and live a happy,
prosperous and healthy life,'' Carter said.
   ``In the process, to be frank about it, it puts America forward
as an enlightened, concerned and peace-loving nation.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed PMs, Sept. 14</NOTE>
