<HEAD>Oil Futures Prices Head Lower</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: for Saturday PMs</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Concern about the worldwide oil glut continues
to weigh heavy on the futures market.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the October contract for
delivery of West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S.
crude, fell 30 cents a 42-gallon barrel Friday to $14.18. The
contract had risen 32 cents on Thursday after falling sharply
earlier in the week.
   Contracts for refined oil products traded on the exchange also
declined.
   Wholesale unleaded gasoline for October delivery plunged 0.93
cent a gallon to 42.06 cents, after rising 0.40 cent the previous
session. Analysts attributed the decline to the end of the
traditional driving season on Labor Day.
   The October wholesale heating oil contract, which gained 0.24
cent Thursday, fell 0.90 cent to 40.97 a gallon.
   Peter Beutel, an energy analyst with Elders Futures Inc., said
prices started out firm amid speculation that the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries' price monitoring committee might
hold an emergency meeting. But with those prospects unconfirmed,
prices took a nosedive, he said.
   ``The sellers came out of the woodwork ...,'' Beutel said.
   The Saudi Arabian newspaper Al-Sharq Bali quoted unnamed
high-level Arab oil sources Friday as saying Venezuela and Algeria
called for a special meeting later this month of the
price-monitoring committee to help stem the decline in oil prices.
   But the newspaper also said a moderate member of the five-member
committee was opposed to the meeting.
   Crude prices on Tuesday and Wednesday hit their lowest point
since Oct. 29, 1986, when they reached $13.73 per barrel. The
following day the price leaped to $15.04 a barrel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880910-0202 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-10-88 0655EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f PM-EconomyRdp     09-10 0275</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wholesale Prices Climb, But Markets Unconcerned</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: for Saturday PMs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The government says wholesale prices rose 0.6 percent in August,
but the rise was a slight 0.3 percent excluding food and energy,
and traders took the report as good news on inflation.
   The Labor Department said Friday the August rise, excluding the
volatile food and energy categories, was half the increase of July.
   Another drop in oil prices also helped the inflation picture.
And gold prices plunged and bonds rose, a classic sign that
investors were less concerned about inflation.
   Gold, which investors hold as a hedge against inflation, sank
$7.25 a troy ounce to $421.25 an ounce in late U.S. trading, its
lowest point since early 1987.
   Bond prices, which are hurt by inflation fears, finished higher
after seesawing through a volatile trading session, pushing key
interest rates below 9 percent.
   The Treasury's closely watched 30-year bond rose 9-16 point, or
about $5.60 for every $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves
inversely to its price and is often an indicator of interest rate
trends, fell to 8.97 percent from 9.03 percent late Thursday.
   Meanwhile, stock prices took a zigzag path, winding up with a
modest gain in continued sluggish trading. The Dow Jones average of
30 industrials rose 5.69 to 2,068.81.
   Crude oil futures plunged on the New York Mercantile Exchange
amid rumors Saudi Arabia had vetoed proposals for a special meeting
of the OPEC pricing committee.
   On other exchanges, contracts for future delivery of precious
metals, grains, soybeans, livestock and meat all finished
moderately to sharply lower while stock-index futures advanced.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
